{"title_page": "Portia de Rossi", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian actress married to comedian ellen}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =Portia de Rossi\n| image              =PortiadeRossi Sept2012.jpg\n| caption            = Portia de Rossi in 2012\n| birth_name         = Amanda Lee Rogers\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1973|01|31}}\n| birth_place        = [[Horsham, Victoria]], Australia\n| residence          = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Australian]], \n[[United States|American]]\n| other_names        = Portia Lee James DeGeneres\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Melbourne]]\n| occupation         = Actress, model, philanthropist\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present\n\n| spouse             = \n{{marriage|Mel Metcalfe<!--- Do not link. Wikipedia has an article about a different Mel Metcalfe.---><br>|1996|1999|reason=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|[[Ellen DeGeneres]]<br>|2008}}\n}}\n\n'''Portia Lee James DeGeneres''' (born '''Amanda Lee Rogers'''; 31 January 1973), known professionally as '''Portia de Rossi''', is an Australian-American model, philanthropist, and actress. She is best known for starring as [[Nelle Porter]] on the American drama series ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' (1998\u20132002), for which she won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], as [[Lindsay F\u00fcnke|Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on the American television sitcom ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' (2003\u20132006, 2013, 2018\u20132019), and as Elizabeth North on the American [[political thriller]] series ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]'' (2014\u20132017).<ref>{{cite web|author=Samantha Highfill |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/07/23/portia-de-rossi-scandal |title=Portia de Rossi joins season 4 of 'Scandal' |website=Entertainment Weekly|date=2014-07-23 |accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/scandal-elizabeth-north-portia-de-rossi-dead-killed-1202391942/|title='Scandal' Star, Shonda Rhimes React to Major Death (SPOILERS)|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=21 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-bios/portia-de-rossi|accessdate=28 January 2009|title=Celebrity Bios: Portia de Rossi|publisher=Us Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Geelong's Portia Marries Ellen|url=http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/08/18/17323_news.html|accessdate=28 January 2009|publisher=Geelong Advertiser|date=18 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nShe also portrayed [[Olivia Lord]] on the American television drama series ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' (2007\u20132009) and Veronica Palmer on the American television sitcom ''[[Better Off Ted]]'' (2009\u20132010). De Rossi is married to comedian, actress, and television host [[Ellen DeGeneres]].\n\n==Early life==\nPortia de Rossi, born Amanda Lee Rogers in [[Horsham, Victoria|Horsham]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi|title=Australian Actress: Portia de Rossi|author=London Academy of Media and Film TV|accessdate=24 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301142048/http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi/|archivedate=1 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is the daughter of Margaret, a medical receptionist, and Barry Rogers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/91/Portia-de-Rossi.html|title=Portia de Rossi profile|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Her father died when she was nine years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTw1MoscAk4|title=Portia de Rossi on Ellen|work=Youtube|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref> She grew up in [[Grovedale, Victoria|Grovedale]], a suburb of [[Geelong]], Victoria, and modelled for print and TV commercials as a child. In 1988, at age 15, Rogers adopted the name Portia de Rossi, by which she remains best known. In 2005, she explained she had intended to reinvent herself, using the given name of [[Portia (Merchant of Venice)|Portia]], a character from [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[The Merchant of Venice]],'' and an Italian last name. She was educated at [[Geelong Grammar| Geelong Grammar School]] and the [[University of Melbourne]], where she studied law.<ref name=Advocate>{{cite web |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200735/http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |title=Portia heart & soul |last1=Kort |first1=Michele |date=29 August 2005 |website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |publisher=[[Here Media]] |access-date=19 August 2015 |archive-date=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDe Rossi's first significant role was as a young and impressionable model in the Australian [[1994 in film|1994 film]] ''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]].'' Soon afterward, she moved to Los Angeles and won guest roles on several TV shows and a permanent role in ''[[Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher]],'' before landing a part in the film ''[[Scream 2]].'' During her time in the United States, de Rossi worked diligently to drop her Australian accent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/05/07/1052280317160.html|title=The Very Private Portia|work=The Age|location=Melbourne|date=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nDe Rossi garnered international attention when she joined the main cast of ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' in 1998, playing lawyer Nelle Porter. She remained with the show until its end in 2002. In 2001, she starred in ''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]'' alongside [[Christian Slater]]. From 2003\u201306, de Rossi starred as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on [[Fox Television]]'s ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]].'' She next portrayed [[John F. Kennedy, Jr.]]'s wife, [[Carolyn Bessette-Kennedy]], in the made-for-TV movie ''[[America's Prince: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story]]'' in 2003.  That same year, she portrayed an Australian reporter who inspires a protest against [[Frank Sinatra]] during a concert tour in ''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]].''\n\nIn 2005 de Rossi portrayed Zela, a fortune-teller, in the Wes Craven thriller ''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]].'' From 2007\u20132008, de Rossi appeared in ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'s'' fifth season as [[Julia McNamara]]'s girlfriend, [[Olivia Lord]].\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, de Rossi played the high-strung and controlling Veronica Palmer on the ABC show ''[[Better Off Ted]].'' In 2011, she appeared in ''Better Off Ted'' cast member [[Malcolm Barrett (actor)|Malcolm Barrett]]'s music video for \"Revenge of the Nerds,\" spoofing her character of Veronica in a cameo alongside other cast members of the cancelled series.<ref>{{cite web| title =Better Off Ted cast reunites for Malcolm Barrett's hip-hop video| publisher =Zap2It.com| url =http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| accessdate =16 November 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120110133350/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| archivedate =10 January 2012| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Portia de Rossi.jpg|thumb|left|Rossi in 2007]]\nShe ranked 69th in ''[[Stuff (magazine)|Stuff]] Magazine's'' 100 Sexiest Women, 31 in ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]]''' Sexiest Women of 2003 list, and 24 in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'s'' 100 Sexiest Women List in 2004; in late 2006, the magazine ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' listed her as one of the hottest women of film and TV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hottest Women of...Film and TV!|date=1 January 2007|first=Mike|last=Errico|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516065116/http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|archivedate=16 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May of 2007, she was featured as one of 100 Most Beautiful in a ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' special edition. ''[[TV Guide]]'' included her and Ellen DeGeneres in their Power A-List couples in 2007.\n\nIn February 2012, it was announced that [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] had ordered a pilot for a new drama series ''The Smart One,'' one of whose executive producers was listed as Ellen DeGeneres, and which featured de Rossi in a leading role. The actress was to star as a \"brilliant and successful woman who begrudgingly goes to work for her less-brainy but more popular sister \u2013 a former beauty queen, weather girl and now big-city Mayor.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one|title=ABC to air Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's \"The Smart One\"|publisher=Unreality TV|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206163932/http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one/|archivedate=6 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> But ''The Smart One'' was not picked up for the 2012-13 season.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nSix years after the series was canceled by Fox, filming for a revived fourth season of ''Arrested Development'' began on 7 August 2012, and de Rossi reprised her role as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]]. This fourth season consisted of 15 new episodes, which debuted at the same time on Netflix on 26 May 2013. Each episode focused on one particular character, with de Rossi's Lindsay featured in Episode 3, \"Indian Takers,\" and Episode 8, \"Red Hairing,\" and also appearing in several other episodes of the season.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|5577}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, ABC confirmed that de Rossi was joining season 4 of ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]],'' in the role of Elizabeth North.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/portia-de-rossi-scandal-1201268000|title=Portia de Rossi Joins 'Scandal' in 'Top Secret Arc'|publisher=Variety|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014|first=Nikara|last=Johns}}</ref> De Rossi joined ''Scandal'' in the fourth season in a recurring role, before being upped to a series regular for the fifth season. In April 2017, in season six, de Rossi's character, Elizabeth North, was killed off by a golf club attack. De Rossi herself made the decision to depart the ''Scandal'' series, saying, \"I am incredibly grateful for my time here at ''Scandal.'' I will miss playing Elizabeth North but I've made the decision to focus on a business opportunity. Shonda, Betsy and the cast have been incredibly supportive of my decision. I will always love my ''Scandal'' family. I'll be watching!\" Creator Shonda Rhimes added, \"I have been a fan of Portia's for years and it was an honor to have her join our ''Scandal'' family.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, de Rossi announced on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' that she would be retiring from acting, though she later elaborated that she would make an exception for future seasons of ''Arrested Development''.<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/4212133/portia-de-rossi-quit-acting/ Portia de Rossi confirms on \u2018Ellen\u2019 that she has decided to quit acting]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IlXvP0O4cfw Portia de Rossi Talks What's Next After Acting]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:PortiadeRossiEllenDeGeneresHWOFSept2012.jpg|thumb|right|upright|De Rossi and her wife, Ellen DeGeneres, in September 2012]]\nDe Rossi was married to documentary film-maker Mel Metcalfe, from 1996 to 1999, initially part of a plan to get a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]], though she did not go through with the plan. She said about the marriage that \"it just obviously wasn't right for me.\"<ref name=Advocate/> In a 2010 interview on ''[[Good Morning America]],'' she explained that as a young actress, she was fearful of being exposed as a lesbian.<ref name=\"gmabook\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/portia-de-rossi-reveals-depths-eating-disorders-book/story?id=12033594|title=Portia de Rossi: 'I Would Starve Myself Daily'|date=3 November 2010|publisher=ABC News|author=Olivia Katrandjian|accessdate=3 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2004, de Rossi dated director [[Francesca Gregorini]], the daughter of [[Barbara Bach]] and the stepdaughter of [[Ringo Starr]]. She said that most of her family and ''Ally McBeal'' castmates did not know she was a lesbian until tabloid pictures of the couple were published.<ref name=Advocate/> She declined to publicly discuss the relationship or her sexual orientation at the time.\n\nDe Rossi and Gregorini broke up in late 2004 because de Rossi began dating DeGeneres, whom she met backstage at an awards show. In 2005, she opened up publicly about her sexual orientation in interviews with ''[[Details (magazine)|Details]]'' and ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]].'' She and DeGeneres became engaged when DeGeneres proposed in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-road-to-romance-2012261|title=Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's Road to Romance |date=26 January 2012|first=Zach|last=Johnson|work=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref> They were married at their Beverly Hills home on 16 August 2008, witnessed by their mothers and 17 other guests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/2580530/Television-presenter-Ellen-DeGeneres-marries-lesbian-lover-Portia-de-Rossi.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=Television presenter Ellen DeGeneres marries lesbian lover Portia de Rossi|first=Anita|last=Singh|date=18 August 2008|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> On 6 August 2010, de Rossi filed a petition to legally change her name to Portia Lee James DeGeneres.<ref name=\"TMZnamechange\">{{cite web|last=TMZ Staff|title=Portia to Ellen: I Want to Be a DeGeneres!|url=http://www.tmz.com/2010/08/09/ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-name-change-petition-married-gay-marriage|work=[[TMZ.com|TMZ]]|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref> The petition was granted on 23 September 2010.<ref name=Yahoo.com>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi takes wife Ellen DeGeneres' name|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2010-09-23-derossi-name-change_N.htm|work=USA Today|date=23 September 2010}}</ref> She became a United States citizen in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2011/09/portia_becomes_a_us_citizen_0915.php|title=Portia Becomes a U.S. Citizen!|publisher=Ellen.warnerbros.com|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, de Rossi published her autobiography, titled ''Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain,'' within which she wrote about the turmoil that she had experienced in her life, including suffering from [[anorexia nervosa]] and [[bulimia]] and being misdiagnosed with [[lupus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=de Rossi|first=Portia|title=Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain|publisher=Atria|date=November 2010|isbn=1-4391-7778-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unbearablelightn00dero}}</ref> She had struggled with the [[eating disorders]] for four years while filming ''Ally McBeal.''<ref name=Vogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com|title= Disappearing Act: How did Portia de Rossi withstand the pressures of Hollywood.|accessdate=22 March 2009|last=Van Meter|first=Jonathan|publisher=Vogue|archiveurl=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-15043182_ITM|archivedate= 1 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi nips at new TV challenges|first=Donna|last=Freydkin|work=USA Today|date=13 November 2007|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-11-12-portia-de-rossi_N.htm}}</ref> To promote the book, she appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' and ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]].''\n \nDeGeneres and de Rossi both became vegans in 2008, though DeGeneres stated that she is no longer vegan.  They have adopted several rescue animals.<ref>{{cite web|author=Juliette Steen |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/2016/04/29/famous-vegans-and-vegetarians-some-of-these-celebrities-might-s/ |title=Famous Vegans And Vegetarians (Some Of These Celebrities Might Surprise You) |website=Huffingtonpost.com.au |date=29 April 2016|accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|title=A Heart for Animals: Ellen DeGeneres & Portia de Rossi on The Celebrity Spot|date=25 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025051112/http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|archivedate=25 October 2014|df=dmy-all|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, de Rossi tweeted that actor [[Steven Seagal]] exposed himself to her while she was auditioning for one of his films.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi: Steven Seagal Sexually Harassed Me During an Audition|first=Tracy E.|last=Gilchrest|work=The Advocate|date=8 November 2017|url=https://www.advocate.com/women/2017/11/08/portia-de-rossi-steven-segal-sexually-harassed-me-during-audition}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41936741|title=Portia de Rossi accuses Steven Seagal of sexual harassment|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nDe Rossi supports a variety of charitable organizations, including [[Locks of Love]], a group that provides human hair wigs (made from donated ponytails) either free of charge or on a sliding scale based on their own guidelines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac5|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Aa8|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|title=Charity Review of Locks of Love|publisher=Charityreports.give.org|accessdate=12 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307045743/http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|archivedate=7 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbb.org/charity-reviews/national/children-and-youth/locks-of-love-in-lake-worth-fl-1839|title=BBB review of Locks of Love|publisher=Bbb.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> for children with [[alopecia]] and other medical conditions that cause [[hair loss]], such as chemotherapy for certain types of [[cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac2|title=Locks of Love FAQ|publisher=Locksoflove.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nShe has also supported fundraising efforts for [[FXB International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2006/07/portia-de-rossi-helps-fxb-to-rebuild.html|title=Portia de Rossi Helps FXB to Rebuild Uganda|work=Celebrity Halo|date=July 2006|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an [[HIV/AIDS in Africa|African AIDS]] relief organization, and The Art of Elysium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2008/01/portia-de-rossi-supports-art-of-elysium.html|title=Portia de Rossi supports The Art of Elysium|work=Celebrity Halo|date=January 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an art foundation for terminally ill children. An avid animal lover, de Rossi also supports [[Alley Cat Allies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|title=I'm an Alley Cat Ally \u2013 Portia de Rossi|accessdate=29 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120045419/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|archivedate=20 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> an organization dedicated to protecting and improving the lives of cats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523010128/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 May 2009|title=Alley Cat Allies \u2013 About Us|accessdate=29 September 2010}}</ref> De Rossi and DeGeneres are strong supporters of [[The Gentle Barn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gentlebarn.org|title=The Gentle Barn|publisher=gentlebarn.org|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> a California sanctuary for abused animals.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!-- do not add rowspans to this table, it breaks sorting -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]]''\n|Giddy\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''The Woman in the Moon''\n|Shauna\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Scream 2]]''\n|Sorority Sister Murphy\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Girl (1998 film)|Girl]]''\n|Carla Sparrow\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''The Invisibles''\n|Joy\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[American Intellectuals]]''\n|Sarah\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Stigmata (film)|Stigmata]]''\n|Jennifer Kelliho\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''Women in Film''\n|Gina\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]''\n|Tess Donnelly\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''Two Girls from Leemore''\n|Blind Woman\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[I Witness]]''\n|Emily Thompson\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]]''\n|Hilary Hunter\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Dead & Breakfast]]''\n|Kelly\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]]''\n|Zela\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''The Shift''\n|Denise Moore\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |title=About the Cast of THE SHIFT (2009) - movie starring Dr. Wayne Dyer |publisher=Dyermovie.com |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222030536/http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Unity (film)|Unity]]''\n|Narrator\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Now Add Honey]]''\n|Beth Halloway\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n<!-- do not add rowspans to this table, it breaks sorting -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1995\u20131996\n|''[[Too Something]]''\n|Maria Hunter\n|Main cast; 22 episodes\n|-\n|1996\u20131997\n|''[[Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher]]''\n|Elana Lewis\n|Main cast; 22 episodes\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Veronica's Closet]]''\n|Carolyn\n| Episode: \"Veronica's First Date\"\n|-\n|1998\n|''Astoria''\n|\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|1998\n|''A Breed Apart''\n|Lana Collins\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|1998\u20132002\n|''[[Ally McBeal]]''\n|[[Nelle Porter]]\n|Main cast; 89 episodes\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Ally (sitcom)|Ally]]''\n|Nelle Porter\n|Main cast; 12 episodes; ''Ally McBeal'' spin-off\n|-\n|2002\n|''The Glow''\n|Jackie Lawrence\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]''\n|Laurel Janus\n| Episode: \"[[Dead Man's Eyes (The Twilight Zone)|Dead Man's Eyes]]\"\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[America's Prince: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story]]''\n|[[Carolyn Bessette-Kennedy]]\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Mister Sterling]]''\n|Lauren Barnes\n|2 episodes: \"Wish List\" and \"Final Passage\"\n|-\n|2003\u20132006,<br>2013,<br>2018-2019\n|''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]''\n|[[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]]\n|Main cast; 70 episodes\n|-\n|2007\u20132009\n|''[[Nip/Tuck]]''\n|[[Olivia Lord]]\n|Recurring cast (Season 5); 10 episodes\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|''[[Better Off Ted]]''\n|Veronica Palmer\n|Main cast; 26 episodes\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Mockingbird Lane]]''\n|Lily Munster\n| Pilot\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Sean Saves the World]]''\n|Jill\n| Episode: \"The Joy of Ex\"\n|-\n|2014\u20132017\n|''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]''\n|Elizabeth North\n|Recurring (Season 4), Main cast (Seasons 5\u20136)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2015/05/14/scandal-season-5-cast-portia-de-rossi-liz-chief-of-staff/|title='Scandal' Season 5 Cast: Portia de Ross a Series Regular, Liz Chief of Staff&nbsp;\u2013 TVLine|author=Michael Ausiello|date=|work=TVLine|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]''\n| Dr. Wolf \n| 2 episodes: \"The Book!\" and \"Baka, Bile and Baseball Bats\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Bonnie Swanson (prank call voice)\n| Episode: \"A House Full of Peters\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Award\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Category\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Work\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Result\n|-\n|1999\n|rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|[[5th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|rowspan=3|''Ally McBeal''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2000\n|[[6th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2001\n|[[7th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2004\n|[[TV Land Award]]\n|Future Classic Award <small> Shared with [[Jason Bateman]], [[Will Arnett]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jessica Walter]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Mitchell Hurwitz|Mitchell Hurwitz (executive producer)]], and [[David Nevins (television producer)|David Nevins (executive producer)]] </small>\n|rowspan=6|''Arrested Development''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Satellite Award|Golden Satellite Award]]\n|[[8th Golden Satellite Awards#Best Supporting Actress - Musical or Comedy Series|Best Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role in a Series, Comedy or Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2005\n|[[9th Golden Satellite Awards#Best Actress - Musical or Comedy Series|Best Actress in a Series, Comedy or Musical]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|[[11th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], and [[Jessica Walters]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2006\n|[[12th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], and [[Jessica Walters]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2014\n|[[20th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Television|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[John Beard (news anchor)|John Beard]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Isla Fisher]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Ron Howard]], [[Liza Minnelli]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Jessica Walter]], and [[Henry Winkler]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q215366|c=Category:Portia de Rossi|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=nO|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|0005577}}\n* {{Amg name|198456}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Portia de Rossi\n|list =\n{{Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVComedy 1994\u20131999}}\n}}\n{{Ellen DeGeneres}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Rossi, Portia}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate actresses in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:People from Geelong]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:People from Horsham, Victoria]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Melbourne Girls Grammar]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian actress married to comedian ellen}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =Portia de Rossi\n| image              =PortiadeRossi Sept2012.jpg\n| caption            = Portia de Rossi in 2012\n| birth_name         = Amanda Lee Rogers\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1973|01|31}}\n| birth_place        = [[Horsham, Victoria]], Australia\n| residence          = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Australian]], \n[[United States|American]]\n| other_names        = Portia Lee James DeGeneres\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Melbourne]]\n| occupation         = Actress, model, philanthropist\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present\n\n| spouse             = \n{{marriage|Mel Metcalfe<!--- Do not link. Wikipedia has an article about a different Mel Metcalfe.---><br>|1996|1999|reason=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|[[Ellen DeGeneres]]<br>|2008}}\n}}\n\n'''Portia Lee James DeGeneres''' (born '''Amanda Lee Rogers'''; 31 January 1973), known professionally as '''Portia de Rossi''', is an Australian-American model, philanthropist, actress. She is best known for starring as [[Nelle Porter]] on the American drama series ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' (1998\u20132002), for which she won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], as [[Lindsay F\u00fcnke|Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on the American television sitcom ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' (2003\u20132006, 2013, 2018\u20132019), and as Elizabeth North on the American [[political thriller]] series ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]'' (2014\u20132017).<ref>{{cite web|author=Samantha Highfill |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/07/23/portia-de-rossi-scandal |title=Portia de Rossi joins season 4 of 'Scandal' |website=Entertainment Weekly|date=2014-07-23 |accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/scandal-elizabeth-north-portia-de-rossi-dead-killed-1202391942/|title='Scandal' Star, Shonda Rhimes React to Major Death (SPOILERS)|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=21 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-bios/portia-de-rossi|accessdate=28 January 2009|title=Celebrity Bios: Portia de Rossi|publisher=Us Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Geelong's Portia Marries Ellen|url=http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/08/18/17323_news.html|accessdate=28 January 2009|publisher=Geelong Advertiser|date=18 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nShe also portrayed [[Olivia Lord]] on the American television drama series ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' (2007\u20132009) and Veronica Palmer on the American television sitcom ''[[Better Off Ted]]'' (2009\u20132010). De Rossi is married to comedian, actress, and television host [[Ellen DeGeneres]].\n\n==Early life==\nPortia de Rossi, born Amanda Lee Rogers in [[Horsham, Victoria|Horsham]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi|title=Australian Actress: Portia de Rossi|author=London Academy of Media and Film TV|accessdate=24 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301142048/http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi/|archivedate=1 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is the daughter of Margaret, a medical receptionist, and Barry Rogers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/91/Portia-de-Rossi.html|title=Portia de Rossi profile|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Her father died when she was nine years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTw1MoscAk4|title=Portia de Rossi on Ellen|work=Youtube|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref> She grew up in [[Grovedale, Victoria|Grovedale]], a suburb of [[Geelong]], Victoria, and modelled for print and TV commercials as a child. In 1988, at age 15, Rogers adopted the name Portia de Rossi, by which she remains best known. In 2005, she explained she had intended to reinvent herself, using the given name of [[Portia (Merchant of Venice)|Portia]], a character from [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[The Merchant of Venice]],'' and an Italian last name. She was educated at [[Geelong Grammar| Geelong Grammar School]] and the [[University of Melbourne]], where she studied law.<ref name=Advocate>{{cite web |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200735/http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |title=Portia heart & soul |last1=Kort |first1=Michele |date=29 August 2005 |website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |publisher=[[Here Media]] |access-date=19 August 2015 |archive-date=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDe Rossi's first significant role was as a young and impressionable model in the Australian [[1994 in film|1994 film]] ''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]].'' Soon afterward, she moved to Los Angeles and won guest roles on several TV shows and a permanent role in ''[[Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher]],'' before landing a part in the film ''[[Scream 2]].'' During her time in the United States, de Rossi worked diligently to drop her Australian accent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/05/07/1052280317160.html|title=The Very Private Portia|work=The Age|location=Melbourne|date=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nDe Rossi garnered international attention when she joined the main cast of ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' in 1998, playing lawyer Nelle Porter. She remained with the show until its end in 2002. In 2001, she starred in ''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]'' alongside [[Christian Slater]]. From 2003\u201306, de Rossi starred as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on [[Fox Television]]'s ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]].'' She next portrayed [[John F. Kennedy, Jr.]]'s wife, [[Carolyn Bessette-Kennedy]], in the made-for-TV movie ''[[America's Prince: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story]]'' in 2003.  That same year, she portrayed an Australian reporter who inspires a protest against [[Frank Sinatra]] during a concert tour in ''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]].''\n\nIn 2005 de Rossi portrayed Zela, a fortune-teller, in the Wes Craven thriller ''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]].'' From 2007\u20132008, de Rossi appeared in ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'s'' fifth season as [[Julia McNamara]]'s girlfriend, [[Olivia Lord]].\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, de Rossi played the high-strung and controlling Veronica Palmer on the ABC show ''[[Better Off Ted]].'' In 2011, she appeared in ''Better Off Ted'' cast member [[Malcolm Barrett (actor)|Malcolm Barrett]]'s music video for \"Revenge of the Nerds,\" spoofing her character of Veronica in a cameo alongside other cast members of the cancelled series.<ref>{{cite web| title =Better Off Ted cast reunites for Malcolm Barrett's hip-hop video| publisher =Zap2It.com| url =http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| accessdate =16 November 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120110133350/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| archivedate =10 January 2012| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Portia de Rossi.jpg|thumb|left|Rossi in 2007]]\nShe ranked 69th in ''[[Stuff (magazine)|Stuff]] Magazine's'' 100 Sexiest Women, 31 in ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]]''' Sexiest Women of 2003 list, and 24 in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'s'' 100 Sexiest Women List in 2004; in late 2006, the magazine ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' listed her as one of the hottest women of film and TV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hottest Women of...Film and TV!|date=1 January 2007|first=Mike|last=Errico|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516065116/http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|archivedate=16 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May of 2007, she was featured as one of 100 Most Beautiful in a ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' special edition. ''[[TV Guide]]'' included her and Ellen DeGeneres in their Power A-List couples in 2007.\n\nIn February 2012, it was announced that [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] had ordered a pilot for a new drama series ''The Smart One,'' one of whose executive producers was listed as Ellen DeGeneres, and which featured de Rossi in a leading role. The actress was to star as a \"brilliant and successful woman who begrudgingly goes to work for her less-brainy but more popular sister \u2013 a former beauty queen, weather girl and now big-city Mayor.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one|title=ABC to air Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's \"The Smart One\"|publisher=Unreality TV|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206163932/http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one/|archivedate=6 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> But ''The Smart One'' was not picked up for the 2012-13 season.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nSix years after the series was canceled by Fox, filming for a revived fourth season of ''Arrested Development'' began on 7 August 2012, and de Rossi reprised her role as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]]. This fourth season consisted of 15 new episodes, which debuted at the same time on Netflix on 26 May 2013. Each episode focused on one particular character, with de Rossi's Lindsay featured in Episode 3, \"Indian Takers,\" and Episode 8, \"Red Hairing,\" and also appearing in several other episodes of the season.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|5577}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, ABC confirmed that de Rossi was joining season 4 of ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]],'' in the role of Elizabeth North.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/portia-de-rossi-scandal-1201268000|title=Portia de Rossi Joins 'Scandal' in 'Top Secret Arc'|publisher=Variety|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014|first=Nikara|last=Johns}}</ref> De Rossi joined ''Scandal'' in the fourth season in a recurring role, before being upped to a series regular for the fifth season. In April 2017, in season six, de Rossi's character, Elizabeth North, was killed off by a golf club attack. De Rossi herself made the decision to depart the ''Scandal'' series, saying, \"I am incredibly grateful for my time here at ''Scandal.'' I will miss playing Elizabeth North but I've made the decision to focus on a business opportunity. Shonda, Betsy and the cast have been incredibly supportive of my decision. I will always love my ''Scandal'' family. I'll be watching!\" Creator Shonda Rhimes added, \"I have been a fan of Portia's for years and it was an honor to have her join our ''Scandal'' family.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, de Rossi announced on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' that she would be retiring from acting, though she later elaborated that she would make an exception for future seasons of ''Arrested Development''.<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/4212133/portia-de-rossi-quit-acting/ Portia de Rossi confirms on \u2018Ellen\u2019 that she has decided to quit acting]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IlXvP0O4cfw Portia de Rossi Talks What's Next After Acting]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:PortiadeRossiEllenDeGeneresHWOFSept2012.jpg|thumb|right|upright|De Rossi and her wife, Ellen DeGeneres, in September 2012]]\nDe Rossi was married to documentary film-maker Mel Metcalfe, from 1996 to 1999, initially part of a plan to get a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]], though she did not go through with the plan. She said about the marriage that \"it just obviously wasn't right for me.\"<ref name=Advocate/> In a 2010 interview on ''[[Good Morning America]],'' she explained that as a young actress, she was fearful of being exposed as a lesbian.<ref name=\"gmabook\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/portia-de-rossi-reveals-depths-eating-disorders-book/story?id=12033594|title=Portia de Rossi: 'I Would Starve Myself Daily'|date=3 November 2010|publisher=ABC News|author=Olivia Katrandjian|accessdate=3 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2004, de Rossi dated director [[Francesca Gregorini]], the daughter of [[Barbara Bach]] and the stepdaughter of [[Ringo Starr]]. She said that most of her family and ''Ally McBeal'' castmates did not know she was a lesbian until tabloid pictures of the couple were published.<ref name=Advocate/> She declined to publicly discuss the relationship or her sexual orientation at the time.\n\nDe Rossi and Gregorini broke up in late 2004 because de Rossi began dating DeGeneres, whom she met backstage at an awards show. In 2005, she opened up publicly about her sexual orientation in interviews with ''[[Details (magazine)|Details]]'' and ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]].'' She and DeGeneres became engaged when DeGeneres proposed in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-road-to-romance-2012261|title=Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's Road to Romance |date=26 January 2012|first=Zach|last=Johnson|work=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref> They were married at their Beverly Hills home on 16 August 2008, witnessed by their mothers and 17 other guests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/2580530/Television-presenter-Ellen-DeGeneres-marries-lesbian-lover-Portia-de-Rossi.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=Television presenter Ellen DeGeneres marries lesbian lover Portia de Rossi|first=Anita|last=Singh|date=18 August 2008|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> On 6 August 2010, de Rossi filed a petition to legally change her name to Portia Lee James DeGeneres.<ref name=\"TMZnamechange\">{{cite web|last=TMZ Staff|title=Portia to Ellen: I Want to Be a DeGeneres!|url=http://www.tmz.com/2010/08/09/ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-name-change-petition-married-gay-marriage|work=[[TMZ.com|TMZ]]|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref> The petition was granted on 23 September 2010.<ref name=Yahoo.com>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi takes wife Ellen DeGeneres' name|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2010-09-23-derossi-name-change_N.htm|work=USA Today|date=23 September 2010}}</ref> She became a United States citizen in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2011/09/portia_becomes_a_us_citizen_0915.php|title=Portia Becomes a U.S. Citizen!|publisher=Ellen.warnerbros.com|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, de Rossi published her autobiography, titled ''Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain,'' within which she wrote about the turmoil that she had experienced in her life, including suffering from [[anorexia nervosa]] and [[bulimia]] and being misdiagnosed with [[lupus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=de Rossi|first=Portia|title=Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain|publisher=Atria|date=November 2010|isbn=1-4391-7778-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unbearablelightn00dero}}</ref> She had struggled with the [[eating disorders]] for four years while filming ''Ally McBeal.''<ref name=Vogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com|title= Disappearing Act: How did Portia de Rossi withstand the pressures of Hollywood.|accessdate=22 March 2009|last=Van Meter|first=Jonathan|publisher=Vogue|archiveurl=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-15043182_ITM|archivedate= 1 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi nips at new TV challenges|first=Donna|last=Freydkin|work=USA Today|date=13 November 2007|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-11-12-portia-de-rossi_N.htm}}</ref> To promote the book, she appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' and ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]].''\n \nDeGeneres and de Rossi both became vegans in 2008, though DeGeneres stated that she is no longer vegan.  They have adopted several rescue animals.<ref>{{cite web|author=Juliette Steen |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/2016/04/29/famous-vegans-and-vegetarians-some-of-these-celebrities-might-s/ |title=Famous Vegans And Vegetarians (Some Of These Celebrities Might Surprise You) |website=Huffingtonpost.com.au |date=29 April 2016|accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|title=A Heart for Animals: Ellen DeGeneres & Portia de Rossi on The Celebrity Spot|date=25 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025051112/http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|archivedate=25 October 2014|df=dmy-all|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, de Rossi tweeted that actor [[Steven Seagal]] exposed himself to her while she was auditioning for one of his films.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi: Steven Seagal Sexually Harassed Me During an Audition|first=Tracy E.|last=Gilchrest|work=The Advocate|date=8 November 2017|url=https://www.advocate.com/women/2017/11/08/portia-de-rossi-steven-segal-sexually-harassed-me-during-audition}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41936741|title=Portia de Rossi accuses Steven Seagal of sexual harassment|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nDe Rossi supports a variety of charitable organizations, including [[Locks of Love]], a group that provides human hair wigs (made from donated ponytails) either free of charge or on a sliding scale based on their own guidelines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac5|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Aa8|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|title=Charity Review of Locks of Love|publisher=Charityreports.give.org|accessdate=12 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307045743/http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|archivedate=7 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbb.org/charity-reviews/national/children-and-youth/locks-of-love-in-lake-worth-fl-1839|title=BBB review of Locks of Love|publisher=Bbb.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> for children with [[alopecia]] and other medical conditions that cause [[hair loss]], such as chemotherapy for certain types of [[cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac2|title=Locks of Love FAQ|publisher=Locksoflove.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nShe has also supported fundraising efforts for [[FXB International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2006/07/portia-de-rossi-helps-fxb-to-rebuild.html|title=Portia de Rossi Helps FXB to Rebuild Uganda|work=Celebrity Halo|date=July 2006|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an [[HIV/AIDS in Africa|African AIDS]] relief organization, and The Art of Elysium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2008/01/portia-de-rossi-supports-art-of-elysium.html|title=Portia de Rossi supports The Art of Elysium|work=Celebrity Halo|date=January 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an art foundation for terminally ill children. An avid animal lover, de Rossi also supports [[Alley Cat Allies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|title=I'm an Alley Cat Ally \u2013 Portia de Rossi|accessdate=29 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120045419/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|archivedate=20 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> an organization dedicated to protecting and improving the lives of cats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523010128/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 May 2009|title=Alley Cat Allies \u2013 About Us|accessdate=29 September 2010}}</ref> De Rossi and DeGeneres are strong supporters of [[The Gentle Barn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gentlebarn.org|title=The Gentle Barn|publisher=gentlebarn.org|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> a California sanctuary for abused animals.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!-- do not add rowspans to this table, it breaks sorting -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]]''\n|Giddy\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''The Woman in the Moon''\n|Shauna\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Scream 2]]''\n|Sorority Sister Murphy\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Girl (1998 film)|Girl]]''\n|Carla Sparrow\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''The Invisibles''\n|Joy\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[American Intellectuals]]''\n|Sarah\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Stigmata (film)|Stigmata]]''\n|Jennifer Kelliho\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''Women in Film''\n|Gina\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]''\n|Tess Donnelly\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''Two Girls from Leemore''\n|Blind Woman\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[I Witness]]''\n|Emily Thompson\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]]''\n|Hilary Hunter\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Dead & Breakfast]]''\n|Kelly\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]]''\n|Zela\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''The Shift''\n|Denise Moore\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |title=About the Cast of THE SHIFT (2009) - movie starring Dr. Wayne Dyer |publisher=Dyermovie.com |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222030536/http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Unity (film)|Unity]]''\n|Narrator\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Now Add Honey]]''\n|Beth Halloway\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n<!-- do not add rowspans to this table, it breaks sorting -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1995\u20131996\n|''[[Too Something]]''\n|Maria Hunter\n|Main cast; 22 episodes\n|-\n|1996\u20131997\n|''[[Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher]]''\n|Elana Lewis\n|Main cast; 22 episodes\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Veronica's Closet]]''\n|Carolyn\n| Episode: \"Veronica's First Date\"\n|-\n|1998\n|''Astoria''\n|\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|1998\n|''A Breed Apart''\n|Lana Collins\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|1998\u20132002\n|''[[Ally McBeal]]''\n|[[Nelle Porter]]\n|Main cast; 89 episodes\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Ally (sitcom)|Ally]]''\n|Nelle Porter\n|Main cast; 12 episodes; ''Ally McBeal'' spin-off\n|-\n|2002\n|''The Glow''\n|Jackie Lawrence\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]''\n|Laurel Janus\n| Episode: \"[[Dead Man's Eyes (The Twilight Zone)|Dead Man's Eyes]]\"\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[America's Prince: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story]]''\n|[[Carolyn Bessette-Kennedy]]\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Mister Sterling]]''\n|Lauren Barnes\n|2 episodes: \"Wish List\" and \"Final Passage\"\n|-\n|2003\u20132006,<br>2013,<br>2018-2019\n|''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]''\n|[[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]]\n|Main cast; 70 episodes\n|-\n|2007\u20132009\n|''[[Nip/Tuck]]''\n|[[Olivia Lord]]\n|Recurring cast (Season 5); 10 episodes\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|''[[Better Off Ted]]''\n|Veronica Palmer\n|Main cast; 26 episodes\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Mockingbird Lane]]''\n|Lily Munster\n| Pilot\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Sean Saves the World]]''\n|Jill\n| Episode: \"The Joy of Ex\"\n|-\n|2014\u20132017\n|''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]''\n|Elizabeth North\n|Recurring (Season 4), Main cast (Seasons 5\u20136)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2015/05/14/scandal-season-5-cast-portia-de-rossi-liz-chief-of-staff/|title='Scandal' Season 5 Cast: Portia de Ross a Series Regular, Liz Chief of Staff&nbsp;\u2013 TVLine|author=Michael Ausiello|date=|work=TVLine|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]''\n| Dr. Wolf \n| 2 episodes: \"The Book!\" and \"Baka, Bile and Baseball Bats\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Bonnie Swanson (prank call voice)\n| Episode: \"A House Full of Peters\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Award\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Category\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Work\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Result\n|-\n|1999\n|rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|[[5th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|rowspan=3|''Ally McBeal''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2000\n|[[6th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2001\n|[[7th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2004\n|[[TV Land Award]]\n|Future Classic Award <small> Shared with [[Jason Bateman]], [[Will Arnett]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jessica Walter]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Mitchell Hurwitz|Mitchell Hurwitz (executive producer)]], and [[David Nevins (television producer)|David Nevins (executive producer)]] </small>\n|rowspan=6|''Arrested Development''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Satellite Award|Golden Satellite Award]]\n|[[8th Golden Satellite Awards#Best Supporting Actress - Musical or Comedy Series|Best Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role in a Series, Comedy or Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2005\n|[[9th Golden Satellite Awards#Best Actress - Musical or Comedy Series|Best Actress in a Series, Comedy or Musical]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|[[11th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], and [[Jessica Walters]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2006\n|[[12th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], and [[Jessica Walters]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2014\n|[[20th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Television|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[John Beard (news anchor)|John Beard]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Isla Fisher]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Ron Howard]], [[Liza Minnelli]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Jessica Walter]], and [[Henry Winkler]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q215366|c=Category:Portia de Rossi|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=nO|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|0005577}}\n* {{Amg name|198456}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Portia de Rossi\n|list =\n{{Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVComedy 1994\u20131999}}\n}}\n{{Ellen DeGeneres}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Rossi, Portia}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate actresses in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:People from Geelong]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:People from Horsham, Victoria]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Melbourne Girls Grammar]]\n", "name_user": "Baane247", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portia_de_Rossi"}
{"title_page": "Ichthyovenator", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Aptian]]) {{fossilrange|125|113}}\n| image = Ichthyovenator laosensis.jpg\n| image_caption = Casts of the known [[spinal column]] at the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo. The thirteenth [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] spine and the lower part of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacrum]] have been partially reconstructed.\n| image_alt = White casts of fossil spinal column with a wave-like sail on display at a museum\n| taxon = Ichthyovenator\n| authority = Allain ''et al.'', [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Ichthyovenator laosensis'''''\n| type_species_authority = Allain ''et al.'', 2012\n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = \n}}\n\n'''''Ichthyovenator''''' is a [[genus]] of [[spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived in what is now Laos during the [[Aptian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]], sometime between 125 to 113 million years ago. It is known from [[Fossil|fossils]] collected in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]], the first of which were found in 2010, and comprised a partial skeleton without the skull or limbs. This specimen became the [[holotype]] of the new genus and [[species]] '''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''', and was described by French [[palaeontologist]] Ronan Allain and colleagues in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]. The generic name, meaning \"fish hunter\", refers to its assumed [[piscivorous]] lifestyle, while the specific name alludes to the country of Laos. In 2014, it was announced that further remains from the dig site had been recovered, these fossils included teeth as well as more [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#vertebrae|vertebrae]] (backbones) and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubic bone]] from the same individual.\n\nThe holotype specimen is estimated to have been {{convert|8.5 and 10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long and weighed {{convert|2 to 2.4|t|short ton|abbr=}}. ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight and conical, and its neck resembled that of the closely related ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''. Like others in its family, ''Ichthyovenator'' had tall [[neural spines]] forming a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back. Unusually among all other known spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail had a [[sinusoidal]] (wave-like) shape, curving downwards over the hips into two separate sails. The [[pelvic girdle]] was reduced, with the length ratio between the main body of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] and the pubes and ischia being higher than in any other known theropod dinosaurs. The animal was initially thought to belong to the [[Baryonychinae]] [[subfamily]], but more recent analyses place it as a primitive member in the [[Spinosaurinae]].\n\nAs a spinosaur, ''Ichthyovenator'' would have had a long, shallow snout and robust forelimbs. Its diet likely consisted mainly of aquatic prey (hence its etymology). Spinosaurids are also known to have eaten small dinosaurs and [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] in addition to fish. ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s conspicuous sail might have been used for [[sexual display]] or [[species recognition]]. Fossil evidence suggests that spinosaurids, especially spinosaurines, were adapted for [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. The vertebral spines of ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s tail were unusually tall, suggesting that\u2014like in today's [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]\u2014the tail may have aided in swimming. ''Ichthyovenator'' lived alongside [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as [[Bivalvia|bivalves]], fish and turtles.\n\n==Discovery and naming==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_skeletal_%26_size_comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|left|alt=Drawing of fossil rib, backbones and pelvis superimposed on silhouette of a dinosaur|Skeletal diagram with [[holotype]] elements in place, excluding the additional [[fossil]] material announced in 2014]]\n\nThe first [[fossil|fossils]] of ''Ichthyovenator'' were found in 2010 at [[Ban Kalum]], in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]] in [[Savannakhet Province]], Laos. These bones were recovered from a [[red sandstone]] layer, within a surface area of less than {{convert|2|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} squared. Designated under the specimen number MDS BK10-01 \u2014 15, it consists of a partly [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#articulation|articulated]], well preserved skeleton lacking the skull and limbs, and including the third to last [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] (back) [[vertebra]], the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#neural spine|neural spine]] of the last dorsal vertebra, five partial [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacral]] (hip) vertebrae, the first two [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae, both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ilium|ilia]] (main hip bone), a right [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubis]] (pubic bone), both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischium|ischia]] (lower and rearmost hip bones) and a posterior dorsal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ribs|rib]]. The twelfth dorsal spine is bent sideways when viewed front-to-back due to [[Taphonomy|taphonomic]] distorsion, and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#centrum|centra]] (bodies of the vertebrae) of the sacrals are largely incomplete due to erosion, but preserved all their accompanying spines with their upper edges intact. At the time of ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s description, excavations at the site were still ongoing.<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref>\n\nAfter undergoing preparation in 2011, the skeleton was used as the basis, or [[holotype]], for the [[type species]] ''Ichthyovenator laosensis''; named and described in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]] by French [[palaeontologist]] Ronan Allain, Tiengkham Xeisanavong, Philippe Richir, and Bounsou Khentavong. The [[Generic name (biology)|generic name]] is derived from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f30\u03c7\u03b8\u03cd\u03c2 (''ichthys''), \"fish\", and [[Latin]] ''venator'', \"hunter\", in reference to its likely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] refers to its provenance from Laos.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> ''Ichthyovenator'' is the third [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] named from Asia, after the Thai genus ''[[Siamosaurus]]'' in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], and the Chinese species \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' in [[2009 in archosaur paleontology|2009]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref>Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref><ref name=\"EBetal08\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B}}</ref> The latter may represent the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019-03-31|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892}}</ref>''\n\nIn 2014, a [[Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology]] abstract on the genus was published by Allain. This abstract indicated that additional remains from the original individual had been found after an excavation in 2012. These remains include three teeth, the left pubis, and many vertebrae, including a nearly complete neck, the first dorsal vertebra, and seven more caudal vertebrae. However, this abstract has not been formally published as an academic paper as of 2020.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Some of these additional vertebrae were compared with those of other spinosaurids in a 2015 paper by German paleontologist Serjoscha Evers and colleagues.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Evers|first=Serjoscha W.|last2=Rauhut|first2=Oliver W.M.|last3=Milner|first3=Angela C.|last4=McFeeters|first4=Bradley|last5=Allain|first5=Ronan|date=2015-10-20|title=A reappraisal of the morphology and systematic position of the theropod dinosaur Sigilmassasaurus from the \"middle\" Cretaceous of Morocco|journal=PeerJ|language=en|volume=3|pages=e1323|doi=10.7717/peerj.1323|pmid=26500829|pmc=4614847|issn=2167-8359}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Spinosauridae_Size_Diagram_by_PaleoGeek_-_Version_2.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Silhouettes of five left-facing spinosaurid dinosaurs compared with a blue human to their left, Ichthyovenator in yellow, second from right|Size of various [[spinosaurid]]s (''Ichthyovenator'' in yellow, second from right) compared with a human|alt=]]\n\nIn 2016, American palaeontologist [[Gregory S. Paul]] estimated ''Ichthyovenator'' at {{convert|8.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} in length and weighing {{convert|2|t|short ton|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Princeton field guide to dinosaurs|last=S.|first=Paul, Gregory|isbn=9781400883141|edition= 2nd|location=Princeton, N.J.|oclc=954055249|date = 2016-10-25}}</ref> The same year Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi gave a higher estimation of {{convert|10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long, {{convert|2.95|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} tall at the hips, and {{convert|2.4|t|short ton|abbr=}} in weight.<ref>{{Cite book|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|last=Molina-P\u00e9rez & Larramendi|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=259}}</ref>\n\n''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s teeth were conical, straight, and bore no [[Serration|serrations]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The front carinae (edges) of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#maxilla|maxillary]] and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentary|dentary]] teeth were evident on the base of the [[tooth crown]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The front articulating surfaces of ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s rear cervical and front dorsal vertebrae were one and a half times wider than they were high and wider than the length of their centra. They also bore robust front [[Tubercle (bone)|tubercles]] (processes for [[skeletal muscle]] attachment) and lacked inter[[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#zygapophyseal laminae|zygapophyseal laminae]], which resulted in their spinopre- and spinopostzygapophyseal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#fossae|fossae]] (depressions) having open undersides. The first dorsal vertebra had extensive [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#transverse processes|transverse processes]] (wing-like projections that articulate with the ribs), as well as deep air pockets at the front and back of its base. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#parapophyses|parapophysis]] (a process that articulated with the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#capitulum|capitulum]] of the ribs) of the first dorsal increased in height from the top and bottom, with its underside remaining in contact with the front lower edge of the centrum, this is unlike the condition in most theropods, where the parapophyses shifted towards the top of the vertebra during the transition from cervical to dorsal vertebrae. All of these features were also present in the African spinosaurid ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''. ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s mid-cervical vertebrae all had elongate, somewhat wider than tall centra that became progressively shorter towards the rear of the neck, as well as well-developed keels on their bottom surfaces, traits all shared with the spinosaurids ''[[Baryonyx]], [[Suchomimus]]'', ''Sigilmassasaurus'',<ref name=\":1\" /> and ''[[Vallibonavenatrix]]''.<ref name=\":3\">Elisabete Malafaia; Jos\u00e9 Miguel Gasulla; Fernando Escaso; Iv\u00e1n Narv\u00e1ez; Jos\u00e9 Luis Sanz; Francisco Ortega (2019). \"A new spinosaurid theropod (Dinosauria: Megalosauroidea) from the late Barremian of Vallibona, Spain: Implications for spinosaurid diversity in the Early Cretaceous of the Iberian Peninsula\". Cretaceous Research. in press: 104221. {{doi|10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104221}}.</ref> The cervical neural spines of ''Ichthyovenator'' were taller than in ''Sigilmassasaurus'' and ''Baryonyx'', but shared the blade-like shape with those two taxa at the mid-cervicals.<ref name=\":1\" /> The single known dorsal rib, which was found near the twelfth dorsal vertebra, had a head typical of the ribs of other moderately to large-sized theropods. The rib shaft was strongly curved, forming a half circle. The lower end of the rib was slightly expanded both sideways and to the front and back. This condition, which differs from the tapered, pointed tips seen in the ribs of other known theropods, suggests that the rearmost dorsal ribs articulated with the complex of the [[sternum]] (breast bone).<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_65849.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Cast fossil spinal column laid out inside a glass display case at a museum|Casts of the [[Vertebra|vertebrae]] at the [[Mus\u00e9um national d'histoire naturelle|Mus\u00e9um National d'Histoire Naturelle]], Paris|alt=|left]]\n\nLike many other spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator'' had a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back and hip, formed by the elongated [[neural spines]] of its vertebrae. Uniquely among known members of the family however, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail was divided in two over the hip, and had a [[sinusoid]] (wave-like) curvature. This is in contrast to the related genera ''[[Spinosaurus]]'' and ''Suchomimus'' (both of which had continuous sails that rose to a peak before sloping down again), and B''aryonyx'' (which showed a less developed sail, having much lower dorsal spines). ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s preserved dorsal and sacral [[spinal column]], over {{Convert|1|m||abbr=}} long, shows a very high spine on the twelfth dorsal vertebra, representing a crest that rose from the back, and a lower rounded sail that extended from the sacral vertebrae of the hip, with its highest point above the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|54.6|cm||adj=on}} high spine of the twelfth dorsal vertebra widened towards the top, giving it a [[Trapezoid|trapezoidal]] shape, whereas the spines of other spinosaurids were roughly rectangular. It also lacked the forward or backward inclination of ''Spinosaurus''<nowiki/>'s neural spines. Its front corner formed a {{Convert|3|cm||adj=on}} narrow process, pointing upwards. The spine of the thirteenth dorsal vertebra has only been partly preserved, its upper and lower ends having broken off. From its general shape the describers inferred however, that it was about as long as the preceding spine. This would imply that the back edge of the front sail would form a rectangular corner, as the spine of the first sacral vertebra is with about {{Convert|21|cm|}} much lower, creating a sudden hiatus in the profile of the sail. The spine of the second sacral vertebra steeply curved upwards again, joining the {{Convert|39|cm||adj=on|abbr=}} and {{Convert|48|cm||adj=on}} high broad fan-shaped spines of the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|40|cm||adj=on|abbr=}} tall spine of the fifth sacral gradually descended. Unlike in most other theropods, including the sail of ''Suchomimus'', the sacral spines were not fused, nor did they have any extensive contacts. The second and third sacral centra were [[co-ossified]] (fused), with the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]] connecting them still visible. Since only the rearmost two dorsal vertebrae are preserved, it is unknown how far the dorsal sail continued towards the front of the animal's back.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour life reconstruction of a left-facing spinosaur|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]], with unknown regions such as the head and limbs based on relatives]]\n\nThe sacral sail was continued by the spines of the first two caudal vertebrae, which were {{Convert|28.4|cm||adj=|abbr=}} and {{Convert|25.7|cm||adj=|abbr=}} tall respectively. They leaned backwards at a 30 degree angle, and had smooth front and rear edges. The centra of the first two caudals were much broader than long and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#amphicoelous|amphicoelous]] (deeply concave on both ends). The caudal transverse processes were prominent, sturdy, and angled upwards towards the rear of the vertebrae. The transverse processes of the first caudal vertebra, when seen from above, had a [[Sigmoid function|sigmoid]] (or S-shaped) profile. The prespinal and postspinal fossae (bony depressions in front and behind the neural spines) were confined only to above the base of the neural spines. The sides of the first caudal were also deeply hollowed out between the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#Prezygapophyses|prezygapophyses]] (articular surfaces with the neural arch of the preceding vertebra) and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#diapophyses|diapophyses]] (processes on the sides for rib articulation), a condition not observed in other theropods.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Some of the caudal vertebrae also had unusually tall, forwardly-extended prezygapophyses.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe {{Convert|92|cm||adj=on|abbr=}} ilium of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] was blade-like, and longer compared to the pubic bone, which was {{Convert|65|cm||adj=|abbr=}} long, than in any other known large theropod. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#postacetabular process|postacetabular ala]] (front expansion) was much longer than the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#preacetabular process|preacetabular ala]] (rear expansion), the latter had a shelf on its central surface, which formed the middle edge of the preacetabular fossa. Viewed distally (away from the centre of attachment), the lower end of the pubis had L-shape, resembling that of ''Baryonyx''. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic apron|pubic apron]] (expanded lower end of the pubis) features a large [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic foramen|pubic foramen]]. On the hind rim of the pubic bone, two openings, the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#obturator%20foramen|obturator foramen]] and a lower fenestra, were not fully closed, making them into notches. The ischium was {{Convert|49.6|cm||adj=|abbr=}} long, making it shorter in relation to the pubis than in all other known [[Tetanurae|tetanuran]] theropods. Its main body was large and extensive, atypical of the Y-shaped upper ischia of other tetanurans, and bore an oval-shaped obturator foramen in its side. The shaft of the ischium was flattened sideways, and had an unexpanded [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischiadic apron|ischiadic apron]] (as in ''[[Monolophosaurus]]'' and ''[[Sinraptor]]'').<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> The ischium attached to the illium via a peg-and-socket-like articulation, unlike the flat and concave condition seen in ''Baryonyx''. This feature was also present in ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:20130825_Brazil_Rio_de_Janeiro_0144.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Reconstructed skeleton of a spinosaurid holding a pterosaur skeleton in its jaws against a painted backdrop|Reconstructed skeleton of the [[spinosaurine]] ''[[Irritator]]'', mounted at the [[National Museum of Rio de Janeiro]]]]\n\nAllain and his team considered ''Ichthyovenator'' as representing the first unequivocal spinosaurid from Asia.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Though prior spinosaurids had been named from the continent; including ''Siamosaurus'' from the [[Barremian]] [[Sao Khua Formation]] of Thailand, and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' from the [[Aptian]] [[Xinlong Formation]] of China, the authors noted that the validity of these taxa has been debated by palaeontologists, due to them only being confidently known from isolated teeth.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\" /> In 2017, Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Caesar Schultz suggested that these teeth may eventually be attributed to spinosaurids similar to ''Ichthyovenator''.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017-11-06|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966}}</ref> However, American researcher Mickey Mortimer pointed out that a spinosaurid skeleton, possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus'', was excavated from the Thai [[Khok Kruat Formation]] in 2004,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and identified as a definite spinosaur in a 2008 conference abstract by British palaeontologist [[Angela Milner]] and colleagues.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> Mortimer stated that even if teeth are ruled out, confirmed evidence of spinosaurids in Asia was known eight years before ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s description.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2012, ''Ichthyovenator'' was assigned by Allain and colleagues to the Spinosauridae, more precisely to the subfamily [[Baryonychinae]] in a [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] position as the [[sister species]] of a [[clade]] formed by ''Baryonyx'' and ''Suchomimus''. The describers established the following [[autapomorphies]] (unique derived traits) in ''Ichthyovenator'': its dorsal and sacral sinusoidal sail; the thirteenth dorsal neural spine being 410% the length of the centrum, and having a distinct finger-shaped [[Process (anatomy)|process]] on its front upper corner; the broad, expanded tips of the third and fourth sacral spines; the first caudal vertebra's deep prezygapophyseal centrodiapophyseal fossae and S-shaped transverse processes in top view; and the lengthy illium, with its accompanying pubis being comparatively shorter to it than in any other known theropod. Allain and colleagues also identified some anatomical features unique among tetanuran theropods, including the rearmost dorsal ribs articulating with the sternal complex, the pubis's main body having obturator and pubic openings, and the ischium having a foramen on its upper end, as well as a shaft that was flatenned sideways. The shrinking of the pubis and ischium relative to the pelvis has been observed in basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaurs]] and [[Allosauroidea|allosauroids]], which the describers attributed to [[mosaic evolution]], the evolution of certain anatomical traits at different times in separate species.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> \n\n[[File:Spinosauridae_\"Sails\"_Comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Three pairs of illustrated fossil pelvic bones and spinal columns compared to the silhouette of a human to their left, Ichthyovenator's pelvis and vertebrae first from the bottom|Comparison of the [[pelvic region]] and [[Neural spine sail|neural spine sails]] of ''[[Suchomimus]]'', ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', and ''Ichthyovenator'']]\n\nIn 2014, Allain's abstract instead found that ''Ichthyovenator'' was part of the subfamily [[Spinosaurinae]], due to the lack of serrations on its teeth and possession of vertebrae with some similarities to those of ''Sigilmassasaurus''.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2015, a [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] analysis by Evers and colleagues suggested that given the apparent presence of both baryonychine and spinosaurine characteristics in ''Ichthyovenator'', the distinction between the two subfamilies may not be as clear as previously thought.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mortimer hypothesized in 2017 that ''Ichthyovenator'' may not have been a spinosaurid at all, instead possibly being a sail-backed [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] dinosaur closely related to ''[[Concavenator]]''. She thus placed ''Ichthyovenator'' as [[Incertae sedis|''incertae sedis'']] (of uncertain taxonomic affinity) within the clade [[Orionides]], pending description of the new material, which she states will likely confirm ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s spinosaurid identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Ichthyovenatorlaosensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=2017|website=The Theropod Database}}</ref> A 2017 analysis by Sales and Schultz questioned Baryonychinae's validity, citing the [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of Brazilian spinosaurids ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Angaturama'' as suggesting they were possible [[Transitional fossil|transitionary forms]] between the earlier baryonychines and the later spinosaurines. The authors thus indicated that with further research, Baryonychinae may turn out to be a [[paraphyletic]] (unnatural) grouping.<ref name=\":17\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s spinosaurine classification was supported by British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues in 2018, who resolved it as a basal member of the group due to its tall dorsal sail. Their [[cladogram]] can be seen below:<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2018|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1=''[[Siamosaurus suteethorni]]''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1='''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\n\n== Palaeobiology ==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator vertebrae.jpg|thumb|alt=White casts of spinal column with wave-like sail laid out on a dark background in a museum exhibit|Casts of the vertebrae seen from behind]]\n\nThough no skull remains have been found for ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had elongated, low and narrow snouts which allowed them to reach far for food and close their jaws quickly, akin to modern [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]. The tips of their upper and lower jaws fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape that bore long teeth, behind which there was a notch in the upper jaw, this formed a natural trap for prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s straight and unserrated teeth,<ref name=\":0\" /> like those of other spinosaurids, would have been suitable for impaling and capturing small animals and aquatic prey. This type of jaw and tooth morphology, also observed in today's [[gharials]] and other fish-eating predators, has led many palaeontologists to believe that spinosaurids were largely piscivorous (as implied in ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s name).<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> This is also evidenced by ''[[Scheenstia]]'' fish scales discovered in the stomach cavity of one ''Baryonyx'' skeleton,<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=L\u00f3pez-Arbarello|first1=A.|year=2012|title=Phylogenetic Interrelationships of Ginglymodian Fishes (Actinopterygii: Neopterygii)|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=7|issue=7|pages=e39370|bibcode=2012PLoSO...739370L|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0039370|pmc=3394768|pmid=22808031}}</ref> and a ''Spinosaurus'' snout found with a vertebra from the [[sawfish]] ''[[Onchopristis]]'' embedded in it.<ref name=\"dalsassoetal05\">{{cite journal|last=dal Sasso|first=C.|author2=Maganuco, S.|author3=Buffetaut, E.|author4=Mendez, M.A.|year=2005|title=New information on the skull of the enigmatic theropod ''Spinosaurus'', with remarks on its sizes and affinities|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume=25|issue=4|pages=888\u2013896|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2005)025[0888:NIOTSO]2.0.CO;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> A more [[generalist diet]] for spinosaurs has also been proposed, based on fossils such as juvenile ''[[Iguanodon]]'' bones also found in the aforementioned ''Baryonyx'' specimen, and an ''Irritator'' tooth embedded in the vertebrae of a [[pterosaur]]. Thus, it is likely that spinosaurids were also scavengers and hunters of larger prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"milner2007\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Andrew|last2=Kirkland|first2=James|date=September 2007|title=The case for fishing dinosaurs at the St. George Dinosaur Discovery Site at Johnson Farm|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285906225|journal=Utah Geological Survey Notes|volume=39|pages=1\u20133|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sales|first1=M. A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=M. B.|last3=Horn|first3=B. L. D.|last4=de Oliveira|first4=I. A. P.|last5=Schultz|first5=C. L.|last6=Bibi|first6=F.|date=2016|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmc=4734717|pmid=26829315|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref> Though no limb bones are known from ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had well-built arms with enlarged thumb claws, which they likely used to hunt and process prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> \n\n[[File:CrocoLoco-swimming-01.jpg|thumb|left|Three images of a crocodile in the water at different stages of swimming sequence as it propels itself with its tail|''Ichthyovenator'' might have used its tail, which had elongated neural spines, for propulsion through water, similar to [[crocodilians]] such as this [[Nile crocodile]]<ref name=\"arden2018\" />]]\n\nMany possible functions, including [[thermoregulation]] or energy storage, have been proposed for spinosaurid sails.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"JBB97\">{{cite journal|last=Bailey|first=J.B.|year=1997|title=Neural spine elongation in dinosaurs: sailbacks or buffalo-backs?|journal=Journal of Paleontology|volume=71|issue=6|pages=1124\u20131146|doi=10.1017/S0022336000036076|jstor=1306608}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues posited that given the high diversity in neural spine elongation observed in different theropod dinosaurs, as well as [[histological]] research done on the sails of [[Synapsid|synapsids]] (stem mammals), ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sinusoidal sail may have instead been used for [[courtship display]] or [[Species recognition|recognising members of its own species]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In a 2013 blog post, British palaeontologist [[Darren Naish]] considered the latter function unlikely however, favouring the hypothesis of [[sexual selection]] for ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail, since it appears to have evolved on its own, without very close relatives. Though Naish also notes that it is possible these similar relatives have not been discovered yet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/tetrapod-zoology/species-recognition-vs-sexual-selection-in-dinosaurs/|title=Dinosaurs and their exaggerated structures : species recognition aids, or sexual display devices?|last=Naish|first=Darren|date=2013|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nSpinosaurids appear to have had [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles, spending much of their time near or in water, as has been inferred by the high density of their limb bones (which would have made them less [[Buoyancy|buoyant]]), and the [[Isotope ratio|isotope ratios]] of their teeth being closer to those of aquatic animals like turtles, crocodilians, and hippopotamuses than those of other, more terrestrial theropods.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Semiaquatic adaptations seem to have been more developed in spinosaurines than baryonychines.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /><ref name=\"Holtz 1998\">{{Cite journal|last1=Holtz Jr.|first1=T. R.|year=1998|title=Spinosaurs as crocodile mimics|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ac3ac036aeff2608055324d2f1186e8359059706|journal=Science|volume=282|issue=5392|pages=1276\u20131277|doi=10.1126/science.282.5392.1276}}</ref><ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=N.|last2=Sereno|first2=P. C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=C.|last4=Maganuco|first4=S.|last5=Fabri|first5=M.|last6=Martill|first6=D. M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=S.|last8=Myhrvold|first8=N.|last9=Lurino|first9=D. A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20131616|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref> ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s short pubis and ischium relative to its illium, coupled with the elongated neural spines in the tails of early spinosaurs, were suggested by Arden and colleagues in 2018 as indication that spinosaurids may have progressively employed further use of their tails to propel themselves underwater (similarly to crocodilians) as they grew more adapted towards an aquatic lifestyle.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /> A similar, though more extreme shrinkage of the pelvis and hind limbs was observed in ''Spinosaurus'', which appears to have been more semiaquatic than any other known spinosaur species.<ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_20142\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=Nizar|last2=Sereno|first2=Paul C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=Cristiano|last4=Maganuco|first4=Simone|last5=Fabri|first5=Matteo|last6=Martill|first6=David M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=Samir|last8=Myhrvold|first8=Nathan|last9=Lurino|first9=Dawid A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20136|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref>\n\n== Palaeoecology and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Caudal vertebrae Tangvayosaurus hoffeti.jpg|thumb|Fossil tail of a sauropod mounted on the wall of a museum, alongside a skeletal diagram of the dinosaur|[[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|Caudal]] (tail) vertebrae of the [[sauropod]] dinosaur ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'' at the [[Savannakhet]] Dinosaur Museum]]\n\n''Ichthyovenator'' is known from the Barremian to [[Cenomanian]] Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation, and was found in a layer probably dating to the Aptian [[Stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], between 125 to 113 million years ago.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> ''Ichthyovenator'' coexisted with other dinosaurs such as the [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'', and an indeterminate sauropod, [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]], and [[neoceratopsian]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Cavin|first=Lionel|last2=Deesri|first2=Uthumporn|last3=Veran|first3=Monette|last4=Khentavong|first4=Bounsou|last5=Jintasakul|first5=Pratueng|last6=Chanthasit|first6=Phornphen|last7=Allain|first7=Ronan|date=2019-03-04|title=A new Lepisosteiformes (Actinopterygii: Ginglymodi) from the Early Cretaceous of Laos and Thailand, SE Asia|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=17|issue=5|pages=393\u2013407|doi=10.1080/14772019.2018.1426060|issn=1477-2019}}</ref><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\" /> [[Fossil trackway|Trackways]] of sauropod and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as plant remains, are also known from the formation.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\">Weishampel, David B; et al. (2004). \"Dinosaur distribution (Early Cretaceous, Asia).\" In: Weishampel, David B.; Dodson, Peter; and Osm\u00f3lska, Halszka (eds.): The Dinosauria, 2nd, Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 563-570. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}.</ref> Fossils of non-dinosaurian fauna are represented by [[Ray finned fish|ray-finned fish]] like ''[[Lanxangichthys]]''<ref name=\":2\" /> and ''[[Lepidotes]]'', as well as turtles, including ''[[Shachemys]]'', ''[[Xinjiangchelys]]'', and an indeterminate [[carettochelyid]] and [[Trionychidae|trionychid]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Lapparent de Broin|first=France|date=2004-09-01|title=A new Shachemydinae (Chelonii, Cryptodira) from the Lower Cretaceous of Laos: preliminary data|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1631068304000934|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=3|issue=5|pages=387\u2013396|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2004.05.004|issn=1631-0683}}</ref> The [[Trigoniida|trigoniid]] [[Bivalvia|bivalves]] ''[[Trigonioides]]'' and ''[[Plicatounio]]'' have also been recovered from the formation.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation is the lateral equivalent of the neighboring Khok Kruat and [[Phu Phan Formation]]<nowiki/>s in Thailand, the former from which fossils of theropods (including spinosaurids), sauropods, iguanodontians, and freshwater fish have also been recovered.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, and thus preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues suggested such a global distribution may have occurred earlier across [[Pangaea]], prior to its breakup starting in the [[Late Jurassic]], even if Asia became separated first.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In 2019, Spanish palaeontologist Elisabete Malafaia and colleagues also indicated a complex [[biogeographical]] pattern for spinosaurs during the Early Cretaceous, based on anatomical similarities between ''Ichthyovenator'' and ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Theropoda|T.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2154884}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2012]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Laos]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = [[Early Cretaceous]], ([[Aptian]]) {{fossilrange|125|113}}\n| image = Ichthyovenator laosensis.jpg\n| image_caption = Casts of the known [[spinal column]] at the [[National Museum of Nature and Science]], Tokyo. The thirteenth [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] spine and the lower part of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacrum]] have been partially reconstructed.\n| image_alt = White casts of fossil spinal column with a wave-like sail on display at a museum\n| taxon = Ichthyovenator\n| authority = Allain ''et al.'', [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]\n| type_species = {{extinct}}'''''Ichthyovenator laosensis'''''\n| type_species_authority = Allain ''et al.'', 2012\n| subdivision_ranks = \n| subdivision = \n}}\n\n'''''Ichthyovenator''''' is a [[genus]] of [[spinosaurid]] [[theropod]] [[dinosaur]] that lived in what is now Laos during the [[Aptian]] [[Stage (geology)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Period (geologic time)|Period]], sometime between 125 to 113 million years ago. It is known from [[Fossil|fossils]] collected in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]], the first of which were found in 2010, and comprised a partial skeleton without the skull or limbs. This specimen became the [[holotype]] of the new genus and [[species]] '''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''', and was described by French [[palaeontologist]] Ronan Allain and colleagues in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]]. The generic name, meaning \"fish hunter\", refers to its assumed [[piscivorous]] lifestyle, while the specific name alludes to the country of Laos. In 2014, it was announced that further remains from the dig site had been recovered, these fossils included teeth as well as more [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#vertebrae|vertebrae]] (backbones) and a [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubic bone]] from the same individual.\n\nThe holotype specimen is estimated to have been {{convert|8.5 and 10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long and weighed {{convert|2 to 2.4|t|short ton|abbr=}}. ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s teeth were straight and conical, and its neck resembled that of the closely related ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''. Like others in its family, ''Ichthyovenator'' had tall [[neural spines]] forming a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back. Unusually among all other known spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail had a [[sinusoidal]] (wave-like) shape, curving downwards over the hips into two separate sails. The [[pelvic girdle]] was reduced, with the length ratio between the main body of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] and the pubes and ischia being higher than in any other known theropod dinosaurs. The animal was initially thought to belong to the [[Baryonychinae]] [[subfamily]], but more recent analyses place it as a primitive member in the [[Spinosaurinae]].\n\nAs a spinosaur, ''Ichthyovenator'' would have had a long, shallow snout and robust forelimbs. Its diet likely consisted mainly of aquatic prey (hence its etymology). Spinosaurids are also known to have eaten small dinosaurs and [[Pterosaur|pterosaurs]] in addition to fish. ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s conspicuous sail might have been used for [[sexual display]] or [[species recognition]]. Fossil evidence suggests that spinosaurids, especially spinosaurines, were adapted for [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles. The vertebral spines of ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s tail were unusually tall, suggesting that\u2014like in today's [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]\u2014the tail may have aided in swimming. ''Ichthyovenator'' lived alongside [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as [[Bivalvia|bivalves]], fish and turtles.\n\n==Discovery and naming==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_skeletal_%26_size_comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|left|alt=Drawing of fossil rib, backbones and pelvis superimposed on silhouette of a dinosaur|Skeletal diagram with [[holotype]] elements in place, excluding the additional [[fossil]] material announced in 2014]]\n\nThe first [[fossil|fossils]] of ''Ichthyovenator'' were found in 2010 at [[Ban Kalum]], in the [[Gres superieurs Formation|Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation]] of the [[Savannakhet Basin]] in [[Savannakhet Province]], Laos. These bones were recovered from a [[red sandstone]] layer, within a surface area of less than {{convert|2|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} squared. Designated under the specimen number MDS BK10-01 \u2014 15, it consists of a partly [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#articulation|articulated]], well preserved skeleton lacking the skull and limbs, and including the third to last [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dorsals|dorsal]] (back) [[vertebra]], the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#neural spine|neural spine]] of the last dorsal vertebra, five partial [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#sacrals|sacral]] (hip) vertebrae, the first two [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|caudal]] (tail) vertebrae, both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ilium|ilia]] (main hip bone), a right [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubis|pubis]] (pubic bone), both [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischium|ischia]] (lower and rearmost hip bones) and a posterior dorsal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ribs|rib]]. The twelfth dorsal spine is bent sideways when viewed front-to-back due to [[Taphonomy|taphonomic]] distorsion, and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#centrum|centra]] (bodies of the vertebrae) of the sacrals are largely incomplete due to erosion, but preserved all their accompanying spines with their upper edges intact. At the time of ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s description, excavations at the site were still ongoing.<ref name=\"AXRK12\">{{Cite journal|last1=Allain|first1=R.|last2=Xaisanavong|first2=T.|last3=Richir|first3=P.|last4=Khentavong|first4=B.|year=2012|title=The first definitive Asian spinosaurid (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the early cretaceous of Laos|journal=Naturwissenschaften|volume=99|issue=5|pages=369\u2013377|bibcode=2012NW.....99..369A|doi=10.1007/s00114-012-0911-7|pmc=|pmid=22528021}}</ref>\n\nAfter undergoing preparation in 2011, the skeleton was used as the basis, or [[holotype]], for the [[type species]] ''Ichthyovenator laosensis''; named and described in [[2012 in archosaur paleontology|2012]] by French [[palaeontologist]] Ronan Allain, Tiengkham Xeisanavong, Philippe Richir, and Bounsou Khentavong. The [[Generic name (biology)|generic name]] is derived from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] \u1f30\u03c7\u03b8\u03cd\u03c2 (''ichthys''), \"fish\", and [[Latin]] ''venator'', \"hunter\", in reference to its likely [[piscivorous]] (fish-eating) lifestyle. The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] refers to its provenance from Laos.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> ''Ichthyovenator'' is the third [[Spinosauridae|spinosaurid]] named from Asia, after the Thai genus ''[[Siamosaurus]]'' in [[1986 in paleontology|1986]], and the Chinese species \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' in [[2009 in archosaur paleontology|2009]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref>Buffetaut, E.; and Ingevat, R. (1986). Unusual theropod dinosaur teeth from the Upper Jurassic of Phu Wiang, northeastern Thailand. Rev. Paleobiol. 5: 217-220.</ref><ref name=\"EBetal08\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B}}</ref> The latter may represent the same animal as ''Siamosaurus''.''<ref name=\"EBetal082\">{{cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=E.|author2=Suteethorn, V.|author3=Tong, H.|author4=Amiot, R.|year=2008|title=An Early Cretaceous spinosaur theropod from southern China|journal=Geological Magazine|volume=145|issue=5|pages=745\u2013748|bibcode=2008GeoM..145..745B|doi=10.1017/S0016756808005360}}</ref><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Wongko|first=Kamonlak|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Khamha|first3=Suchada|last4=Lauprasert|first4=Komsorn|date=2019-03-31|title=Spinosaurid theropod teeth from the Red Beds of the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) in Northeastern Thailand|url=https://li01.tci-thaijo.org/index.php/tnh/article/view/181194|journal=Tropical Natural History|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=8\u201320|issn=2586-9892}}</ref>''\n\nIn 2014, a [[Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology]] abstract on the genus was published by Allain. This abstract indicated that additional remains from the original individual had been found after an excavation in 2012. These remains include three teeth, the left pubis, and many vertebrae, including a nearly complete neck, the first dorsal vertebra, and seven more caudal vertebrae. However, this abstract has not been formally published as an academic paper as of 2020.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Allain|first=Ronan|date=2014|title=New material of the theropod Ichthyovenator from Ban Kalum type locality (Laos): Implications for the synonymy of Spinosaurus and Sigilmassasaurus and the phylogeny of Spinosauridae|url=http://vertpaleo.org/GlobalPDFS/SVP-2014-Program-and-Abstract-Book-9-18-2014.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology Programs and Abstracts|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Some of these additional vertebrae were compared with those of other spinosaurids in a 2015 paper by German paleontologist Serjoscha Evers and colleagues.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Evers|first=Serjoscha W.|last2=Rauhut|first2=Oliver W.M.|last3=Milner|first3=Angela C.|last4=McFeeters|first4=Bradley|last5=Allain|first5=Ronan|date=2015-10-20|title=A reappraisal of the morphology and systematic position of the theropod dinosaur Sigilmassasaurus from the \"middle\" Cretaceous of Morocco|journal=PeerJ|language=en|volume=3|pages=e1323|doi=10.7717/peerj.1323|pmid=26500829|pmc=4614847|issn=2167-8359}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Spinosauridae_Size_Diagram_by_PaleoGeek_-_Version_2.svg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Silhouettes of five left-facing spinosaurid dinosaurs compared with a blue human to their left, Ichthyovenator in yellow, second from right|Size of various [[spinosaurid]]s (''Ichthyovenator'' in yellow, second from right) compared with a human|alt=]]\n\nIn 2016, American palaeontologist [[Gregory S. Paul]] estimated ''Ichthyovenator'' at {{convert|8.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} in length and weighing {{convert|2|t|short ton|abbr=}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Princeton field guide to dinosaurs|last=S.|first=Paul, Gregory|isbn=9781400883141|edition= 2nd|location=Princeton, N.J.|oclc=954055249|date = 2016-10-25}}</ref> The same year Spanish palaeontologists Rub\u00e9n Molina-P\u00e9rez and Asier Larramendi gave a higher estimation of {{convert|10.5|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} long, {{convert|2.95|m|ft|sp=|abbr=}} tall at the hips, and {{convert|2.4|t|short ton|abbr=}} in weight.<ref>{{Cite book|title=R\u00e9cords y curiosidades de los dinosaurios Ter\u00f3podos y otros dinosauromorfos|last=Molina-P\u00e9rez & Larramendi|publisher=Larousse|year=2016|isbn=|location=Barcelona, Spain|pages=259}}</ref>\n\n''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s teeth were conical, straight, and bore no [[Serration|serrations]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The front carinae (edges) of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#maxilla|maxillary]] and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#dentary|dentary]] teeth were evident on the base of the [[tooth crown]].<ref name=\":1\" /> The front articulating surfaces of ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s rear cervical and front dorsal vertebrae were one and a half times wider than they were high and wider than the length of their centra. They also bore robust front [[Tubercle (bone)|tubercles]] (processes for [[skeletal muscle]] attachment) and lacked inter[[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#zygapophyseal laminae|zygapophyseal laminae]], which resulted in their spinopre- and spinopostzygapophyseal [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#fossae|fossae]] (depressions) having open undersides. The first dorsal vertebra had extensive [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#transverse processes|transverse processes]] (wing-like projections that articulate with the ribs), as well as deep air pockets at the front and back of its base. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#parapophyses|parapophysis]] (a process that articulated with the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#capitulum|capitulum]] of the ribs) of the first dorsal increased in height from the top and bottom, with its underside remaining in contact with the front lower edge of the centrum, this is unlike the condition in most theropods, where the parapophyses shifted towards the top of the vertebra during the transition from cervical to dorsal vertebrae. All of these features were also present in the African spinosaurid ''[[Sigilmassasaurus]]''. ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s mid-cervical vertebrae all had elongate, somewhat wider than tall centra that became progressively shorter towards the rear of the neck, as well as well-developed keels on their bottom surfaces, traits all shared with the spinosaurids ''[[Baryonyx]], [[Suchomimus]]'', ''Sigilmassasaurus'',<ref name=\":1\" /> and ''[[Vallibonavenatrix]]''.<ref name=\":3\">Elisabete Malafaia; Jos\u00e9 Miguel Gasulla; Fernando Escaso; Iv\u00e1n Narv\u00e1ez; Jos\u00e9 Luis Sanz; Francisco Ortega (2019). \"A new spinosaurid theropod (Dinosauria: Megalosauroidea) from the late Barremian of Vallibona, Spain: Implications for spinosaurid diversity in the Early Cretaceous of the Iberian Peninsula\". Cretaceous Research. in press: 104221. {{doi|10.1016/j.cretres.2019.104221}}.</ref> The cervical neural spines of ''Ichthyovenator'' were taller than in ''Sigilmassasaurus'' and ''Baryonyx'', but shared the blade-like shape with those two taxa at the mid-cervicals.<ref name=\":1\" /> The single known dorsal rib, which was found near the twelfth dorsal vertebra, had a head typical of the ribs of other moderately to large-sized theropods. The rib shaft was strongly curved, forming a half circle. The lower end of the rib was slightly expanded both sideways and to the front and back. This condition, which differs from the tapered, pointed tips seen in the ribs of other known theropods, suggests that the rearmost dorsal ribs articulated with the complex of the [[sternum]] (breast bone).<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_65849.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Cast fossil spinal column laid out inside a glass display case at a museum|Casts of the [[Vertebra|vertebrae]] at the [[Mus\u00e9um national d'histoire naturelle|Mus\u00e9um National d'Histoire Naturelle]], Paris|alt=|left]]\n\nLike many other spinosaurids, ''Ichthyovenator'' had a [[Neural spine sail|sail]] on its back and hip, formed by the elongated [[neural spines]] of its vertebrae. Uniquely among known members of the family however, ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail was divided in two over the hip, and had a [[sinusoid]] (wave-like) curvature. This is in contrast to the related genera ''[[Spinosaurus]]'' and ''Suchomimus'' (both of which had continuous sails that rose to a peak before sloping down again), and B''aryonyx'' (which showed a less developed sail, having much lower dorsal spines). ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s preserved dorsal and sacral [[spinal column]], over {{Convert|1|m||abbr=}} long, shows a very high spine on the twelfth dorsal vertebra, representing a crest that rose from the back, and a lower rounded sail that extended from the sacral vertebrae of the hip, with its highest point above the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|54.6|cm||adj=on}} high spine of the twelfth dorsal vertebra widened towards the top, giving it a [[Trapezoid|trapezoidal]] shape, whereas the spines of other spinosaurids were roughly rectangular. It also lacked the forward or backward inclination of ''Spinosaurus''<nowiki/>'s neural spines. Its front corner formed a {{Convert|3|cm||adj=on}} narrow process, pointing upwards. The spine of the thirteenth dorsal vertebra has only been partly preserved, its upper and lower ends having broken off. From its general shape the describers inferred however, that it was about as long as the preceding spine. This would imply that the back edge of the front sail would form a rectangular corner, as the spine of the first sacral vertebra is with about {{Convert|21|cm|}} much lower, creating a sudden hiatus in the profile of the sail. The spine of the second sacral vertebra steeply curved upwards again, joining the {{Convert|39|cm||adj=on|abbr=}} and {{Convert|48|cm||adj=on}} high broad fan-shaped spines of the third and fourth sacrals. The {{Convert|40|cm||adj=on|abbr=}} tall spine of the fifth sacral gradually descended. Unlike in most other theropods, including the sail of ''Suchomimus'', the sacral spines were not fused, nor did they have any extensive contacts. The second and third sacral centra were [[co-ossified]] (fused), with the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]] connecting them still visible. Since only the rearmost two dorsal vertebrae are preserved, it is unknown how far the dorsal sail continued towards the front of the animal's back.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" />\n\n[[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek.jpg|thumb|alt=Colour life reconstruction of a left-facing spinosaur|Speculative life [[Paleoart|restoration]], with unknown regions such as the head and limbs based on relatives]]\n\nThe sacral sail was continued by the spines of the first two caudal vertebrae, which were {{Convert|28.4|cm||adj=|abbr=}} and {{Convert|25.7|cm||adj=|abbr=}} tall respectively. They leaned backwards at a 30 degree angle, and had smooth front and rear edges. The centra of the first two caudals were much broader than long and [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#amphicoelous|amphicoelous]] (deeply concave on both ends). The caudal transverse processes were prominent, sturdy, and angled upwards towards the rear of the vertebrae. The transverse processes of the first caudal vertebra, when seen from above, had a [[Sigmoid function|sigmoid]] (or S-shaped) profile. The prespinal and postspinal fossae (bony depressions in front and behind the neural spines) were confined only to above the base of the neural spines. The sides of the first caudal were also deeply hollowed out between the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#Prezygapophyses|prezygapophyses]] (articular surfaces with the neural arch of the preceding vertebra) and the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#diapophyses|diapophyses]] (processes on the sides for rib articulation), a condition not observed in other theropods.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Some of the caudal vertebrae also had unusually tall, forwardly-extended prezygapophyses.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe {{Convert|92|cm||adj=on|abbr=}} ilium of the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pelvis|pelvis]] was blade-like, and longer compared to the pubic bone, which was {{Convert|65|cm||adj=|abbr=}} long, than in any other known large theropod. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#postacetabular process|postacetabular ala]] (front expansion) was much longer than the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#preacetabular process|preacetabular ala]] (rear expansion), the latter had a shelf on its central surface, which formed the middle edge of the preacetabular fossa. Viewed distally (away from the centre of attachment), the lower end of the pubis had L-shape, resembling that of ''Baryonyx''. The [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic apron|pubic apron]] (expanded lower end of the pubis) features a large [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#pubic foramen|pubic foramen]]. On the hind rim of the pubic bone, two openings, the [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#obturator%20foramen|obturator foramen]] and a lower fenestra, were not fully closed, making them into notches. The ischium was {{Convert|49.6|cm||adj=|abbr=}} long, making it shorter in relation to the pubis than in all other known [[Tetanurae|tetanuran]] theropods. Its main body was large and extensive, atypical of the Y-shaped upper ischia of other tetanurans, and bore an oval-shaped obturator foramen in its side. The shaft of the ischium was flattened sideways, and had an unexpanded [[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#ischiadic apron|ischiadic apron]] (as in ''[[Monolophosaurus]]'' and ''[[Sinraptor]]'').<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> The ischium attached to the illium via a peg-and-socket-like articulation, unlike the flat and concave condition seen in ''Baryonyx''. This feature was also present in ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Classification==\n[[File:20130825_Brazil_Rio_de_Janeiro_0144.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Reconstructed skeleton of a spinosaurid holding a pterosaur skeleton in its jaws against a painted backdrop|Reconstructed skeleton of the [[spinosaurine]] ''[[Irritator]]'', mounted at the [[National Museum of Rio de Janeiro]]]]\n\nAllain and his team considered ''Ichthyovenator'' as representing the first unequivocal spinosaurid from Asia.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> Though prior spinosaurids had been named from the continent; including ''Siamosaurus'' from the [[Barremian]] [[Sao Khua Formation]] of Thailand, and \"''Sinopliosaurus''\" ''fusuiensis'' from the [[Aptian]] [[Xinlong Formation]] of China, the authors noted that the validity of these taxa has been debated by palaeontologists, due to them only being confidently known from isolated teeth.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"hone2017\" /> In 2017, Brazilian palaeontologists Marcos Sales and Caesar Schultz suggested that these teeth may eventually be attributed to spinosaurids similar to ''Ichthyovenator''.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite journal|last=Sales|first=Marcos A. F.|last2=Schultz|first2=Cesar L.|date=2017-11-06|title=Spinosaur taxonomy and evolution of craniodental features: Evidence from Brazil|journal=PLOS One|language=en|volume=12|issue=11|pages=e0187070|bibcode=2017PLoSO..1287070S|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187070|issn=1932-6203|pmc=5673194|pmid=29107966}}</ref> However, American researcher Mickey Mortimer pointed out that a spinosaurid skeleton, possibly belonging to ''Siamosaurus'', was excavated from the Thai [[Khok Kruat Formation]] in 2004,<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://dml.cmnh.org/2012Apr/msg00480.html|title=RE: Ichthyovenator, new spinosaurid from Early Cretaceous of Laos|website=dml.cmnh.org|access-date=2018-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|displayauthors=etal|date=2004|title=Asian spinosaur confirmed|url=http://svpca.org/abstracts.php?yr=2004&abstID=00000000010#abst~00000000010|journal=SVPCA|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> and identified as a definite spinosaur in a 2008 conference abstract by British palaeontologist [[Angela Milner]] and colleagues.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Angela|last2=Buffetaut|first2=Eric|last3=Suteethorn|first3=Varavudh|date=2007|title=A tall-spined spinosaurid theropod from Thailand and the biogeography of spinosaurs|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Future-Past-Meetings/MeetingPdfs/JVP_07.aspx|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume='''27''' (supplement 3)|pages=118A|via=}}</ref> Mortimer stated that even if teeth are ruled out, confirmed evidence of spinosaurids in Asia was known eight years prior to ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s description.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2012, ''Ichthyovenator'' was assigned by Allain and colleagues to the Spinosauridae, more precisely to the subfamily [[Baryonychinae]] in a [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] position as the [[sister species]] of a [[clade]] formed by ''Baryonyx'' and ''Suchomimus''. The describers established the following [[autapomorphies]] (unique derived traits) in ''Ichthyovenator'': its dorsal and sacral sinusoidal sail; the thirteenth dorsal neural spine being 410% the length of the centrum, and having a distinct finger-shaped [[Process (anatomy)|process]] on its front upper corner; the broad, expanded tips of the third and fourth sacral spines; the first caudal vertebra's deep prezygapophyseal centrodiapophyseal fossae and S-shaped transverse processes in top view; and the lengthy illium, with its accompanying pubis being comparatively shorter to it than in any other known theropod. Allain and colleagues also identified some anatomical features unique among tetanuran theropods, including the rearmost dorsal ribs articulating with the sternal complex, the pubis's main body having obturator and pubic openings, and the ischium having a foramen on its upper end, as well as a shaft that was flatenned sideways. The shrinking of the pubis and ischium relative to the pelvis has been observed in basal [[Coelurosauria|coelurosaurs]] and [[Allosauroidea|allosauroids]], which the describers attributed to [[mosaic evolution]], the evolution of certain anatomical traits at different times in separate species.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> \n\n[[File:Spinosauridae_\"Sails\"_Comparison_by_PaleoGeek.png|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Three pairs of illustrated fossil pelvic bones and spinal columns compared to the silhouette of a human to their left, Ichthyovenator's pelvis and vertebrae first from the bottom|Comparison of the [[pelvic region]] and [[Neural spine sail|neural spine sails]] of ''[[Suchomimus]]'', ''[[Spinosaurus]]'', and ''Ichthyovenator'']]\n\nIn 2014, Allain's abstract instead found that ''Ichthyovenator'' was part of the subfamily [[Spinosaurinae]], due to the lack of serrations on its teeth and possession of vertebrae with some similarities to those of ''Sigilmassasaurus''.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2015, a [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] analysis by Evers and colleagues suggested that given the apparent presence of both baryonychine and spinosaurine characteristics in ''Ichthyovenator'', the distinction between the two subfamilies may not be as clear as previously thought.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mortimer hypothesized in 2017 that ''Ichthyovenator'' may not have been a spinosaurid at all, instead possibly being a sail-backed [[Carcharodontosauridae|carcharodontosaurid]] dinosaur closely related to ''[[Concavenator]]''. She thus placed ''Ichthyovenator'' as [[Incertae sedis|''incertae sedis'']] (of uncertain taxonomic affinity) within the clade [[Orionides]], pending description of the new material, which she states will likely confirm ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s spinosaurid identity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theropoddatabase.com/Megalosauroidea.htm#Ichthyovenatorlaosensis|title=Megalosauroidea|last=Mortimer|first=Mickey|date=2017|website=The Theropod Database}}</ref> A 2017 analysis by Sales and Schultz questioned Baryonychinae's validity, citing the [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]] of Brazilian spinosaurids ''[[Irritator]]'' and ''Angaturama'' as suggesting they were possible [[Transitional fossil|transitionary forms]] between the earlier baryonychines and the later spinosaurines. The authors thus indicated that with further research, Baryonychinae may turn out to be a [[paraphyletic]] (unnatural) grouping.<ref name=\":17\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s spinosaurine classification was supported by British palaeontologist Thomas Arden and colleagues in 2018, who resolved it as a basal member of the group due to its tall dorsal sail. Their [[cladogram]] can be seen below:<ref name=\"arden2018\">{{cite journal|last=Arden|first=T.M.S.|last2=Klein|first2=C.G.|last3=Zouhri|first3=S.|last4=Longrich|first4=N.R.|year=2018|title=Aquatic adaptation in the skull of carnivorous dinosaurs (Theropoda: Spinosauridae) and the evolution of aquatic habits in ''Spinosaurus''|journal=Cretaceous Research|volume=93|pages=275\u2013284|doi=10.1016/j.cretres.2018.06.013}}</ref>\n\n{{clade|{{clade\n |1=Praia das Aguncheiras taxon\n |label2=[[Baryonychinae]]\n |2={{clade\n  |1=''[[Baryonyx walkeri]]'' [[File:Baryonyx_walkeri_restoration.jpg|middle|80px]]\n  |2=''[[Suchomimus tenerensis]]'' [[File:Suchomimustenerensis_(Flipped).png|middle|80px]] }}\n |label3=[[Spinosaurinae]]\n |3={{clade\n  |1=''[[Siamosaurus suteethorni]]''\n  |2={{clade\n   |1=Eumeralla taxon\n   |2={{clade\n    |1='''''Ichthyovenator laosensis''''' [[File:Ichthyovenator_laosensis_by_PaleoGeek_(Flipped).jpg|middle|77px]]\n    |2={{clade\n     |1=''[[Irritator challengeri]]'' [[File:Irritator Life Reconstruction.jpg|middle|80 px]]\n     |2=''[[Oxalaia quilombensis]]''\n     |label3=[[Spinosaurini]]\n     |3={{clade\n      |1=Gara Samani taxon\n      |2=''[[Sigilmassasaurus brevicollis]]''\n      |3=''[[Spinosaurus aegyptiacus]]'' [[File:Spinosaurus by Joschua Kn\u00fcppe.png|middle|80 px]] }} }} }} }} }} }}|style=font-size: 85%; line-height:85%;|label1=[[Spinosauridae]]}}\n\n== Palaeobiology ==\n[[File:Ichthyovenator vertebrae.jpg|thumb|alt=White casts of spinal column with wave-like sail laid out on a dark background in a museum exhibit|Casts of the vertebrae seen from behind]]\n\nThough no skull remains have been found for ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had elongated, low and narrow snouts which allowed them to reach far for food and close their jaws quickly, akin to modern [[Crocodilia|crocodilians]]. The tips of their upper and lower jaws fanned out into a [[Rosette (design)|rosette]]-like shape that bore long teeth, behind which there was a notch in the upper jaw, this formed a natural trap for prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s straight and unserrated teeth,<ref name=\":0\" /> like those of other spinosaurids, would have been suitable for impaling and capturing small animals and aquatic prey. This type of jaw and tooth morphology, also observed in today's [[gharials]] and other fish-eating predators, has led many palaeontologists to believe that spinosaurids were largely piscivorous (as implied in ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s name).<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> This is also evidenced by ''[[Scheenstia]]'' fish scales discovered in the stomach cavity of one ''Baryonyx'' skeleton,<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=L\u00f3pez-Arbarello|first1=A.|year=2012|title=Phylogenetic Interrelationships of Ginglymodian Fishes (Actinopterygii: Neopterygii)|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=7|issue=7|pages=e39370|bibcode=2012PLoSO...739370L|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0039370|pmc=3394768|pmid=22808031}}</ref> and a ''Spinosaurus'' snout found with a vertebra from the [[sawfish]] ''[[Onchopristis]]'' embedded in it.<ref name=\"dalsassoetal05\">{{cite journal|last=dal Sasso|first=C.|author2=Maganuco, S.|author3=Buffetaut, E.|author4=Mendez, M.A.|year=2005|title=New information on the skull of the enigmatic theropod ''Spinosaurus'', with remarks on its sizes and affinities|journal=Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology|volume=25|issue=4|pages=888\u2013896|doi=10.1671/0272-4634(2005)025[0888:NIOTSO]2.0.CO;2|issn=0272-4634}}</ref> A more [[generalist diet]] for spinosaurs has also been proposed, based on fossils such as juvenile ''[[Iguanodon]]'' bones also found in the aforementioned ''Baryonyx'' specimen, and an ''Irritator'' tooth embedded in the vertebrae of a [[pterosaur]]. Thus, it is likely that spinosaurids were also scavengers and hunters of larger prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"milner2007\">{{Cite journal|last=Milner|first=Andrew|last2=Kirkland|first2=James|date=September 2007|title=The case for fishing dinosaurs at the St. George Dinosaur Discovery Site at Johnson Farm|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285906225|journal=Utah Geological Survey Notes|volume=39|pages=1\u20133|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Sales|first1=M. A. F.|last2=Lacerda|first2=M. B.|last3=Horn|first3=B. L. D.|last4=de Oliveira|first4=I. A. P.|last5=Schultz|first5=C. L.|last6=Bibi|first6=F.|date=2016|title=The \"\u03c7\" of the Matter: Testing the Relationship between Paleoenvironments and Three Theropod Clades|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=2|pages=e0147031|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147031|pmc=4734717|pmid=26829315|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147031S}}</ref> Though no limb bones are known from ''Ichthyovenator'', all known spinosaurids had well-built arms with enlarged thumb claws, which they likely used to hunt and process prey.<ref name=\"hone2017\">{{Cite journal|last=Hone|first=David William Elliott|last2=Holtz|first2=Thomas Richard|date=June 2017|title=A century of spinosaurs \u2013 a review and revision of the Spinosauridae with comments on their ecology|journal=Acta Geologica Sinica \u2013 English Edition|language=en|volume=91|issue=3|pages=1120\u20131132|doi=10.1111/1755-6724.13328|issn=1000-9515}}</ref> \n\n[[File:CrocoLoco-swimming-01.jpg|thumb|left|Three images of a crocodile in the water at different stages of swimming sequence as it propels itself with its tail|''Ichthyovenator'' might have used its tail, which had elongated neural spines, for propulsion through water, similar to [[crocodilians]] such as this [[Nile crocodile]]<ref name=\"arden2018\" />]]\n\nMany possible functions, including [[thermoregulation]] or energy storage, have been proposed for spinosaurid sails.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /><ref name=\"JBB97\">{{cite journal|last=Bailey|first=J.B.|year=1997|title=Neural spine elongation in dinosaurs: sailbacks or buffalo-backs?|journal=Journal of Paleontology|volume=71|issue=6|pages=1124\u20131146|doi=10.1017/S0022336000036076|jstor=1306608}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues posited that given the high diversity in neural spine elongation observed in different theropod dinosaurs, as well as [[histological]] research done on the sails of [[Synapsid|synapsids]] (stem mammals), ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sinusoidal sail may have instead been used for [[courtship display]] or [[Species recognition|recognising members of its own species]].<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In a 2013 blog post, British palaeontologist [[Darren Naish]] considered the latter function unlikely however, favouring the hypothesis of [[sexual selection]] for ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s sail, since it appears to have evolved on its own, without very close relatives. Though Naish also notes that it is possible these similar relatives have not been discovered yet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/tetrapod-zoology/species-recognition-vs-sexual-selection-in-dinosaurs/|title=Dinosaurs and their exaggerated structures : species recognition aids, or sexual display devices?|last=Naish|first=Darren|date=2013|website=Scientific American Blog Network|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nSpinosaurids appear to have had [[semiaquatic]] lifestyles, spending much of their time near or in water, as has been inferred by the high density of their limb bones (which would have made them less [[Buoyancy|buoyant]]), and the [[Isotope ratio|isotope ratios]] of their teeth being closer to those of aquatic animals like turtles, crocodilians, and hippopotamuses than those of other, more terrestrial theropods.<ref name=\"hone2017\" /> Semiaquatic adaptations seem to have been more developed in spinosaurines than baryonychines.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /><ref name=\"Holtz 1998\">{{Cite journal|last1=Holtz Jr.|first1=T. R.|year=1998|title=Spinosaurs as crocodile mimics|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ac3ac036aeff2608055324d2f1186e8359059706|journal=Science|volume=282|issue=5392|pages=1276\u20131277|doi=10.1126/science.282.5392.1276}}</ref><ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=N.|last2=Sereno|first2=P. C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=C.|last4=Maganuco|first4=S.|last5=Fabri|first5=M.|last6=Martill|first6=D. M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=S.|last8=Myhrvold|first8=N.|last9=Lurino|first9=D. A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20131616|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref> ''Ichthyovenator''<nowiki/>'s short pubis and ischium relative to its illium, coupled with the elongated neural spines in the tails of early spinosaurs, were suggested by Arden and colleagues in 2018 as indication that spinosaurids may have progressively employed further use of their tails to propel themselves underwater (similarly to crocodilians) as they grew more adapted towards an aquatic lifestyle.<ref name=\"arden2018\" /> A similar, though more extreme shrinkage of the pelvis and hind limbs was observed in ''Spinosaurus'', which appears to have been more semiaquatic than any other known spinosaur species.<ref name=\"Ibrahim_et_al_20142\">{{cite journal|last1=Ibrahim|first1=Nizar|last2=Sereno|first2=Paul C.|last3=Dal Sasso|first3=Cristiano|last4=Maganuco|first4=Simone|last5=Fabri|first5=Matteo|last6=Martill|first6=David M.|last7=Zouhri|first7=Samir|last8=Myhrvold|first8=Nathan|last9=Lurino|first9=Dawid A.|date=2014|title=Semiaquatic adaptations in a giant predatory dinosaur|url=https://researchportal.port.ac.uk/portal/en/publications/semiaquatic-adaptations-in-a-giant-predatory-dinosaur(8f11a1ce-3265-4b3b-8c81-6f576856a87f).html|journal=Science|volume=345|issue=6204|pages=1613\u20136|bibcode=2014Sci...345.1613I|doi=10.1126/science.1258750|pmid=25213375}} [http://www.sciencemag.org/content/suppl/2014/09/10/science.1258750.DC1/Ibrahim.SM.pdf Supplementary Information]</ref>\n\n== Palaeoecology and palaeobiogeography ==\n[[File:Caudal vertebrae Tangvayosaurus hoffeti.jpg|thumb|Fossil tail of a sauropod mounted on the wall of a museum, alongside a skeletal diagram of the dinosaur|[[Glossary of dinosaur anatomy#caudals|Caudal]] (tail) vertebrae of the [[sauropod]] dinosaur ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'' at the [[Savannakhet]] Dinosaur Museum]]\n\n''Ichthyovenator'' is known from the Barremian to [[Cenomanian]] Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation, and was found in a layer probably dating to the Aptian [[Stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] of the [[Early Cretaceous]] [[Geological period|Period]], between 125 to 113 million years ago.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> ''Ichthyovenator'' coexisted with other dinosaurs such as the [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] ''[[Tangvayosaurus]]'', and an indeterminate sauropod, [[Iguanodontia|iguanodontian]], and [[neoceratopsian]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Cavin|first=Lionel|last2=Deesri|first2=Uthumporn|last3=Veran|first3=Monette|last4=Khentavong|first4=Bounsou|last5=Jintasakul|first5=Pratueng|last6=Chanthasit|first6=Phornphen|last7=Allain|first7=Ronan|date=2019-03-04|title=A new Lepisosteiformes (Actinopterygii: Ginglymodi) from the Early Cretaceous of Laos and Thailand, SE Asia|journal=Journal of Systematic Palaeontology|volume=17|issue=5|pages=393\u2013407|doi=10.1080/14772019.2018.1426060|issn=1477-2019}}</ref><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\" /> [[Fossil trackway|Trackways]] of sauropod and [[Ornithopoda|ornithopod]] dinosaurs, as well as plant remains, are also known from the formation.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\"cretaceousdistribution\">Weishampel, David B; et al. (2004). \"Dinosaur distribution (Early Cretaceous, Asia).\" In: Weishampel, David B.; Dodson, Peter; and Osm\u00f3lska, Halszka (eds.): The Dinosauria, 2nd, Berkeley: University of California Press. Pp. 563-570. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}.</ref> Fossils of non-dinosaurian fauna are represented by [[Ray finned fish|ray-finned fish]] like ''[[Lanxangichthys]]''<ref name=\":2\" /> and ''[[Lepidotes]]'', as well as turtles, including ''[[Shachemys]]'', ''[[Xinjiangchelys]]'', and an indeterminate [[carettochelyid]] and [[Trionychidae|trionychid]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=de Lapparent de Broin|first=France|date=2004-09-01|title=A new Shachemydinae (Chelonii, Cryptodira) from the Lower Cretaceous of Laos: preliminary data|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1631068304000934|journal=Comptes Rendus Palevol|language=en|volume=3|issue=5|pages=387\u2013396|doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2004.05.004|issn=1631-0683}}</ref> The [[Trigoniida|trigoniid]] [[Bivalvia|bivalves]] ''[[Trigonioides]]'' and ''[[Plicatounio]]'' have also been recovered from the formation.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Gr\u00e8s sup\u00e9rieurs Formation is the lateral equivalent of the neighboring Khok Kruat and [[Phu Phan Formation]]<nowiki/>s in Thailand, the former from which fossils of theropods (including spinosaurids), sauropods, iguanodontians, and freshwater fish have also been recovered.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Buffetaut|first=Eric|last2=Suteethorn|first2=Varavudh|last3=Le Loeuff|first3=Jean|last4=Khansubha|first4=Sasa-On|last5=Tong|first5=Haiyan|last6=Wongko|first6=K|date=2005-01-01|title=The dinosaur fauna from the Khok Kruat Formation (Early Cretaceous) of Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/312976683|journal=Proceedings of the International Conference on Geology, Geotechnology and Mineral Resources of Indochina|pages=575\u2013581}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, American palaeontologist [[Stephen L. Brusatte|Stephen Brusatte]] and colleagues noted that the discovery of spinosaurids in Asia, a family previously known only from Europe, Africa, and South America, suggests faunal interchange between the [[Supercontinent|supercontinents]] [[Laurasia]] (in the north) and [[Gondwana]] (in the south) during the early Late Cretaceous. Though it may also be possible that spinosaurids already had a [[cosmopolitan distribution]] before the Middle Cretaceous, and thus preceding the breakup of Laurasia from Gondwana. However, the authors noted that more evidence is needed to test this hypothesis.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite journal|last=Brusatte|first=Stephen|last2=B. J. Benson|first2=R|last3=Xu|first3=Xing|date=2010-12-10|title=The evolution of large-bodied therood dinosaurs during the Mesozoic in Asia|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/260714806|journal=Journal of Iberian Geology|volume=36|issue=2|pages=275\u2013296|doi=10.5209/rev_JIGE.2010.v36.n2.12}}</ref> In 2012, Allain and colleagues suggested such a global distribution may have occurred earlier across [[Pangaea]], prior to its breakup starting in the [[Late Jurassic]], even if Asia became separated first.<ref name=\"AXRK12\" /> In 2019, Spanish palaeontologist Elisabete Malafaia and colleagues also indicated a complex [[biogeographical]] pattern for spinosaurs during the Early Cretaceous, based on anatomical similarities between ''Ichthyovenator'' and ''Vallibonavenatrix''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Dinosaurs}}\n{{Theropoda|T.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2154884}}\n\n[[Category:Early Cretaceous dinosaurs of Asia]]\n[[Category:Spinosaurids]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 2012]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Laos]]\n", "name_user": "Casliber", "label": "safe", "comment": "prior to --> before (plainer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ichthyovenator"}
{"title_page": "USS Vandegrift (FFG-48)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = [[File:USS Vandegrift (FFG-48).jpg|300px|USS Vandegrift (FFG-48)]]\n| Ship caption = USS ''Vandegrift'' (FFG-48) launching a missile, 15 March 1996.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship country = United States\n| Ship flag = {{USN flag|2015}}\n| Ship name = \n| Ship namesake = [[General (United States)|General]] [[Alexander A. Vandegrift]]\n| Ship owner = \n| Ship operator = \n| Ship registry = \n| Ship route = \n| Ship ordered = \n| Ship awarded = 28 April 1980\n| Ship builder = [[Todd Pacific Shipyards]], [[Seattle, Washington]]\n| Ship original cost = \n| Ship yard number = \n| Ship way number = \n| Ship laid down = 13 October 1981\n| Ship launched = 15 October 1982\n| Ship sponsor = *Ms. Serina N. S. Vandegrift\n*Ms. Courtney A. Vandegrift\n*Ms. Stephanie S. Vandegrift\n*Ms. Daphne L. Vandegrift\n| Ship christened = \n| Ship completed = \n| Ship acquired = \n| Ship commissioned = 24 November 1984\n| Ship recommissioned = \n| Ship decommissioned = 19 February 2015\n| Ship maiden voyage = \n| Ship in service = \n| Ship out of service = \n| Ship renamed = \n| Ship reclassified = \n| Ship refit = \n| Ship struck = 31 March 2015\n| Ship reinstated = \n| Ship homeport = [[Naval Base San Diego]]\n| Ship identification = *[[Hull classification symbol#Surface combatant type|Hull symbol]]: FFG-48\n*{{MMSI Number|368726000}}\n*[[International Code of Signals|Code letters]]: NAAV\n*{{ICS|November}}{{ICS|Alpha}}{{ICS|Alpha}}{{ICS|Victor}}\n| Ship motto = \"Exercitatus, Conservatus, Paratus\"\n| Ship nickname = Vandy\n| Ship honours = \n| Ship honors = \n| Ship captured = \n| Ship fate = \n| Ship status = Stricken, to be sunk as a target\n| Ship notes = \n| Ship badge = [[File:USS Vandegrift (FFG-48) insignia 1984.png|150px]]\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header = \n| Header caption = \n| Ship class = {{sclass-|Oliver Hazard Perry|frigate}}\n| Ship type = \n| Ship tonnage = \n| Ship displacement = {{OHP frigate displacement}}\n| Ship tons burthen = \n| Ship length = {{OHP frigate length}}\n| Ship beam = {{OHP frigate beam}}\n| Ship height = \n| Ship draught = {{OHP frigate draft}}\n| Ship draft = \n| Ship depth = \n| Ship hold depth = \n| Ship decks = \n| Ship deck clearance = \n| Ship ramps = \n| Ship ice class = \n| Ship power = \n| Ship propulsion = {{OHP frigate propulsion}}\n| Ship sail plan = \n| Ship speed = {{OHP frigate speed}}\n| Ship range = {{OHP frigate range}}\n| Ship endurance = \n| Ship test depth = \n| Ship boats = \n| Ship capacity = \n| Ship troops = \n| Ship complement = {{OHP frigate complement}}\n| Ship crew = \n| Ship time to activate = \n| Ship sensors = {{OHP frigate sensors}}\n| Ship EW = [[AN/SLQ-32]]\n| Ship armament = {{OHP frigate armament}}\n| Ship armour = \n| Ship armor = \n| Ship aircraft = 2 \u00d7 [[SH-60 Seahawk|SH-60 LAMPS III]] helicopters\n| Ship aircraft facilities = {{OHP frigate aircraft facilities}}\n| Ship notes = \n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Vandegrift'' (FFG-48)''' was an {{Sclass-|Oliver Hazard Perry|frigate}} of the [[United States Navy]]. The ship was named for General [[Alexander A. Vandegrift]] (1887\u20131973), 18th [[Commandant of the Marine Corps]].\n\n''Vandegrift'' was laid down on 13 October 1981 at [[Todd Pacific Shipyards]], [[Seattle, Washington]].  She was launched on 15 October 1982<ref name=History/> \u2013 cosponsored by Ms. Courtney A. Vandegrift, Ms. Stephanie S. Vandegrift, and Ms. Daphne L. Vandegrift, three of the late Gen. Vandegrift\u2019s granddaughters, and Ms. Serina N. S. Vandegrift, his great granddaughter.<ref name=\"DANFS\">{{cite web | url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/v/vandegrift--ffg-48-.html | title=Vandegrift (FFG-48) | publisher=Naval History and Heritage Command | date=19 August 2015 | accessdate=6 January 2016 | author=Evans, Mark L.}}</ref><ref name=Serina>{{cite web|last1=USS Vandegrift Public Affairs|title=Ship\u2019s Sponsor Returns after 31 Years for Visit|url=http://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/ffg48/Pages/ShipsSponsorReturnsafter31YearsforVisit.aspx#.VU96KvlVhBc|publisher=Commander Naval Surface Force, U.S. Pacific Fleet|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>  ''Vandegrift'' was [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 24 November 1984;  Commander Clinton James Coneway in command;<ref name=\"DANFS\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Distinguished guests attend the commissioning of the guided missile frigate USS ''Vandegrift'' (FFG 48)|url=https://research.archives.gov/description/6395761|website=Records of the Office of the Secretary of Defense, 1921\u20132008|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> and, after over 30 years of service, [[ship decommissioning|decommissioned]] on 19 February 2015.<ref name=History/>\n\n== 1980s ==\n\nThe ship's inaugural cruise began on 5 January 1987. During the course of this around-the-world cruise, she sailed three oceans, seven seas and visited four continents. The [[plank owner]]s also crossed the [[International Date Line]], [[Equator]], [[Greenwich Meridian]], and sailed through the [[Strait of Gibraltar]], and the [[Suez Canal|Suez]] and [[Panama Canal]]s. ''Vandegrift'' conducted operations with {{USS|Kitty Hawk|CV-63|6}} in the [[Arabian Sea]] and Indian Ocean.  These operations were highlighted by an air and sea power demonstration for president [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]] of Pakistan. Port visits included [[Pearl Harbor]]; [[U.S. Naval Base Subic Bay|Subic Bay]] in the Republic of the Philippines; [[Karachi]], Pakistan; [[Mombasa]], Kenya; [[Maxime]], France; [[Roosevelt Roads]], Puerto Rico; and [[St. Croix]] and [[St. Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands]].  ''Vandegrift'' returned home to [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]] in June 1987.<ref name=History>{{cite web |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121004074159/http://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/ffg48/Pages/ourship.aspx |archivedate= 4 October 2012 |url= http://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/FFG48/Pages/ourship.aspx |title= Our History |website= USS Vandegrift FFG-48 |accessdate= 21 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe ship's second deployment began in June 1988, returning her to operations in the [[Persian Gulf]] shortly after the cease-fire between Iran and Iraq.  ''Vandegrift'''s mission while on patrol in the northern [[Persian Gulf]] focused on providing protection and logistic support for joint forces in the area.  ''Vandegrift'' also participated in numerous [[Operation Earnest Will|Earnest Will]] missions, escorting U.S. and reflagged Kuwaiti [[Tanker (ship)|tankers]]. Port visits included Pearl Harbor; Subic Bay, Republic of the Philippines; Bahrain; [[Pattaya Beach]], Thailand and Hong Kong. ''Vandegrift'' returned home in December 1988.<ref name=History/>\n\n== 1990s ==\n\nThe ship's third deployment to the Persian Gulf began in March 1990. ''Vandegrift'' patrolled the Northern Persian Gulf and conducted Earnest Will escort missions. As the senior ship on station in the Persian Gulf during the invasion of Kuwait, ''Vandegrift'' served as the Anti-Air Warfare Commander and Electronic Warfare Coordinator. ''Vandegrift'' participated in [[Gulf War#Operation Desert Shield|Operation Desert Shield]]'s Maritime Interception Operations with units from United Kingdom, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and France. Ports of call included Pearl Harbor; Subic Bay; [[Phuket city|Phuket]], Thailand; Singapore and Hong Kong. ''Vandegrift'' returned home after an extended deployment in October 1990.<ref name=History/>\n\nOn 22 April 1992, ''Vandegrift'' began her fourth deployment to the Persian Gulf. ''Vandegrift'' participated in exercises with India, Qatar and Pakistan,\nhelping to strengthen U.S. relations in that area. Ports of call included [[Doha]], Qatar; [[Dubai]], [[Jebel Ali]] and [[Abu Dhabi]], United Arab Emirates; Karachi, Pakistan; Phuket, Thailand; [[Goa]], India; Bahrain; Hong Kong; Singapore and [[Guam]], and earned the [[Chief of Naval Operations]] LAMPS [[Helicopter Safety Award]].<ref name=History/> ''Vandegrift'' returned home on 22 October 1992.\n\nFrom 1 January to 3 February 1993, ''Vandegrift'' was homeported in Long Beach, CA.<ref>Vandegrift Command History 1993</ref> Due to extensive shipyard time and the closing of [[Naval Station Long Beach]], from 3 February 1993, ''Vandegrift'' was homeported in San Diego, CA. From 1 January to 2 April, ''Vandegrift'' was commanded by Commander Theodore L. Kaye. From 2 April to 31 December, ''Vandegrift'' was commanded by Commander David C. Harrison. From 1 January to 31 July, Vandegrift was under the administrative command of Commander, [[Destroyer Squadron 9]]. From 31 July to 31 December, ''Vandegrift'' was under the administrative command of Commander, [[Destroyer Squadron 33]].{{cn|date= February 2015|reason=majority of paragraph not in sources provided}}\n\nThe ship earned the [[Commander, Naval Surface Forces Pacific|COMNAVSURFPAC]] Food Service Award in March 1994. The fifth deployment to the Persian Gulf began on 25 October 1994. ''Vandegrift'''s mission was the enforcement of UN sanctions against Iraq in the Northern Persian Gulf. The most memorable event was conducting a non-permissive boarding of a sanctions violator on 25 December.<ref name=History/> During the return transit, ''Vandegrift'' played host to a major diplomatic reception in [[Muscat, Oman]], to better diplomatic relations. Ports of call included [[Sasebo, Nagasaki|Sasebo]], Japan; [[Manila]], Republic of the Philippines; Jebel Ali, United Arab Emirates; Bahrain; Singapore and Hong Kong. ''Vandegrift'' returned home on 25 April 1995.<ref name=History/>\n\nIn 1998, the ship shifted homeports to [[Yokosuka, Japan]].<ref name=History/>  Between 1998 and 2000, the ship performed numerous cruises to South Korea, Thailand, China,  Singapore, the [[Marianas Islands]], Australia, and conducted a [[RIMPAC]] deployment to Hawaii in company with the Japanese Navy.  In 1999, the vessel was visited by [[Admiral]] [[Jay L. Johnson]], then Chief of Naval Operations (CNO).\n\n== 2000s ==\nIn January 2003, ''Vandegrift'' deployed for the eighth time to the Persian Gulf in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom/Operation Enduring Freedom. Assigned escort operations in the Straits of Hormuz, ''Vandegrift'' conducted over 180 transits, safely escorting over 78 vessels carrying over 1 million tons of hardware in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom. Additionally, ''Vandegrift'' seized two Iraqi mine-laying vessels in the Southern Persian Gulf and was credited with protecting the Coalition\u2019s flank from planned mine-laying operations.<ref name=History/>\n\nOn 19 November 2003, the frigate became the first US warship to enter Vietnamese waters since April 1975.<ref>{{cite news |last=Warth |first=Gary |date=19 February 2015 |title=Bittersweet farewell to Vandegrift frigate |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2015/feb/19/vandegrift-frigate-decommission-navy/ |newspaper=San Diego Union Tribune |access-date=19 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe ship's decorations include the [[Meritorious Unit Commendation]], [[National Defense Service Medal]], [[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]]; [[Southwest Asia Service Medal]], and five [[Sea Service Ribbon]]s.<ref name=History/>\n\nAs of 2006, ''Vandegrift'' was based in [[San Diego]], California.<ref name=History/>\n\n== 2010s ==\n\nIn March 2014, Eric and Charlotte Kauffman, and their daughters, three-year-old Cora and one-year-old Lyra, set sail from San Diego, California, to [[circumnavigate]] the globe in their 36-foot sailboat, ''Rebel Heart''. Lyra fell sick, however, and on 3 April the family sent a distress call, from a position hundreds of miles off the Mexican coast. A [[Lockheed MC-130#MC-130P Combat Shadow|Lockheed MC-130P Combat Shadow]] of the [[California Air National Guard]]\u2019s [[130th Rescue Squadron]], [[129th Rescue Wing]], flew out to the area and four [[pararescuemen]] jumped into the water, climbed on board the sailboat and medically treated and stabilized Lyra. ''Vandegrift'' reached the area on 5 April, and at about 0800 the following morning, she lowered a team in a [[rigid hull inflatable boat]] (RHIB), and the sailors brought the family and the pararescuemen on board the frigate. The rescuers provided the Kauffmans with food, water, and medical assistance, but instructed the castaways that because of the limited room on board the RHIB and ship, they could only retrieve three bags of their personal belongings in a single trip before ''Vandegrift'' sank ''Rebel Heart'' as a hazard to navigation. Some of the Kauffmans' neighbors in the San Diego area therefore raised funds and donated goods to help the family recover from their ordeal when they returned ashore.<ref name=\"DANFS\" /><ref>{{cite episode |url= http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/525/call-for-help |title= Prologue |series= Call for Help |episode= 525 |website= WBEZ |first= Ira |last= Glass |date= 9 May 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/USS-Vandegrift-San-Diego-Return-Baby-Rescue-Sea-Kaufman--254568371.html |title= Baby Rescued at Sea Returns to San Diego |first= R. |last= Stickney |website= NBC San Diego |date= 10 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1 May to 28 November 2012 ''Vandegrift ''participated in a [[Cooperation Afloat Readiness and Training|CARAT]] deployment, visiting Russia, Japan, Cambodia, Malaysia, and other Pacific nations.\n\n''Vandegrift'' returned from its final deployment on 12 December 2014, where she operated in the U.S. Naval Forces Southern Command/U.S. 4th Fleet area of responsibility (AOR). During this final deployment, ''Vandegrift'' was part of the counter-transnational organized crime (C-TOC) mission [[Operation Martillo]], a joint, combined operation involving the U.S. and 14 European and Western Hemisphere partner nations, that targets illicit trafficking routes in the waters off Central America. While participating in Operation Martillo, ''Vandegrift'' intercepted approximately 8,996&nbsp;kg of cocaine. The ship also participated in three community relations (COMREL) projects in [[Panama City]] during which 36 sailors helped build a workshop for the blind, assist an outreach group in refurbishing their building and spent time with children in the Aid for AIDS community.\n\nAfter returning from her last deployment, the crew began to make preparations for decommissioning. After over 30 years of service, ''Vandegrift'' was decommissioned on 19 February 2015 at Naval Base San Diego.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2015/02/23/uss-vandegrift-bids-farewell-after-30-years-of-service.html|title=USS Vandergrift Decommissioned At Naval Base San Diego|first=|date=19 February 2015|work=|newspaper=XETV|location=San Diego|agency=City News Service|access-date=19 February 2015|via=|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->}}</ref>\n\nShe will be sunk as a target in a future SINKEX as a part of a future RIMPAC or Valiant Shield training exercise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.navy.mil/strategic/PB20_Shipbuilding_Plan.pdf|title=Report to Congress on the Annual Long-Range Plan for Construction of Naval Vessels for Fiscal Year 2020|website=Navy|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n;2012 Russian incident\nDuring the ''Vandegrift's'' 2012 deployment they received negative international media attention during their three-day stop to Vladivostok, Russia. While a lot of the exact details of the incident have yet to be published, it has been stated that many of the personal conduct policies normally upheld by the military had been violated. \n\nAs a result, most of the chain of command was removed, including the Commanding Officer, Executive Officer, the Chief Engineer, and the Operations Officer. \n\nThe Navy also followed suite in explaining the reprimands because of, \"''personal conduct involving alcohol,\"'' and ''\"due to loss of confidence after demonstrating poor leadership and failure to ensure the proper conduct of this wardroom (''Wardroom is how the military refers to officers) ''officers during a September port visit in Vladivostok, Russia\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/news/uss-vandegrift-commander-fired-947/|title=Drunken sailors: US frigate commander fired over crew's Russian bender|website=RT International|language=en|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{USNAVY|article=Our Ship|url=http://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/FFG48/Pages/ourship.aspx}}\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/v/vandegrift--ffg-48-.html}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|USS Vandegrift (FFG-48)}}\n*[http://www.public.navy.mil/surfor/ffg48 USS ''Vandegrift'' homepage]\n*{{navsource|07/0748|USS Vandegrift (FFG-48)}}\n*[http://www.navysite.de/ffg/FFG48.HTM  navysite.de: USS ''Vandegrift'']\n*[http://www.maritimequest.com/warship_directory/us_navy_pages/frigates/pages/vandegrift_ffg48_page_1.htm MaritimeQuest USS Vandegrift FFG-48 pages]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_depth/photo_gallery/3283263.stm In pictures: US frigate's historic Vietnam visit (BBC News)]\n*[http://www.history.navy.mil/research/archives/command-operations-reports/ships/v/vandergrift-ffg-48.html USS ''Vandegrift'' command histories] \n\n\n\n{{Oliver Hazard Perry class frigate}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vandegrift (Ffg-48)}}\n[[Category:1982 ships]]\n[[Category:Oliver Hazard Perry-class frigates of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Seattle]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image = [[File:USS Vandegrift (FFG-48).jpg|300px|USS Vandegrift (FFG-48)]]\n| Ship caption = USS ''Vandegrift'' (FFG-48) launching a missile, 15 March 1996.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header = \n| Ship country = United States\n| Ship flag = {{US