{"title_page": "Hulu", "text_new": "{{for|the Chinese animated series|Calabash Brothers}}\n{{short description|American provider of on-demand streaming media}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name = Hulu, LLC\n| logo = Hulu Logo.svg\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| collapsible = yes\n| collapsetext = Screenshot\n| screenshot = Hulu screenshot.png\n| screenshot_size = \n| screenshot_alt = \n| caption = Hulu website screenshot\n| company_type = [[Joint venture]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|2007|10|29}}\n| launched = {{Start date|2007|10|29}}<br />(Hulu Syndication Network)<ref name=\"pr_launch\" /><br />(Hulu.com destination site)<ref name=\"pr_launch\" />\n| predecessor = \n| location = 2500 Broadway 2nd Floor, [[Santa Monica, California]]\n| country = United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/company/3276470Z:US|title=Hulu LLC|website=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n| area_served = United States<br />Japan\n| founder = \n| CEO = \n| key_people = Kelly Campbell ([[President (corporate title)|president]])\n| products = {{flatlist|\n* [[Streaming media]]\n* [[Video on demand]]\n* [[Video on demand|Television on demand]]\n}}\n| services = {{flatlist|\n* [[Television production]]\n* [[Digital distribution]]\n* [[Web syndication]]\n}}\n| revenue = {{increase}} $1 billion (2013)<ref>{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Rogowsky|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markrogowsky/2013/12/19/hulus-billion-dollar-milestone-a-sign-of-just-how-far-behind-netflix-it-has-fallen|title=Hulu's Billion-Dollar Milestone: A Sign Of Just How Far Behind Netflix It Has Fallen|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130092127/https://www.forbes.com/sites/markrogowsky/2013/12/19/hulus-billion-dollar-milestone-a-sign-of-just-how-far-behind-netflix-it-has-fallen|archive-date=2018-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| international = \n| parent = [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]]\n| owners = '''United States:''' {{Plainlist|\n* [[The Walt Disney Company]]<br>(67% equity; full control)<ref name=\"Disney\" />\n* [[Comcast Corporation]]<br>(33% equity; silent partner)<br>'''Japan:'''\n[[Nippon TV]]  ([[Brand licensing|branding]] licensed by Hulu, LLC) \n}}\n| url = {{URL|https://www.hulu.com/}} (US)<br /> {{URL|https://www.hulu.jp/}} (Japan)\n| alexa = {{Increase}} 212 {{small|{{nowrap|(Global, {{as of|2020|01|14|alt=January 2020}})}}}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/hulu.com|title=hulu.com Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic - Alexa|website=www.alexa.com|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n| website_type = {{plainlist|\n* [[Entertainment]]\n* [[Over-the-top media services|OTT platform]]}}\n| advertising = Most plans ad-supported.\n| registration = Required\n| users = {{Unbulleted list|\n* {{increase}}30.4 million {{asof|2020|2|3|df=US}}\n* {{increase}}3.2 million (Hulu with Live TV) {{asof|2020|2|3|df=US}}<ref name=\"HuluSubsQ12020\"/>\n}}\n| language = English<br>Japanese\n| current_status = <!--- Active --->\n}}\n\n'''Hulu''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|u\u02d0|l|u\u02d0}}) is a U.S.-based [[subscription video on demand]] service fully controlled and majority-owned by [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]], a business segment of [[The Walt Disney Company]], with [[NBCUniversal]], owned by [[Comcast]], as an [[Equity (finance)|equity]] stakeholder. \n\nThe service was initially established as a [[joint venture]] between [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] and [[NBCUniversal|NBC Universal]], [[Providence Equity Partners]], and later [[The Walt Disney Company]], serving as an aggregation of recent episodes of television series from their respective [[television network]]s. In 2010, Hulu launched a subscription service, initially [[brand]]ed as ''Hulu Plus'', which featured full seasons of programs from the companies and other partners, and [[broadcast delay|undelayed]] access to new episodes. In 2017, the company launched ''Hulu with Live TV''\u2014an [[Over-the-top media services|over-the-top]] [[IPTV]] service featuring [[linear television]] channels. Time Warner (now [[WarnerMedia]]) later held a stake in the service. As of the first quarter of 2020, Hulu had 30.4 million subscribers.<ref name=\"HuluSubsQ12020\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/disney-plus-reaches-26-5-million-subscribers-1203492187/|title=Disney Plus Reaches 28.6 Million Subscribers, Hulu Hits 30.4 Million|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | first = Cynthia|last=Littleton|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Disney [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquired 21st Century Fox]], giving it a 60% [[controlling interest|majority stake]] in Hulu. [[AT&T]] (which acquired Time Warner in 2018) sold back its roughly 10% stake the following month. Comcast, the only other shareholder, announced on May 14, 2019,    that it had agreed to cede its control to Disney, and reached an agreement for Disney to purchase its 33% stake in the company as early as 2024. Hulu will be operated as a bridge brand alongside Disney's fellow OTT ventures [[Disney+]] and [[ESPN+]], with Hulu positioned as its streaming brand for general entertainment outside of Disney's [[family-friendly|family-oriented]] movies, shows and properties.<ref name=\"DisneyIstakingfullcontrolofHulu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/14/media/disney-buys-comcast-hulu-ownership/index.html|title=Disney is taking full control of Hulu|work=CNN|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=July 24, 2019|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie}}</ref>\n\n== Name ==\nThe name Hulu comes from two [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] words, ''h\u00fal\u00fa'' ([[wikt:\u846b\u82a6|\u846b\u82a6]]/[[wikt:\u846b\u8606|\u846b\u8606]]), \"[[calabash]]; bottle gourd\", and ''h\u00f9l\u00f9'' ([[wikt:\u4e92\u5f55|\u4e92\u5f55]]/[[wikt:\u4e92\u9304|\u4e92\u9304]]), \"interactive recording\". The company blog explains:\n<blockquote>In Mandarin, ''Hulu'' has two interesting meanings, each highly relevant to our mission. The primary meaning interested us because it is used in an ancient Chinese proverb that describes the Hulu as the holder of precious things. It literally translates to \"gourd,\" and in ancient times, the Hulu was hollowed out and used to hold precious things. The secondary meaning is \"interactive recording\". We saw both definitions as appropriate bookends and highly relevant to the mission of Hulu.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kilar|first=Jason|title=What's in a Name?|date=2008-05-14|url=http://blog.hulu.com/2008/05/13/meaning-of-hulu/|accessdate=2010-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717203005/http://blog.hulu.com/2008/05/13/meaning-of-hulu/|archive-date=2011-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== History ==\nKey executives instrumental in the founding of Hulu include Bruce Campbell,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://corporate.discovery.com/our-company/leadership/|title=Leadership \u2013 Discovery Communications, Inc.|website=corporate.discovery.com|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529041516/https://corporate.discovery.com/our-company/leadership/|archive-date=2016-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> Peter Chernin,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/peter-chernin-offers-500m-hulu-84381/|title=Peter Chernin Offers $500M for Hulu|date=2013-04-05|website=TheWrap|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020070543/http://www.thewrap.com/peter-chernin-offers-500m-hulu-84381/|archive-date=2016-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref> JB Perrette,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/09/mf-hulu/|title=Free, Legal and Online: Why Hulu Is the New Way to Watch TV|journal=WIRED|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527061240/http://www.wired.com/2008/09/mf-hulu/|archive-date=2016-05-27|url-status=live|date=2008-09-22}}</ref> Michael Lang,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/01/we-happy-miramax-deal-brings-hundreds-of-movies-to-hulu-hulu-plus/|title=We Happy? Miramax Deal Brings Hundreds Of Movies To Hulu Plus (And To Hulu)|last=Wauters|first=Robin|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503174249/http://techcrunch.com/2011/06/01/we-happy-miramax-deal-brings-hundreds-of-movies-to-hulu-hulu-plus/|archive-date=2016-05-03|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Beth Comstock]] and [[Jason Kilar]]. The venture was announced in March 2006 with [[AOL]], [[NBC Universal]] (now [[Comcast]]), [[Facebook]], [[MSN]], [[Myspace]], and [[Yahoo!]] planned as \"initial distribution partners\". Jason Kilar was named Hulu CEO in late 2007.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070322005690/en/NBC-Universal-News-Corp.-Announce-Deal-Internet |title=NBC Universal and News Corp. Announce Deal with Internet Leaders AOL, MSN, MySpace And Yahoo! to Create a Premium Online Video Site with Unprecedented Reach |publisher=Business Wire |accessdate=12 December 2017 |date=22 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101212907/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070322005690/en/NBC-Universal-News-Corp.-Announce-Deal-Internet |archive-date=1 January 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"foe\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-still-on-top/newsanalysis/technet/10346071.html |title=Google's Still on Top |accessdate=2007-08-29 |date=2007-03-22 |author=Nat Worden |work=[[TheStreet.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930180547/http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-still-on-top/newsanalysis/technet/10346071.html |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref>\n\nThe name ''Hulu'' was chosen in late August 2007, when the website went live, with an announcement only and no content. It invited users to leave their email addresses for the upcoming [[Software release life cycle|beta test]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-new-foe-hulu/newsanalysis/mediaentertainment/10376991.html |title=Google's New Foe: Hulu |accessdate=2007-08-29 |date=2007-08-29 |author=Nat Worden |work=[[TheStreet.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904013423/http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-new-foe-hulu/newsanalysis/mediaentertainment/10376991.html |archivedate=2007-09-04 }}</ref> In October 2007, Hulu began the private beta testing by invitation, and later allowed users to invite friends.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20071028005079/en/Hulu-Debuts-Private-Beta-Distribution-Partners-AOL |title=Hulu Debuts via Private Beta and on Distribution Partners AOL, Comcast, MSN, MySpace and Yahoo! |publisher=Business Wire |accessdate=11 December 2017 |date=20 October 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222050812/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20071028005079/en/Hulu-Debuts-Private-Beta-Distribution-Partners-AOL |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Hulu launched for public access in the United States on March 12, 2008.<ref name=\"pr_launch\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080312005454/en/Hulu.com-Opens-Public-Offers-Free-Streams-Hit\n|title=Hulu.com Opens to Public, Offers Free Streams of Hit TV Shows, Movies and Clips from More Than 50 Providers Including FOX, NBC Universal, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Studios Inc. and Sony Pictures Television |publisher=Business Wire\n|accessdate=11 December 2017 |date=12 March 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051815/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080312005454/en/Hulu.com-Opens-Public-Offers-Free-Streams-Hit |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The first product to launch was the HULU Syndication network, which was designed and developed by the NBC Universal team from New York, on October 29, 2007, followed by the Hulu.com destinations site.\n\nHulu began an advertising campaign during NBC's broadcast of [[Super Bowl XLIII]] with an initial ad starring [[Alec Baldwin]] titled \"Alec in Huluwood\".<ref name=\"TV Ads\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hulu.com/watch/58538/hulu-tv-ads-alec-in-huluwood |title= Hulu TV Ads: Alec in Huluwood |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work= Hulu |publisher= Hulu |accessdate= May 10, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090508080115/http://www.hulu.com/watch/58538/hulu-tv-ads-alec-in-huluwood |archive-date= 2009-05-08 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The ad intended to humorously reveal \"the shocking secret behind Hulu\", portraying the site as being an \"evil plot to destroy the world\" by suggesting that Baldwin is really an alien in disguise.<ref name=\"hulu-shock\">{{cite web |url= http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-10150197-36.html |title= Hulu to shock the world with Super Bowl ad |last= McCarthy |first= Caroline |date= January 26, 2009 |publisher= CNET News |accessdate= February 2, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090806043548/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-10150197-36.html |archive-date= August 6, 2009 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Advertisements have since aired featuring [[Eliza Dushku]], [[Seth MacFarlane]], [[Denis Leary]], and [[Will Arnett]].\n\nIn July 2007, [[Providence Equity Partners]], the owner of [[Newport Television]], became one of the earliest \"outside\" investors by purchasing a 10 percent stake in the company for [[United States dollar|US$]]100 million [[equity (finance)|equity investment]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cable360.net/competition/web/25376.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120906054018/http://www.cable360.net/competition/web/25376.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 6, 2012 |title=NBC and Fox Jump Through Hulu Hoop |accessdate=2007-08-29 |date=August 29, 2006 |first=Shirley |last=Brady |work=Cable360.net }}</ref> before the company was known as \"Hulu\".<ref name=\"SoldStake\" /> With its investment came a seat on the board of directors, where Providence was said to act as an \"independent voice on the board\".<ref name=\"SoldStake\" /> In April 2009, [[The Walt Disney Company]] joined the Hulu consortium as a stakeholder, with plans to offer content from [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and [[Disney Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-us-disney-hulu-043009-2009apr30-story.html|title=Disney joins NBC and News Corp. with Hulu stake|date=2009-04-30|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.multichannel.com/news/disney-takes-stake-hulu-video-site-298847|title=Disney Takes Stake In Hulu Video Site|last=Spangler|first=Todd|website=Multichannel|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/disney-signs-onto-hulu/|title=Disney signs onto Hulu|last=McCarthy|first=Caroline|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Providence sold its 10 percent stake to \"Hulu's media owners\" and ceased participation in the board.<ref name=\"SoldStake\">{{cite news|url = https://techcrunch.com/2012/10/12/providence-equity-sells-its-stake-in-hulu/|title = It's Done: Early Hulu Investor Providence Equity Partners Has Sold Its Stake For $200M|accessdate = 2012-05-12|date = May 12, 2012|first = Ryan|last = Lawler|work = techcrunch.com|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121013055831/http://techcrunch.com/2012/10/12/providence-equity-sells-its-stake-in-hulu/|archive-date = October 13, 2012|url-status = live|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2010, Hulu chief executive Jason Kilar said the service had made a profit in two quarters and that the company could top $100 million in revenue by summer 2010, more than its income for all of 2009. [[ComScore]] says monthly video streams reached 903 million in January 2010, over three times the figure for a year earlier,<ref name=\"Stelter\">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2011517934_bthulufuture05.html?syndication=rss|title=Hulu, the online-video hub, contemplates its future|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|last2=Stone|first2=Brad|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2010-04-05|accessdate=2010-04-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622021349/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2011517934_bthulufuture05.html?syndication=rss|archive-date=2011-06-22|url-status=live}}</ref> and second only to [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"Grotticelli\">{{cite news|url=http://broadcastengineering.com/news/hulu-plans-subscripiton-service-0426/ |title=Hulu plans subscription service |last=Grotticelli |first=Michael |work=Broadcast Engineering |date=2010-04-26 |accessdate=2010-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704080501/http://broadcastengineering.com/news/hulu-plans-subscripiton-service-0426/ |archivedate=2010-07-04 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 16, 2010, a report revealed that Hulu was planning an [[initial public offering]] (IPO) which could value the company at more than $2 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20100816/tc_nm/us_hulu_ipo|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820123350/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20100816/tc_nm/us_hulu_ipo|url-status=dead|title=U.S. video viewing site Hulu plans an IPO: report|archivedate=August 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Dealbook |url=http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/16/hulu-is-said-to-be-ready-for-an-i-p-o/ |title=Hulu Is Said to Be Ready for an I.P.O |publisher=Dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com |date=2010-08-16 |accessdate=2010-12-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101022161929/http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/16/hulu-is-said-to-be-ready-for-an-i-p-o/ |archive-date=2010-10-22 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2011, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that an \"unsolicited offer\" caused Hulu to begin \"weighing whether to sell itself\".<ref>{{cite news |author= Vascellaro |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303936704576400133483416612 |title= Website Hulu Considers Sale |work= [[The Wall Street Journal]] |date= 2011-06-21 |accessdate= 2011-06-21 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150328030500/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303936704576400133483416612 |archive-date= 2015-03-28 |url-status= live }}</ref> However, on October 13, 2011, Hulu and its owners announced that they would not sell the company, as none of the bidders offered an amount that was satisfactory to its owners.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://mashable.com/2011/10/13/no-hulu-sale/ |title= Hulu Is No Longer For Sale |last1= Parr |first1= Ben |date= October 13, 2011 |work= [[Mashable]] |publisher= Mashable, Inc. |accessdate= June 14, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130521112923/http://mashable.com/2011/10/13/no-hulu-sale/ |archive-date= May 21, 2013 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHulu generated $420 million in revenue in 2011, $80 million short of the company's target.<ref>{{cite web |last= Van Grove |first= Jennifer |date= January 31, 2012 |title= Hulu CEO Jason Kilar: Original programming is an important part of the agenda. |url= https://venturebeat.com/2012/01/31/hulu-jason-kilar/ |work= VentureBeat |access-date= August 31, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703055106/https://venturebeat.com/2012/01/31/hulu-jason-kilar/ |archive-date= July 3, 2017 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> The vacant CEO post was officially filled by former Fox Networks President Mike Hopkins on October 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Hopkins Named CEO of Hulu|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20131017006396/en/Mike-Hopkins-Named-CEO-Hulu|accessdate=17 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020060749/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20131017006396/en/Mike-Hopkins-Named-CEO-Hulu|archive-date=20 October 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2013-10-17}}</ref> Fox Networks Group COO Randy Freer was named CEO on October 24, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/hulu-randy-freer-named-new-ceo-succeed-mike-hopkins-1202193844/|title=Hulu Names Randy Freer New CEO To Succeed Mike Hopkins|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 24, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Disney ownership ===\nIn December 2017, Disney announced that they would [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquire 21st Century Fox]], including its 30% stake in Hulu, in a sale completed on March 20, 2019. The deal resulted in Disney having a controlling 60% interest in Hulu.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/12/14/media/disney-fox-deal/index.html|title=Disney is buying most of 21st Century Fox for $52.4 billion|last=Riley|first=Charles and [[Hadas Gold]]|work=CNNMoney|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180121041657/http://money.cnn.com/2017/12/14/media/disney-fox-deal/index.html|archive-date=2018-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/fox-corporation-debut-disney-murdoch-1203165925/|title=Fox Corporation Emerges as Standalone Entity, Paul Ryan Joins Board|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|last2=Steinberg|first2=Brian|date=March 18, 2019|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2019, [[AT&T]] (via [[WarnerMedia]]) sold its 9.5% stake in Hulu back to the company for $1.43 billion.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/15/att-sells-hulu-stake-valuing-company-at-15-billion.html|title=AT&T sells Hulu stake, valueing company at $15 billion|last=Levy|first=Ari|date=2019-04-15|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref> WarnerMedia plans to launch [[HBO Max]], its own competing service featuring content from its entertainment brands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-att-streaming-service-20181010-story.html |title=WarnerMedia announces new streaming service to compete with Netflix and Disney |last=Faughnder |first=Ryan |first2=Wendy |last2=Lee |website=Los Angeles Times |access-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Huluownership.jpg|alt=Ownership history of Hulu.|left|thumb|257x257px|Ownership history of Hulu.]]\nOn May 14, 2019, Comcast relinquished its control in Hulu to Disney effective immediately. As a result, the streaming service became a division of [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]] with Comcast effectively becoming a [[Partnership#Silent partners|silent partner]]. Under the agreement, Comcast's 33% stake can be sold to Disney at [[fair market value]] as early as 2024. The fair market value will be determined at that time, but Disney guaranteed a minimum valuation of the entire company at $27.5 billion (valuing the Comcast stake as worth at least $5.8 billion).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/what-expect-hulu-under-disneys-control-1212776|title=\"Older, Broader, Edgier\": What to Expect From Hulu Under Disney's Control|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|date=May 22, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref> Randy Freer would report to Disney executive [[Kevin A. Mayer|Kevin Mayer]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn the wake of the deal, Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]] explained that direct integration of Hulu with Disney's studios would allow increased investments in original content,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/06/18/hulu-ceo-expect-more-original-content-now-that-disney-is-in-control.html|title=Hulu CEO: Expect to see more original content now that Disney is in control|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|date=June 18, 2019|work=CNBC|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref> which would in turn allow it to \"make the service even more compelling and a greater value for consumers\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/14/comcast-has-agreed-to-sell-its-stake-in-hulu-in-5-years.html|title=Disney to take full control over Hulu, Comcast has option to sell its stake in 5 years|last=Sherman|first=Lauren Feiner,Christine Wang,Alex|date=2019-05-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/disney-full-control-hulu-comcast-deal-1203214338/|title=Disney Assumes Full Control of Hulu in Deal With Comcast|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2019-05-14|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nNBCUniversal will continue to license its content to the service through at least 2024, but it will have the option to begin transitioning its exclusivity deals with Hulu to non-exclusive terms beginning in 2020, and to end other content deals beginning in 2022.<ref name=\"Disney\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/14/comcast-has-agreed-to-sell-its-stake-in-hulu-in-5-years.html|title=Disney to take full control over Hulu, Comcast has option to sell its stake in 5 years|last=Feiner|first=Lauren|last2=Wang|first2=Christine|last3=Sherman|first3=Alex|work=CNBC|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, NBCUniversal had announced an intent to launch its own competing streaming platform known as [[Peacock (streaming service)|Peacock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/nbcuniversal-entering-the-streaming-wars-with-2020-launch-of-bonnie-hammer-run-service-mark-lazarus-jeff-schell-get-major-promotions-1202534914|title=NBCUniversal Entering The Streaming Wars With 2020 Launch Of Bonnie Hammer-Run Service; Mark Lazarus, Jeff Shell Also Get Major Promotions|last1=Hayes|first1=Dade|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030214327/https://deadline.com/2019/01/nbcuniversal-entering-the-streaming-wars-with-2020-launch-of-bonnie-hammer-run-service-mark-lazarus-jeff-schell-get-major-promotions-1202534914/|archive-date=October 30, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDisney stated that its control of Hulu was the third major component of its direct-to-consumer strategy, complimenting its sports streaming service [[ESPN+]], and its then-forthcoming [[Disney+]] (which would be focused primarily on [[family-friendly]] content from Disney's flagship franchises and studios). Hulu would be oriented towards \"general\" entertainment and content targeting mature audiences.<ref name=\"deadline-norrated\">{{cite web |author=Mike Fleming Jr. |title=Disney Unveils Inaugural Streaming Service Launch Slate To Town; No R-Rated Fare |url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/disney-streaming-service-launch-slate-star-wars-marvel-1202281846/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=April 5, 2018 |date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226065353/http://deadline.com/2018/02/disney-streaming-service-launch-slate-star-wars-marvel-1202281846/ |archivedate=February 26, 2018 }}</ref> \n\nOn July 31, 2019, Disney reorganized Hulu's reporting structure, placing Hulu's Scripted Originals team under [[Walt Disney Television]]. Under the new structure, Hulu's SVP of Original Scripted Content would report directly to the chairman of Disney Television Studios and ABC Entertainment.<ref name=\"HuluWDTV\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/hulu-scripted-originals-disney-tv-erwich-1203287122/ |title=Walt Disney Television Gains Oversight of Hulu's Scripted Originals Content Team |publisher = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date= July 31, 2019 | accessdate = July 31, 2019 | first = Elaine | last = Low}}</ref> As of November 2019, [[FX (TV channel)#FX Networks|FX]] and [[Searchlight Pictures|Fox Searchlight]] were assigned to supply Hulu with content.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |last2=Littleton |first2=Cynthia |title=FX to Produce Original Series for Hulu as Brands Become More Closely Intertwined |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/fx-hulu-disney-mrs-america-american-horror-story-1203397601/ |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=Variety |date=November 7, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Disney eliminated the role of Hulu CEO, as part of fully integrating Hulu with Disney's business model. Under the new structure, top Hulu executives would report directly to DTCI and Walt Disney Television leads.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/hulu-ceo-randy-freer-exits-streamer-is-integrated-into-disneys-direct-to-consumer-international-1202848283/ | title = Hulu CEO Randy Freer Exits As Streamer Is Integrated Into Disney's Direct-to-Consumer & International Unit | publisher = [[Deadline Hollywood]] | first = Nellie | last = Andreeva | date = January 31, 2020 | accessdate = January 31, 2020}}</ref> On January 31, 2020, CEO Randy Freer resigned from his role as part of a major restructuring of Disney's streaming business;<ref>{{cite news|last=Flint|first=Joe|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hulu-ceo-randy-freer-to-exit-as-part-of-disney-restructuring-11580512202|title=Hulu CEO Randy Freer to Exit as Part of Disney Restructuring|date=2020-01-31|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref> a part of the restructuring, Disney announced on February 25, 2020 that Kelly Campbell would run Hulu as president, reporting to DTCI Chairman, Kevin Mayer.<ref name=\"HuluPresident\">{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-promotes-kelly-campbell-run-hulu-1281088 | title = Disney Promotes Kelly Campbell to Run Hulu | publisher = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | first = Natalie| last = Jarvey | date = February 25, 2020 | accessdate = February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Partners ==\nFollowing the start of its service, Hulu signed deals with several new content providers making additional material available to consumers. On April 30, 2009, [[The Walt Disney Company]] announced that it would join the venture, purchasing a 27 percent stake in Hulu.<ref name=\"abchulu\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/30/AR2009043001853.html|title=It's Official: Disney Joins News Corp., NBCU In Hulu; Deal Includes Some Cable Nets|author=Kramer, Staci D.|date=April 30, 2006|accessdate=October 30, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504054305/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/30/AR2009043001853.html|archive-date=May 4, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nStarting August 15, 2011, viewers of content from Fox and related networks are required to authenticate paid cable or satellite service wherever Fox streams episodes, including on Hulu, to be able to watch them the morning after the first airing. Non-subscribers will see those episodes delayed a week before they are viewable.<ref>[[Brian Stelter]], ''[[The New York Times]]''. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/27/business/media/fox-to-limit-next-day-streaming-on-hulu.html Fox to Limit Next-Day Streaming on Hulu to Paying Cable Customers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531154143/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/27/business/media/fox-to-limit-next-day-streaming-on-hulu.html |date=2013-05-31 }}\". July 26, 2011. Retrieved July 28, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2011, Hulu announced that they had inked a five-year deal with [[The CW]], giving the streaming site access to next-day content from five of the six major networks.<ref>Wasserman, Todd, [[Mashable]] [http://mashable.com/2011/10/28/hulu-gossip-girl-cw/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111030165419/http://mashable.com/2011/10/28/hulu-gossip-girl-cw/ |date=2011-10-30 }}</ref> On September 18, 2013, Hulu announced a multi-year deal with the [[BBC]] that will deliver 2,000 episodes from 144 different titles in the first 12 months.<ref>{{cite web | title = Hulu BBC Deal, A Positive Step After Some Cloudy Times | url = http://ceoworld.biz/2013/09/18/hulu-bbc-deal-a-positive-step-after-some-cloudy-times | work = CEOWORLD Magazine | date = 18 September 2013 | access-date = 20 August 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130928075905/http://ceoworld.biz/2013/09/18/hulu-bbc-deal-a-positive-step-after-some-cloudy-times | archive-date = 28 September 2013 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nIn 2015, Hulu began offering content from [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] for an additional $8.99/month, which is cheaper than Showtime's own streaming service. On June 16, 2016, Hulu announced a deal with the Disney-ABC Television Group for the exclusive SVOD rights to past seasons of seven Disney Channel, Disney Junior and Disney XD series, and more than 20 Disney Channel original movies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/hulu-makes-big-kids-programming-push-new-disney-channel-deal-172048 |title=Hulu Makes Big Kids Programming Push With New Disney Channel Deal |work=[[Ad Week]] |access-date=17 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617144309/http://www.adweek.com/news/television/hulu-makes-big-kids-programming-push-new-disney-channel-deal-172048 |archive-date=17 June 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe CW's agreement with Hulu ended September 18, 2016; in-season streaming of current CW programs moved to the network's own digital platforms, and Netflix began to carry past seasons of The CW's programs through 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/official-netflix-cw-reach-new-908442|title=It's Official: Netflix, The CW Reach New Streaming Pact|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> {{As of|2017|January}}, a limited amount of content from [[CBS]]'s library is available on-demand, mostly limited to shows that are no longer producing new episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.hulu.com/articles/22330147|title=CBS shows on Hulu|website=help.hulu.com|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105084731/https://help.hulu.com/articles/22330147|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulu.com/companies/cbs|title=CBS|website=Hulu|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105080054/http://www.hulu.com/companies/cbs|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 4, 2017, it was reported that a deal was reached to bring live broadcasts of CBS and several affiliated channels to Hulu's upcoming live streaming service<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cbs-corp-hulu-deal-idUSKBN14O1Y1|title=CBS signs deal to be on Hulu's live-streaming platform|date=2017-01-04|publisher=Reuters|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104233511/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-cbs-corp-hulu-deal-idUSKBN14O1Y1|archive-date=2017-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as to make more shows available on-demand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/04/hulu-adds-cbs-to-its-upcoming-live-tv-service/|title=Hulu adds CBS to its upcoming live TV service|publisher=[[Engadget]]|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105061502/https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/04/hulu-adds-cbs-to-its-upcoming-live-tv-service/|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Hulu announced a partnership with [[Spotify]] that allows users to purchase both streaming services for a discounted price per month. This discount also includes an even more discounted rate for university students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17222646/spotify-hulu-bundle-deal-now-available-pricing|title=Now you can get Spotify and Hulu together for just $12.99 each month|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412001334/https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17222646/spotify-hulu-bundle-deal-now-available-pricing|archive-date=2018-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\n\n=== {{anchor|Hulu Plus}} Hulu subscription service ===\nAt an industry conference held on October 21, 2009, [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] Deputy Chairman [[Chase Carey]] stated that Hulu \"needs to evolve to have a meaningful subscription model as part of its business\" and that it would likely start charging for at least some content by 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/blog/ADverse_Atkinson_on_Advertising/23941-Chase_Carey_Hulu_to_Charge_in_2010.php?nid=2228&source=title&rid=6454445 |title=Chase Carey: Hulu to Charge in 2010 |date=2009-10-21 |author=Atkinson, Claire |work=Broadcasting & Cable |publisher=Reed Business Information |accessdate=2009-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025045542/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/blog/ADverse_Atkinson_on_Advertising/23941-Chase_Carey_Hulu_to_Charge_in_2010.php?nid=2228&source=title&rid=6454445 |archive-date=2009-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carey's comment jibes with other News Corp. heads, including Rupert Murdoch who has expressed a desire to charge for content with a number of online units.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-10381622-261.html |title=More signs Hulu subscription service is coming |first=Greg |last=Sandoval |date=October 22, 2009 |accessdate=November 4, 2009 |work=Media Maverick |publisher=CNET |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617000040/http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-10381622-261.html |archive-date=June 17, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHulu's subscription service was launched in [[Beta test|beta (preview)]] on June 29, 2010,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/29/hulu-unveils-subscription-service-for-9-99-a-month/ |title=Hulu Unveils Subscription Service For $9.99 a Month |first=Brian |last=Stelter |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2014 |work=New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112160157/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/29/hulu-unveils-subscription-service-for-9-99-a-month/ |archive-date=12 November 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and officially launched on November 17, 2010 under the branding '''Hulu Plus'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/17/hulu-drops-prices-to-compete-with-netflix/ |title=Hulu Drops Prices to Compete With Netflix |first=Brian |last=Stelter |date=27 November 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2014 |work=New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112161947/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/17/hulu-drops-prices-to-compete-with-netflix/ |archive-date=12 November 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  The service remains advertising-supported, but it offers an expanded content library including full seasons, day-after access to current season content and more episodes of shows available. Hulu also launched Hulu Plus apps on other types of devices, including mobile, [[digital media player]]s, and [[video game console]]s. By the end of 2011, Hulu Plus had around 1.5 million subscribers.<ref>Nakashima, Ryan January 13, 2012. [http://www.newsday.com/business/hulu-plus-ends-year-with-1-5-million-subscribers-1.3448597 \"Hulu Plus ends year with 1.5 million subscribers\"].</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2015, it was announced that the \"Hulu Plus\" branding would be discontinued, and that the service would be henceforth marketed as simply \"Hulu\" to place it in-line with its subscription-only competitors. By then, the service had grown to 9 million subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/hulu-makes-name-change-official-ditches-the-plus-1201520583/|title=Hulu Makes Name Change Official, Ditches the Plus|last=Roettgers|first=Janko|last2=Roettgers|first2=Janko|date=2015-06-16|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=Advertising Age|url=http://adage.com/article/media/hulu-drop-hulu-brand-picks-seinfeld/298305/|title=Hulu Will Drop Hulu Plus Brand, Picks up 'Seinfeld'|accessdate=September 13, 2015|author=Peterson, Tim|date=April 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906123704/http://adage.com/article/media/hulu-drop-hulu-brand-picks-seinfeld/298305/|archive-date=September 6, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Wall Street Journal'' reported in July 2015 that Hulu was exploring an advertising-free subscription option for around $12 to $14 a month.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Shields|url=https://www.wsj.com/article_email/hulu-explores-adding-ad-free-option-to-its-service-1437103682-lMyQjAxMTI1MzE1NzIxMDc2Wj|title=Hulu Explores Adding Ad-Free Option to Its Service|date=July 16, 2015|publisher=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109235948/http://www.wsj.com/article_email/hulu-explores-adding-ad-free-option-to-its-service-1437103682-lMyQjAxMTI1MzE1NzIxMDc2Wj|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> This was confirmed as going forward {{as of|2015|September|2|lc=y|df=US}}, with a \"No Commercials\" plan priced at $11.99, $4 more than the $7.99 monthly rate for a \"Limited Commercials\" subscription,<ref>{{cite web|title = Hulu \u2013 About|url = http://www.hulu.com/about|website = Hulu|accessdate = 2015-04-08|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150406223353/http://www.hulu.com/about|archive-date = 2015-04-06|url-status = live}}</ref> though a few highlighted network series (less than 10) would retain pre-roll and post-roll{{clarification|date=April 2020}} ad pods.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/hulu-adds-mostly-ad-free-subscription-service-1201583375/|title=Hulu Adds (Mostly) Ad-Free Subscription Service|last=Wallenstein|first=Andrew|date=2 September 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903042841/http://variety.com/2015/digital/news/hulu-adds-mostly-ad-free-subscription-service-1201583375/|archive-date=3 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Starting in 2019, Hulu plans to begin displaying on-screen ads when the viewer pauses the show, although it is unclear whether this will apply to customers on the $11.99/month No Ads plan.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Anthony|last=Ha| url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/31/hulu-pause-ad/ | title=Hulu announces a new ad unit that appears when you pause|website=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Hulu announced that it had reached 12 million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|title=Hulu closes in on 12 million subscribers; plans cable-like TV option|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/05/04/media/hulu-subscribers-cable-bundle/|website=CNN Money|publisher=CNN|accessdate=1 November 2016|date=4 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103234634/http://money.cnn.com/2016/05/04/media/hulu-subscribers-cable-bundle/|archive-date=3 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2018, Hulu announced that it had reached 17 million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|title=Hulu closes in on 12 million subscribers; plans cable-like TV option|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/9/16868864/hulu-17-million-subscribers-announced-2018|website=theverge.com|publisher=Verge|accessdate=6 February 2018|date=9 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207123153/https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/9/16868864/hulu-17-million-subscribers-announced-2018|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2016, Hulu announced that it would discontinue its free video on-demand content, and syndicate it to [[Yahoo!]] on a new website known as [[Yahoo! View]]. This service features recent episodes of ABC, Fox, and NBC series. The Hulu website is now devoted exclusively to the subscription service.<ref name=\"wp-hulunofree\">{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Fung|title=This is the end of Hulu as we know it|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/08/08/hulu-is-getting-rid-of-what-made-it-famous/|website=Washington Post|accessdate=9 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809122415/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/08/08/hulu-is-getting-rid-of-what-made-it-famous/|archive-date=9 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|title=Hulu to End Free TV Service|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hulu-end-free-tv-service-917917|accessdate=August 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808222239/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hulu-end-free-tv-service-917917|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Brodkin|first=Jon|title=Hulu will soon end its free streaming options|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/08/hulus-free-shows-move-to-yahoo-as-it-becomes-a-paid-only-service/|accessdate=August 8, 2016|work=Ars Technica|date=August 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808160803/http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/08/hulus-free-shows-move-to-yahoo-as-it-becomes-a-paid-only-service/|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Hulu introduced [[5.1 surround sound]] on select devices for its original content.<ref>[https://help.hulu.com/en-us/sound-quality Audio quality on Hulu]. Hulu.</ref> In December 2016 Hulu began streaming content in [[4K resolution|4K]], also limited to its original content.<ref>[https://www.hulu.com/press/4k-ultra-hd-now-streaming-on-hulu/ 4K Ultra HD Now Streaming on Hulu]. Hulu Press Release. 2 December 2016.</ref> 4K video was quietly rolled back in 2018, and reintroduced in July 2019. [[High-dynamic-range video|HDR]] video is not supported.<ref>[https://www.cordcutters.com/can-you-get-4k-hdr-video-hulu Can you get 4K HDR video on Hulu?] Cord Cutters. 4 October 2018.</ref><ref>[https://bgr.com/2019/07/12/hulu-4k-streaming-devices-original-shows/ Hulu finally brings back 4K streaming after killing it last year]. BGR. 12 July 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/home-theater/4k-back-on-hulu/|title=Hulu Brings Back 4K Streaming, But There Are Some Major Limitations|date=2019-10-14|website=Digital Trends|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, 2019, Hulu announced a $2 price drop for the basic ad-supported plan to $5.99. The $5.99 monthly plan has previously been offered as a promotional offer since late 2017 where users that signed up (or reactivated accounts that had previously ended their service) during the offer period would keep the price for an entire year before paying the regular rate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welch |first1=Chris |title=Hulu drops to just $5.99 per month after Netflix's price hikes |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/23/18193539/hulu-price-change-subscription-ads-live-tv-2019 |website=The Verge |accessdate=23 January 2019 |date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince the launch of Disney+ in November 2019, the service has been available in a bundle with ESPN+ and the ad-supported tier of Hulu, priced at US$12.99 per-month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/6/20757626/disney-plus-espn-hulu-bundle-price-date-streaming-service|title=Disney announces $12.99 bundle for Disney+, Hulu, and ESPN+|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2019-08-06|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Hulu + Live TV ===\nIn May 2016, Hulu announced that it planned to begin offering an [[over-the-top content|over-the-top]] [[IPTV]] service with \"live programming from broadcast and cable brands\" some time in 2017.<ref name=\"verge-hululivetv\">{{cite web|title=Hulu confirms plan to stream live TV next year|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11590306/hulu-confirms-live-tv-2017-plans|website=The Verge|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=10 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810115549/http://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11590306/hulu-confirms-live-tv-2017-plans|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2016-05-04}}</ref> In late 2016, co-owners 21st Century Fox and The Walt Disney Company agreed to supply their channels to the streaming service, joined by Time Warner, which previously reached an agreement with Hulu.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lieberman|first1=David|title=Disney And Fox Agree To Provide Sports And Broadcast Channels To Hulu|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/disney-fox-agree-provide-sports-other-channels-hulu-1201846186/|accessdate=January 24, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030818/http://deadline.com/2016/11/disney-fox-agree-provide-sports-other-channels-hulu-1201846186/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe service, originally marketed as \"Hulu with Live TV,\" that couples the live TV offerings with Hulu's existing library of television series and films, launched in [[beta testing|beta]] on May 3, 2017. It was later renamed to \"Hulu + Live TV.\" The service \u2013 which provides support for [[Xbox One]], [[Android TV]], [[Apple TV]], [[Chromecast]], [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices \u2013 offers live streams of more than 50 broadcast and cable-originated channels, including feeds of the five major broadcast networks \u2013 ABC, CBS, NBC, Fox and The CW \u2013 as well as cable channels owned by Hulu co-parents NBCUniversal, 21st Century Fox and The Walt Disney Company, along with [[ViacomCBS]], [[Turner Broadcasting System|WarnerMedia Entertainment]], [[Scripps Networks Interactive]] and [[A+E Networks]] (encompassing networks such as [[CNN]], [[Food Network]], [[Disney Channel]], [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]], [[MSNBC]] and [[ESPN]]), with the Showtime OTT service available as an add-on for an extra fee. Hulu representatives stated that it intends to negotiate carriage agreements with independently owned broadcasting groups to gain distribution rights to local stations from additional markets.<ref>{{cite web|title=You can now watch 50-plus channels of live TV on Hulu with $39.99 upgrade|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/05/03/net-video-streamer-hulu-gets-3999-live-tv-upgrade/101218510/|author=Mike Snider|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508210018/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/05/03/net-video-streamer-hulu-gets-3999-live-tv-upgrade/101218510/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hulu Live TV launches in beta: What you need to know|url=http://www.techhive.com/article/3193912/streaming-services/hulu-live-tv-launches-in-beta-what-you-need-to-know.html|author=Jared Newman|website=[[TechHive]]|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509022030/http://www.techhive.com/article/3193912/streaming-services/hulu-live-tv-launches-in-beta-what-you-need-to-know.html|archive-date=May 9, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Todd Spangler\">{{cite web|title=Hulu Live TV Service Launches With 50 Channels for $40 Monthly|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-launch-channels-1202407778/|author=Todd Spangler|periodical=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508083536/http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-launch-channels-1202407778/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Todd Spangler\" /> \n\nFeatures include the ability to create up of six user account profiles per a single subscription (with personalized program recommendations based on a user's favorite programs and varying simultaneous streams depending on the package), personalized sports recommendations and a [[cloud computing|cloud]] [[digital video recorder|DVR]] with between 50 and 200 hours of storage depending on the level of service (the lower-tier DVR does not have ad skipping functionality).<ref>{{cite news|title=Hulu just launched its $40-a-month cable-TV competitor \u2014 here are all the details|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/hulu-live-tv-package-details-pricing-channels-features-2017-5|author=Nathan McAlone|website=Business Insider|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507140451/http://www.businessinsider.com/hulu-live-tv-package-details-pricing-channels-features-2017-5|archive-date=May 7, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hulu launches live TV service|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/03/media/hulu-live-tv-service/index.html|author=Sandra Gonzalez|website=CNN Money|publisher=Time Warner|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503203436/http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/03/media/hulu-live-tv-service/index.html|archive-date=May 3, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hulu Live TV Bundle: Full Channel Lineup|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-full-channel-lineup-1202407833/|author=Todd Spangler|periodical=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508033929/http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-full-channel-lineup-1202407833/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hulu Live TV Service Won't Have Viacom Networks|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-no-viacom-networks-1202006300/|author=Todd Spangler|periodical=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512084000/http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-no-viacom-networks-1202006300/|archive-date=May 12, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Subscribers must have a residential broadband connection in order to use the Hulu with Live TV service. The Hulu with Live TV service can be used on mobile devices and networks, but service will be blocked unless the user has accessed the service on the device via their designated \"home\" network within the past 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2020/03/hulus-live-tv-doesnt-work-on-t-mobile-home-internet/|title=Hulu\u2019s live TV doesn\u2019t work on T-Mobile home Internet|last=Brodkin|first=Jon|date=2020-03-06|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe service was initially priced at $39.99 per-month. In December 2019, the price had been increased to $54.99 per month (after having previously been raised to $44.99).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hulu-20190122-story.html|title=Hulu will raise price of live TV packages, but lower the cost of basic streaming|date=2019-01-23|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/15/hulu-is-increasing-the-price-of-its-hulu-live-stream-starting-dec-18.html|title=Hulu is increasing the price of its Hulu + Live TV 22% starting Dec. 18|last=Cosgrove|first=Elly|date=2019-11-15|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> By May 2018, the service had reached 800,000 subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/hulu-pay-tv-bundle-hits-800k-subscribers-1202400295/|title=Hulu Pay-TV Bundle Hits 800K Subscribers|last=Hayes|first=Dade|date=2018-05-30|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> In the third quarter of 2019, Hulu overtook [[Sling TV]] as the top OTT pay television service in the United States, with 2.7 million subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-beats-sling-top-streaming-pay-tv-research-1203406138/|title=Hulu Live TV Tops Sling TV as No. 1 Streaming Pay-TV Service, Analysts Estimate|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2019-11-15|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Viewership ==\nViewership numbers for the site are tracked by measurement firms such as [[ComScore]], [[Nielsen ratings]], and [[Quantcast]]. In partnership with comScore, Hulu is the first digital company to receive multi-platform measurement at an individual level that includes co-viewing for living room devices. When factoring this in, Hulu's reach among adults aged 18\u201349 increases 50 percent.\n\nHowever, the reliability of these metrics has been drawn into question, partly due to widely divergent estimates. For example, between May and June 2010, ComScore updated its scoring methodology and its estimates for Hulu dropping from 43.5 million unique and special viewers to 24 million in a single month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/26/business/la-fi-ct-hulu-20100721|title=Hulu's sharp decline in viewership underscores inconsistency in measuring size of online audience|publisher=LA Times|author=Dawn C. Chmielewski|date=26 Jul 2010|accessdate=1 Nov 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311095132/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/26/business/la-fi-ct-hulu-20100721|archive-date=11 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a comScore digital trends report in 2010, comScore's Digital Year in Review report found that Hulu was watched twice as much as viewers who watched on the websites of the five major TV networks combined.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schonfeld|first1=Erick|title=ComScore: Hulu Is Watched Twice As Much As The 5 Major TV Networks Online Combined|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/02/07/comscore-hulu-tv-networks/|publisher=TechCrunch|date=7 Feb 2011|access-date=11 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212031532/https://techcrunch.com/2011/02/07/comscore-hulu-tv-networks/|archive-date=12 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHulu in May 2018 announced it has surpassed 20 million subscribers in the United States.<ref name=\"Media Play News\">{{cite news|last1=Gruenwedel|first1=Erik|title=Hulu Tops 20 Million Subs, Inks First Deal with DreamWorks Animation|url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/hulu-tops-20-million-subs-inks-first-deal-with-dreamworks-animation/|accessdate=May 2, 2018|work=Media Play News|date=May 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503041617/https://www.mediaplaynews.com/hulu-tops-20-million-subs-inks-first-deal-with-dreamworks-animation/|archive-date=May 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tally, which puts the company about 36 million subscriptions behind Netflix, was disclosed at a media presentation at the newly named Hulu Theater at Madison Square Garden in New York. Hulu said it has grown total engagement by more than 60%, with 78% of viewing taking place in the living room on connected TVs.\n\n== Programming ==\n\n=== Content partners ===\nHulu distributes video on its own website and syndicates its hosting to other sites,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120519822483125987 |title=Can Hulu Find Its Mojo With Viewers? |accessdate=2008-03-19 |date=2008-03-11 |author=Rebecca Dana and Emily Steel |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109235949/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120519822483125987 |archive-date=2016-01-09 |url-status=live }}</ref> and allows users to embed Hulu clips on their websites.<ref name=\"pr_launch\" /> In addition to NBC, ABC and Fox programs and movies, Hulu carries shows from networks such as [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]], [[Big Ten Network]], [[Bravo (American TV channel)|Bravo]], [[E!]], [[Fox Sports 2]], [[FX (TV channel)|FX]], [[PBS]], [[NFL Network]], [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]], [[RT America]], [[Fox Sports 1]], [[SundanceTV]], [[Syfy]], [[USA Network]], [[NBCSN]], and online comedy sources such as [[Onion News Network]].<ref name=\"The Live Feed\">{{cite web|url= http://www.thrfeed.com/2009/04/abc-to-offer-shows-on-hulu.html|title= ABC to offer shows on Hulu|publisher= The Live Feed|date= April 30, 2009|access-date= December 11, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090504084734/http://www.thrfeed.com/2009/04/abc-to-offer-shows-on-hulu.html|archive-date= May 4, 2009|url-status= live|df= mdy-all}}</ref> Hulu retains between thirty and fifty percent of advertising revenue generated by the shows it distributes.<ref name=\"Stelter\" />\n\nIn November 2009, Hulu also began to establish partnerships with record labels to host music videos and concert performances on the site, including [[EMI]] in November 2009,<ref name=\"emi-hulu\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2356071,00.asp|title=Hulu, EMI Strike Deal for Music Videos, Concerts|date=November 18, 2009|publisher=PC Magazine|accessdate=24 December 2009|first=Chloe|last=Albanesius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121155534/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2356071,00.asp|archive-date=21 November 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Warner Music Group]] in December 2009.<ref name=\"hulu-wmg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2357529,00.asp|title=Hulu, Warner Music Sign Deal for Music Content|date=December 23, 2009|publisher=PC Magazine|accessdate=24 December 2009|first=Chloe|last=Albanesius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227044623/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2357529,00.asp|archive-date=27 December 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn early March 2010, [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] announced that it was pulling two of the website's most popular shows, ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' and ''[[The Daily Show]]'', off Hulu.<ref name=\"nydn\">''[[New York Daily News]]'' article: \"[http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2010/03/03/2010-03-03_comedy_central_pulls_daily_show_and_colbert_off_hulu.html Comedy Central's 'The Daily Show' and 'The Colbert Report' off Hulu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306151209/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2010/03/03/2010-03-03_comedy_central_pulls_daily_show_and_colbert_off_hulu.html |date=2010-03-06 }}.\"</ref> The programs had been airing on Hulu since late 2008.<ref name=\"mcn\" /> A spokesman for [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] noted that \"in the current economic model, there is not that much in it for us to continue at this time. If they can get to the point where the monetization model is better, then we may go back.\"<ref name=\"mcn\">Multichannel News article: \"[http://www.multichannel.com/article/449861-Dauman_Vivendi_Could_Return_To_Hulu.php Dauman: Vivendi Could Return To Hulu].\"</ref> In February 2011, both shows were made available for streaming on Hulu again. ''The Daily Show'' was again removed from Hulu in March 2017 in order to push viewers to watch the program on Viacom and Comedy Central's apps.\n\nIn April 2017, Hulu signed a first-run license deal with [[Annapurna Pictures]]. Hulu also has output deals with [[IFC Films]] and [[Magnolia Pictures]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-annapurna-pictures-movie-output-deal-1202024899 | title=Hulu Inks Annapurna Pictures Pay-One TV Window Movie Output Deal| date=2017-04-06}}</ref>\n\nNew releases from 20th Century Studios will not immediately be available on either Disney+ or Hulu, as it has an existing output deal with [[HBO]] until 2022.<ref name=\"HBO Fox\">{{cite news|title=HBO and 20th Century Fox renew output deal|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-hbo20th-20120815,0,5442974.story|author=Joe Flint|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHulu in May 2018 announced its first-ever license deal with [[DreamWorks Animation]], becoming the exclusive streaming home for future DWA movies feature films, as well as library films. DWA had streamed exclusively through Netflix since 2013.<ref name=\"Media Play News\" /> Films will be available on the service in 2019, while original series will be available later in 2020.\n\nOn December 4, 2018, Hulu confirmed an exclusive multi-year first-look SVOD deal with [[Funimation]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/hulu-funimation-anime-japanese-series-1203079274/ | title=Hulu Lands Funimation First-Look Deal for Japanese Anime Series (EXCLUSIVE)| date=2018-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Hulu and [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] signed an output deal with [[Lionsgate]], where Hulu and FX would respectably gain the streaming and TV rights to films released under the Lionsgate label in 2020 and 2021.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/lionsgate-hulu-fx-distribution-deal-1203240225/|title=Lionsgate Pacts With Hulu, FX for Two-Year Output Deal|date=June 11, 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=July 30, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Hulu agreed to control the streaming rights to upcoming films released by [[Bleecker Street (company)|Bleecker Street]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/hulu-bleecker-street-partner-on-exclusive-svod-deal-1202661486/|title=Hulu & Bleecker Street Partner On Exclusive SVOD Deal|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|date=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2020, Hulu launched a dedicated \"hub\" for content from FX branded as ''FX on Hulu'', with the service becoming the exclusive streaming outlet for current and past series from the network. Beginning with [[Breeders (TV series)|''Breeders'']], new episodes of FX original series also become available on Hulu immediately after their television airing, and selected series will also premiere exclusively on the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fx-on-hulu-check-out-the-release-schedule-for-all-/1100-6472637/|title=FX On Hulu: Check Out The Release Schedule For All Your Favorite New Shows|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/disney-fx-hulu-streaming-cate-blanchett-disney-earnings-1202780657/|title=Hulu To Be Official FX Streaming Home Next Year, Bob Iger Says; Cate Blanchett\u2019s \u2018Mrs. America\u2019 & 3 Other Series Move Online|last=Patten|first=Dominic|last2=Patten|first2=Dominic|date=2019-11-07|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/john-landgraf-calls-fx-on-hulu-transformative-opportunity-for-cabler-tca-1202825633/|title=John Landgraf Calls FX On Hulu \u201cTransformative Opportunity\u201d For Cabler As Digital Hub Sets March Launch Plans \u2013 TCA|last=White|first=Peter|last2=White|first2=Peter|date=2020-01-09|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Original content ===\n{{Further|List of original programs distributed by Hulu}}\nFrom January 17, 2011 to April 24, 2014, Hulu streamed its own in-house web series ''[[The Morning After (web series)|The Morning After]]'', a light-hearted pop-culture news show. It was produced by Hulu in conjunction with [[Jace Hall]]'s HDFilms and stars Brian Kimmet and Ginger Gonzaga. Producing the show was a first for the company, which in the past has been primarily a content distributor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gigaom.com/video/new-series-the-morning-after-nudges-hulu-into-production/ |title=New Series The Morning After Nudges Hulu Into Production |date=2011-01-18 |author=Liz Shannon Miller |publisher=GigaOM |accessdate=2011-05-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718145157/http://gigaom.com/video/new-series-the-morning-after-nudges-hulu-into-production/ |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2012, Hulu announced that it would be airing its first original script based program, titled ''[[Battleground (TV series)|Battleground]]'', which premiered in February 2012. The program aired on Hulu's free web service rather than on the subscription-based Hulu Plus. ''Battleground'' is described as a documentary-style political drama.<ref>Rother, Larry, January 16, 2012, [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/16/hulu-announces-first-original-script-based-program/ \"Hulu Announces First Original-Script-Based Program\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065859/https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/16/hulu-announces-first-original-script-based-program/ |date=2017-10-29 }}</ref>\n\nLater that same month, Hulu announced it would air ''The Fashion Fund'', a six-part reality series, and the winner of the show would receive $300,000 to start their career.<ref>Poggi Jeanine January 27, 2012. [http://adage.com/article/mediaworks/hulu-introduces-fashion-fund-original-reality-series/232384/ Hulu Adds Unscripted Series 'The Fashion Fund,' Accelerating Original Content Effort.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120710210257/http://adage.com/article/mediaworks/hulu-introduces-fashion-fund-original-reality-series/232384/ |date=2012-07-10 }}</ref>\n\nTo continue with its original programming movement, Hulu announced that there would be a total of seven original programs that were planned to air on its service: ''Battleground'', ''Day in the Life'', and ''Up to Speed'' were previously mentioned; and on April 19, Hulu added four more shows to its list: ''Don't Quit Your Daydream'', ''Flow'', ''The Awesomes'', and ''We Got Next''. Some of these programs began airing in 2012, while others premiered over the next few years.<ref>{{cite news|author=Perez, Sarah|date=April 19, 2012|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/04/19/hulu-announces-four-more-original-series-will-feature-snl-vets-adrian-grenier-of-hbos-entourage-others/|work=TechCrunch|title=Hulu Announces Four More Original Series|access-date=December 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029174512/https://techcrunch.com/2012/04/19/hulu-announces-four-more-original-series-will-feature-snl-vets-adrian-grenier-of-hbos-entourage-others/|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2012, Hulu announced it would be bringing [[Kevin Smith]] to its line-up of original programming. Smith hosts a movie discussion show titled ''[[Spoilers (TV series)|Spoilers]]'', which began airing in mid-2012.<ref>{{cite news|author=Wasserman, Todd|date=May 21, 2012|title=Hulu to Launch New Show With Kevin Smith Plus 9 Other Titles|url=http://mashable.com/2012/05/21/hulu-new-shows-kevin-smith/|work=Mashable|access-date=December 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029174001/http://mashable.com/2012/05/21/hulu-new-shows-kevin-smith/|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, [[Lionsgate Premiere]] and Hulu jointly acquired distribution rights to the film, ''[[Joshy (film)|Joshy]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/lionsgate-hulu-joshy-1201712664/|title=Lionsgate, Hulu Acquire Comedy 'Joshy'|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=March 1, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302195219/http://deadline.com/2016/03/lionsgate-hulu-joshy-1201712664/|archive-date=March 2, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> which was later released on August 12, 2016.<ref name=\"RELEASE\">{{cite web|url=https://thefilmstage.com/reviews/sundance-review-joshy/|title=Joshy Sundance 2016 Film Review|website=The Film Stage|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616225857/https://thefilmstage.com/reviews/sundance-review-joshy/|archive-date=June 16, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2016, Hulu acquired ''[[The Beatles: Eight Days a Week]]'', as its first documentary acquisition, as part of a planned Hulu Documentary Films collection.<ref name=\"Kastrenakes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11589950/hulu-documentaries-ron-howard-the-beatles-eight-days-a-week|title=Hulu is getting into documentaries, starting with Ron Howard's Beatles film|last=Kastrenakes|first=Jacob|date=4 May 2016|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507104718/http://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11589950/hulu-documentaries-ron-howard-the-beatles-eight-days-a-week|archive-date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film premiered theatrically on September 15, before debuting on the streaming service on September 17.<ref name=\"Beatles Official\">{{cite web|title=Watch the Trailer for ''The Beatles: Eight Days a Week \u2013 The Touring Years''|accessdate=20 June 2016|url=http://www.thebeatles.com/news/watch-trailer-beatles-eight-days-week-touring-years|publisher=[[The Beatles]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624042652/http://www.thebeatles.com/news/watch-trailer-beatles-eight-days-week-touring-years|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== ''South Park'' ===\n{{overly detailed|date=February 2020}}\nOn July 12, 2014, it was announced that Hulu had signed a three-year deal purchasing exclusive online streaming rights to the ''[[South Park]]'' library. Through the deal, the [[South Park]] Studios website became powered by Hulu video and featured advertising.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/pecom/20140712005015/en|title=Hulu and South Park Announce Exclusive Multi-Year Content Licensing Deal at 2014 Television Critics Association Summer Press Tour \u2013 Business Wire|work=businesswire.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212193104/https://www.businesswire.com/news/pecom/20140712005015/en|archive-date=2017-12-12|url-status=live|date=2014-07-12}}</ref> Along with this, the domain name changed from \"southparkstudios.com\" to \"southpark.cc.com\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southparkstudios.com|title=South Park \u2013 Watch Full Episodes, Clips & More|work=southparkstudios.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712171540/http://www.southparkstudios.com/|archive-date=2014-07-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://southpark.cc.com|title=South Park \u2013 Watch Full Episodes, Clips & More|work=cc.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927005623/http://southpark.cc.com/|archive-date=2017-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref> Previously, the show had been available on the television website [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowyourmobile.com/apps/20082/netflix-removes-south-park-and-other-titles-its-library|title=Netflix removes South Park and other titles from its library|work=Know Your Mobile|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212032206/http://www.knowyourmobile.com/apps/20082/netflix-removes-south-park-and-other-titles-its-library|archive-date=2017-12-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The new site launch caused some technical issues, which were resolved allowing fans to watch uncensored<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxim.com/gadgets/all-uncensored-south-park-episodes-available-legally-free-online |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019085802/http://www.maxim.com/gadgets/all-uncensored-south-park-episodes-available-legally-free-online |archivedate=2014-10-19 }}</ref> episodes and clips. For viewers outside the US, episodes and clips still stream through the \"classic\" South Park player and nothing changed aside from the new site design. A handful of countries also have their own localized versions of South Park sites, with the old experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southpark.cc.com/blog/2014/07/28/south-park-new-site-faqs|title=South Park \u2013 New Site FAQs|work=cc.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212031653/http://southpark.cc.com/blog/2014/07/28/south-park-new-site-faqs|archive-date=2017-12-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced that beginning in September 2014, following the premiere of the 18th season, only 30 select episodes will be featured for free viewing at a time on the website, with new episodes being available for an entire month starting the day following their original airings. Almost every episode will be available for viewing on the Hulu subscription service, except for \"[[Super Best Friends]]\", \"[[200 (South Park)|200]]\", and \"[[201 (South Park)|201]]\", until June 2020, when the show will exit the service due to the acquisition of streaming rights by [[HBO Max]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/1107582-hbo-max-streaming-rights-rick-and-morty-and-south-park|title=South Park & Rick and Morty Streaming Rights Go to HBO Max|date=2019-10-30|website=ComingSoon.net|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Neon Alley ===\n[[Neon Alley]] is a [[Viz Media]]-owned anime-oriented streaming service that launched on October 2, 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2012-10-02/viz-debuts-neon-alley|title=Viz Debuts Neon Alley|accessdate=8 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628222130/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2012-10-02/viz-debuts-neon-alley|archive-date=28 June 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> streaming to both the US and Canadian markets. At the start of April 2014, the service discontinued its original livestream format and relaunched as a video-on-demand ([[Video on demand|FVOD]]) platform accessible on either its website or [[Internet]]-connected devices through Hulu. Since Hulu wasn't available in the Canadian market, Neon Alley subsequently restricted its service to the United States. On July 21, 2016, [[Tubi TV]] announced that they had commenced streaming of certain Viz titles in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tubitv.com/blog/2016/07/21/stream-naruto-sailor-moon-viz-media-partners-tubi-tv-deliver-free-anime/|title=Stream Naruto, Sailor Moon & More: VIZ Media Partners with Tubi TV to Deliver Free Anime|publisher=Tubi TV|date=July 21, 2016|accessdate=October 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024131340/http://tubitv.com/blog/2016/07/21/stream-naruto-sailor-moon-viz-media-partners-tubi-tv-deliver-free-anime/|archive-date=October 24, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHulu is known for streaming anime titles from many distributors, including [[Funimation]], [[TMS Entertainment]], and [[Bandai Visual]], in addition to Viz Media.\n\n=== International platforms ===\n* [[Viki (website)|Viki]] (Asian programs)\n\n== Awards ==\n\nHulu's original series [[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|''The Handmaid's Tale'']], won two awards at the [[33rd TCA Awards|33rd annual Television Critics Association Awards]] for [[TCA Award for Program of the Year|Program of the Year]] and [[TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Drama|Outstanding Achievement in Drama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/tca-awards-winners-carrie-coon-the-handmaids-tale-this-is-us-atlanta-1202516771/|title=TCA Award Winners: 'The Handmaid's Tale,' 'This Is Us,' 'Atlanta,' Carrie Coon Take Top Honors|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|date=5 Aug 2017|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004030647/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/tca-awards-winners-carrie-coon-the-handmaids-tale-this-is-us-atlanta-1202516771/|archive-date=4 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/handmaids-tale-wins-top-honor-at-2017-tca-awards-1027101/item/outstanding-achievement-drama-1027110|title='Handmaid's Tale' Wins Top Honor at 2017 TCA Awards|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=5 Aug 2017|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911075757/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/handmaids-tale-wins-top-honor-at-2017-tca-awards-1027101/item/outstanding-achievement-drama-1027110|archive-date=11 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[69th Primetime Emmy Awards|69th]] [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, Hulu earned a total of 8 awards for ''The Handmaid's Tale'' and became the first streaming service to win [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/the-handmaids-tale-wins-emmy-best-drama-series-hulu-streaming-service-1202171581/|title=Hulu's 'The Handmaid's Tale' Win Marks First Best Series Emmy For A Streaming Service|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002002658/http://deadline.com/2017/09/the-handmaids-tale-wins-emmy-best-drama-series-hulu-streaming-service-1202171581/|archive-date=2 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/18/media/hulu-emmy-win/index.html|title=And the top award goes to ... Hulu?|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=18 Sep 2017|website=[[CNN]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005120828/http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/18/media/hulu-emmy-win/index.html|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''The Handmaid's Tale'' also received Emmys for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Directing]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Writing]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Single-Camera Series|Outstanding Cinematography]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Production Design for a Narrative Contemporary or Fantasy Program (One Hour or More)|Outstanding Production Design]]. [[Elisabeth Moss]] won the Emmy for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress]], and [[Ann Dowd]] received the award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/17/arts/television/emmy-winners-list.html|title=Emmys 2017 Winners List|last=Chow|first=Andrew R.|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106073636/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/17/arts/television/emmy-winners-list.html|archive-date=6 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-nominees-winners-list-2017-story.html|title=The complete list of 2017 Emmy winners and nominees|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714020129/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-nominees-winners-list-2017-story.html|archive-date=14 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the 75th Golden Globe Awards ''The Handmaid's Tale'' took home two awards, Best TV Drama and Best Actress in a Drama TV Series<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2018/all|title=Winners & Nominees 2018|website=www.goldenglobes.com|access-date=2018-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114092934/https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2018/all|archive-date=2018-01-14|url-status=live}}</ref> (Elisabeth Moss).\n\nAt the [[22nd Critics' Choice Awards|2016 Critics' Choice Documentary Awards]], Hulu's first-released documentary, [[The Beatles: Eight Days a Week|''The Beatles: Eight Days A Week \u2013 The Touring Years'']] won the award for Best Music Documentary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/|title=CRITICS' CHOICE DOCUMENTARY AWARDS FEATURED ON CBS SUNDAY MORNING, OCT 29|date=9 Oct 2017|website=[[Critics' Choice Movie Award|Critic's Choice]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20171112085340/http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/|archive-date=12 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/critics-choice-documentary-awards-o-j-made-in-america-13th-1201848408/|title=Critics' Choice Documentary Awards: 'O.J.: Made In America' & '13th' Dominate|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106124126/http://deadline.com/2016/11/critics-choice-documentary-awards-o-j-made-in-america-13th-1201848408/|archive-date=6 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2016-11-04}}</ref> The documentary also received [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Film]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|2017 Grammy Awards]] and Best Documentary at the 16th Annual Movies for Grownups Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html|title=Grammys 2017: Complete list of winners and nominees|date=12 Feb 2017|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206205501/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/7603856/beatles-eight-days-a-week-producer-nigel-sinclair-grammys-2017-nomination|title='The Beatles: Eight Days a Week' Producer Nigel Sinclair 'Honored' by Best Music Film Grammy Nomination|date=6 Dec 2016|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104051948/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/7603856/beatles-eight-days-a-week-producer-nigel-sinclair-grammys-2017-nomination|archive-date=4 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[Creative Arts Emmy Award|Creative Arts Emmys]], the documentary earned two Emmys including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Sound Editing for Nonfiction Programming (Single or Multi-Camera)|Outstanding Sound Editing]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Sound Mixing for a Nonfiction Program (Single or Multi-Camera)|Outstanding Sound Mixing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/emmys-2017-hulu-handmaids-tale-1202557512/|title=Hulu Carried to Emmys Glory by Eight Wins for 'Handmaid's Tale'|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003004312/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/emmys-2017-hulu-handmaids-tale-1202557512/|archive-date=3 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/09/09/creative-arts-emmy-awards-2017-winners-list/|title=2017 Creative Arts Emmy winners include Carpool Karaoke, RuPaul's Drag Race, SNL|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=9 Sep 2017|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014151028/http://ew.com/tv/2017/09/09/creative-arts-emmy-awards-2017-winners-list/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[68th Primetime Emmy Awards]], Hulu received its first Emmy Award nominations for its Original series, ''[[11.22.63]]'' and for [[Triumph the Insult Comic Dog|''Triumph's Election Special 2016'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2016/outstanding-special-visual-effects-in-a-supporting-role|title=68th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|website=[[Emmys]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001235315/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2016/outstanding-special-visual-effects-in-a-supporting-role|archive-date=1 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-2016-nominees-winners-list-20160714-snap-story.html|title=Complete list of 2016 Emmy nominations and winners|last=Lewis|first=Dave|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714190232/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-2016-nominees-winners-list-20160714-snap-story.html|archive-date=14 July 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2016, Hulu received its first [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nomination for its Original series, [[Casual (TV series)|''Casual'']], for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|TV series, Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/golden-globes-hulus-first-nomination-for-casual-2015-12|title=Hulu just got its first Golden Globes nomination and it's a huge blow to the major networks|last=Nededog|first=Jethro|date=10 Dec 2015|website=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106064620/http://www.businessinsider.com/golden-globes-hulus-first-nomination-for-casual-2015-12|archive-date=6 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/golden-globes-hulu-casual-mike-hopkins-1201658366/|title=Golden Globes: 'Casual' Comedy Series Nom Marks Hulu's Awards Arrival|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|date=10 Dec 2015|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925205945/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/golden-globes-hulu-casual-mike-hopkins-1201658366/|archive-date=25 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== International availability ==\nIn July 2010, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' revealed that Hulu had been working on plans for an international launch of Hulu Plus for several months, and had identified the UK and Japan as markets where its free website and subscription model could feasibly work.<ref>Garrahan, Matthew. [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f01d42b0-8ade-11df-bead-00144feab49a.html Hulu eyes launching global pay platform] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150838/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f01d42b0-8ade-11df-bead-00144feab49a.html |date=2015-09-24 }}, ''Financial Times'', July 8, 2010. Retrieved July 11, 2010.</ref> Hulu chief executive Jason Kilar expressed his belief that the US model could be replicated elsewhere, saying \"We won't be satisfied until this is a global service.\"<ref>Laughlin, Andrew. [http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/digitaltv/news/a240992/hulu-puts-uk-launch-back-on-agenda.html Hulu 'puts UK launch back on agenda'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921051701/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/digitaltv/news/a240992/hulu-puts-uk-launch-back-on-agenda.html |date=2011-09-21 }}, ''Digital Spy'', July 9, 2010. Retrieved July 11, 2010.</ref> Hulu's first expansion into an international market took place with the launch of a service in Japan on September 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hulu officially launches streaming service in Japan |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/hulu-officially-launches-streaming-service-in-japan/ |website=CNET |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=1 September 2011}}</ref> On February 27, 2014, [[Nippon TV]] announced that it would acquire Hulu's Japanese business. The service would maintain the Hulu name under license, and Hulu would continue to provide its infrastructure and support to the service as a regional licensee. Nippon TV also planned to produce its own original content for the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/global/hulu-japan-to-be-acquired-by-nippon-tv-1201122915/|title=Hulu Japan to Be Acquired by Nippon TV|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2014-02-28|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nAs rights to its content are already held by other broadcasters, U.S.-based video on demand services are not usually available in Canada. Hulu also cited a small advertising market in Canada as reasoning.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mudhar|first1=Raju|title=Why these five well-known online services snub Canada|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/01/04/why-are-these-five-well-known-online-services-snubbing-canada.html|website=Toronto Star|accessdate=1 November 2016|date=4 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103235733/https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/01/04/why-are-these-five-well-known-online-services-snubbing-canada.html|archive-date=3 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rights to Hulu's original series have often been picked up by domestic broadcasters; for example, ''[[The Mindy Project]]'' was retained by its previous broadcast home, [[Citytv]], after its move to Hulu,<ref>{{cite web|title=Mindy Project staying on City despite being dropped by Fox|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/05/25/mindy-project-staying-on-city-despite-being-dropped-by-fox.html|website=Toronto Star|accessdate=27 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928204054/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/05/25/mindy-project-staying-on-city-despite-being-dropped-by-fox.html|archive-date=28 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|The Handmaid's Tale]]'' was acquired by [[Bell Media]] cable network [[Bravo (Canada)|Bravo]] (unrelated to the NBC-owned channel) and its streaming service [[Crave (streaming service)|Crave]],<ref name=\"torstar-hmtbravo\">{{cite news|title=The Handmaid's Tale finally gets Canadian distributor|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2017/03/27/the-handmaids-tale-finally-gets-canadian-distributor.html|work=Toronto Star|first=Debra|last=Yeo|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref> and ''[[The Path (TV series)|The Path]]'' by [[Showcase (Canadian TV channel)|Showcase]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2511881/aaron-paul-tv-show-the-path-coming-to-showcase-this-spring/|title=Aaron Paul TV show 'The Path' coming to Showcase this spring|date=2016-02-11|work=Global News|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nThe lack of international operations had been considered a potential shortcoming of Hulu in comparison to competitors, such as [[Prime Video]] and [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/television/hulu-could-go-international-to-compete-with-netflix-1314601|title=Hulu could go international to compete with Netflix|last=James|first=Dave|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref> During an earnings call on November 8, 2018, Disney CEO Bob Iger stated that after its purchase of 21st Century Fox, it planned to make stronger investments into Hulu, including wider international expansion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/9/18079218/disney-hulu-original-series-international-bob-iger-fox|title=Disney plans heavy investment in Hulu, wants more original series|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2018-11-09|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Iger announced that the international expansion of Hulu will start likely by 2021.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perez |first1=Sarah |title=Disney aims to launch Hulu internationally in 2021 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/02/05/disney-aims-to-launch-hulu-internationally-in-2021/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |accessdate=5 February 2020 |date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Netflix]]\n* [[CBS All Access]]\n* [[Disney+]]\n* [[HBO Max]]\n* [[Hotstar]]\n* [[Locast]]\n* [[Peacock (streaming service)]]\n* [[Seeso]], a defunct service launched by NBCUniversal in 2016 focusing on comedy\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Hulu}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Disney}}\n{{Comcast}}\n{{VOD services}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Hulu| ]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2007]]\n[[Category:NBCUniversal]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Company subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Subscription video on demand services]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Internet television streaming services]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 software]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Chinese animated series|Calabash Brothers}}\n{{short description|American provider of on-demand streaming media}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name             = Hulu, LLC\n| logo             = Hulu Logo.svg\n| logo_size        =\n| logo_alt         =\n| collapsible      = yes\n| collapsetext     = Screenshot\n| screenshot       = Hulu screenshot.png\n| screenshot_size  =\n| screenshot_alt   =\n| caption          = Hulu website screenshot\n| company_type     = [[Joint venture]]\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|2007|10|29}}\n| launched         = {{Start date|2007|10|29}}<br />(Hulu Syndication Network)<ref name=\"pr_launch\" /><br />(Hulu.com destination site)<ref name=\"pr_launch\" />\n| predecessor      =\n| location         = 2500 Broadway 2nd Floor, [[Santa Monica, California]]\n| country          = United States<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profile/company/3276470Z:US|title=Hulu LLC|website=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref>\n| area_served      = United States<br />Japan\n| founder          =\n| CEO              =\n| key_people       = Kelly Campbell ([[President (corporate title)|president]])\n| products         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Streaming media]]\n* [[Video on demand]]\n* [[Video on demand|Television on demand]]\n}}\n| services         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Television production]]\n* [[Digital distribution]]\n* [[Web syndication]]\n}}\n| revenue          = {{increase}} $1 billion (2013)<ref>{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Rogowsky|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markrogowsky/2013/12/19/hulus-billion-dollar-milestone-a-sign-of-just-how-far-behind-netflix-it-has-fallen|title=Hulu's Billion-Dollar Milestone: A Sign Of Just How Far Behind Netflix It Has Fallen|work=Forbes|access-date=2017-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130092127/https://www.forbes.com/sites/markrogowsky/2013/12/19/hulus-billion-dollar-milestone-a-sign-of-just-how-far-behind-netflix-it-has-fallen|archive-date=2018-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| operating_income =\n| international    =\n| parent           = [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]]\n| owners           = '''United States:''' {{Plainlist|\n* [[The Walt Disney Company]]<br>(67% equity; full control)<ref name=\"Disney\" />\n* [[Comcast Corporation]]<br>(33% equity; silent partner)<br>'''Japan:'''\n[[Nippon TV]]  ([[Brand licensing|branding]] licensed by Hulu, LLC) \n}}\n| url              = {{URL|https://www.hulu.com/}} (US)<br /> {{URL|https://www.hulu.jp/}} (Japan)\n| alexa            = {{Increase}} 212 {{small|{{nowrap|(Global, {{as of|2020|01|14|alt=January 2020}})}}}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/hulu.com|title=hulu.com Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic - Alexa|website=www.alexa.com|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n| website_type     = {{plainlist|\n* [[Entertainment]]\n* [[Over-the-top media services|OTT platform]]}}\n| advertising      = Most plans ad-supported.\n| registration     = Required\n| users            = {{Unbulleted list|\n* 30.4 million {{asof|2020|2|3|df=US}}\n* 3.2 million (Hulu with Live TV) {{asof|2020|2|3|df=US}}<ref name=\"HuluSubsQ12020\"/>\n}}\n| language         = English<br>Japanese \n| current_status   = <!--- Active --->\n}}\n\n'''Hulu''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|u\u02d0|l|u\u02d0}}) is a U.S.-based [[subscription video on demand]] service fully controlled and majority-owned by [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]], a business segment of [[The Walt Disney Company]], with [[NBCUniversal]], owned by [[Comcast]], as an [[Equity (finance)|equity]] stakeholder. \n\nThe service was initially established as a [[joint venture]] between [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] and [[NBCUniversal|NBC Universal]], [[Providence Equity Partners]], and later [[The Walt Disney Company]], serving as an aggregation of recent episodes of television series from their respective [[television network]]s. In 2010, Hulu launched a subscription service, initially [[brand]]ed as ''Hulu Plus'', which featured full seasons of programs from the companies and other partners, and [[broadcast delay|undelayed]] access to new episodes. In 2017, the company launched ''Hulu with Live TV''\u2014an [[Over-the-top media services|over-the-top]] [[IPTV]] service featuring [[linear television]] channels. Time Warner (now [[WarnerMedia]]) later held a stake in the service. As of the first quarter of 2020, Hulu had 30.4 million subscribers.<ref name=\"HuluSubsQ12020\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/disney-plus-reaches-26-5-million-subscribers-1203492187/|title=Disney Plus Reaches 28.6 Million Subscribers, Hulu Hits 30.4 Million|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | first = Cynthia|last=Littleton|date=February 4, 2020|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Disney [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquired 21st Century Fox]], giving it a 60% [[controlling interest|majority stake]] in Hulu. [[AT&T]] (which acquired Time Warner in 2018) sold back its roughly 10% stake the following month. Comcast, the only other shareholder, announced on May 14, 2019,    that it had agreed to cede its control to Disney, and reached an agreement for Disney to purchase its 33% stake in the company as early as 2024. Hulu will be operated as a bridge brand alongside Disney's fellow OTT ventures [[Disney+]] and [[ESPN+]], with Hulu positioned as its streaming brand for general entertainment outside of Disney's [[family-friendly|family-oriented]] movies, shows and properties.<ref name=\"DisneyIstakingfullcontrolofHulu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/14/media/disney-buys-comcast-hulu-ownership/index.html|title=Disney is taking full control of Hulu|work=CNN|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=July 24, 2019|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie}}</ref>\n\n== Name ==\nThe name Hulu comes from two [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] words, ''h\u00fal\u00fa'' ([[wikt:\u846b\u82a6|\u846b\u82a6]]/[[wikt:\u846b\u8606|\u846b\u8606]]), \"[[calabash]]; bottle gourd\", and ''h\u00f9l\u00f9'' ([[wikt:\u4e92\u5f55|\u4e92\u5f55]]/[[wikt:\u4e92\u9304|\u4e92\u9304]]), \"interactive recording\". The company blog explains:\n<blockquote>In Mandarin, ''Hulu'' has two interesting meanings, each highly relevant to our mission. The primary meaning interested us because it is used in an ancient Chinese proverb that describes the Hulu as the holder of precious things. It literally translates to \"gourd,\" and in ancient times, the Hulu was hollowed out and used to hold precious things. The secondary meaning is \"interactive recording\". We saw both definitions as appropriate bookends and highly relevant to the mission of Hulu.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kilar|first=Jason|title=What's in a Name?|date=2008-05-14|url=http://blog.hulu.com/2008/05/13/meaning-of-hulu/|accessdate=2010-07-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717203005/http://blog.hulu.com/2008/05/13/meaning-of-hulu/|archive-date=2011-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== History ==\nKey executives instrumental in the founding of Hulu include Bruce Campbell,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://corporate.discovery.com/our-company/leadership/|title=Leadership \u2013 Discovery Communications, Inc.|website=corporate.discovery.com|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529041516/https://corporate.discovery.com/our-company/leadership/|archive-date=2016-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> Peter Chernin,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/peter-chernin-offers-500m-hulu-84381/|title=Peter Chernin Offers $500M for Hulu|date=2013-04-05|website=TheWrap|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020070543/http://www.thewrap.com/peter-chernin-offers-500m-hulu-84381/|archive-date=2016-10-20|url-status=live}}</ref> JB Perrette,<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.wired.com/2008/09/mf-hulu/|title=Free, Legal and Online: Why Hulu Is the New Way to Watch TV|journal=WIRED|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527061240/http://www.wired.com/2008/09/mf-hulu/|archive-date=2016-05-27|url-status=live|date=2008-09-22}}</ref> Michael Lang,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/01/we-happy-miramax-deal-brings-hundreds-of-movies-to-hulu-hulu-plus/|title=We Happy? Miramax Deal Brings Hundreds Of Movies To Hulu Plus (And To Hulu)|last=Wauters|first=Robin|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2016-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503174249/http://techcrunch.com/2011/06/01/we-happy-miramax-deal-brings-hundreds-of-movies-to-hulu-hulu-plus/|archive-date=2016-05-03|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Beth Comstock]] and [[Jason Kilar]]. The venture was announced in March 2006 with [[AOL]], [[NBC Universal]] (now [[Comcast]]), [[Facebook]], [[MSN]], [[Myspace]], and [[Yahoo!]] planned as \"initial distribution partners\". Jason Kilar was named Hulu CEO in late 2007.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070322005690/en/NBC-Universal-News-Corp.-Announce-Deal-Internet |title=NBC Universal and News Corp. Announce Deal with Internet Leaders AOL, MSN, MySpace And Yahoo! to Create a Premium Online Video Site with Unprecedented Reach |publisher=Business Wire |accessdate=12 December 2017 |date=22 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101212907/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20070322005690/en/NBC-Universal-News-Corp.-Announce-Deal-Internet |archive-date=1 January 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"foe\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-still-on-top/newsanalysis/technet/10346071.html |title=Google's Still on Top |accessdate=2007-08-29 |date=2007-03-22 |author=Nat Worden |work=[[TheStreet.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930180547/http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-still-on-top/newsanalysis/technet/10346071.html |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref>\n\nThe name ''Hulu'' was chosen in late August 2007, when the website went live, with an announcement only and no content. It invited users to leave their email addresses for the upcoming [[Software release life cycle|beta test]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-new-foe-hulu/newsanalysis/mediaentertainment/10376991.html |title=Google's New Foe: Hulu |accessdate=2007-08-29 |date=2007-08-29 |author=Nat Worden |work=[[TheStreet.com]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904013423/http://www.thestreet.com/s/googles-new-foe-hulu/newsanalysis/mediaentertainment/10376991.html |archivedate=2007-09-04 }}</ref> In October 2007, Hulu began the private beta testing by invitation, and later allowed users to invite friends.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20071028005079/en/Hulu-Debuts-Private-Beta-Distribution-Partners-AOL |title=Hulu Debuts via Private Beta and on Distribution Partners AOL, Comcast, MSN, MySpace and Yahoo! |publisher=Business Wire |accessdate=11 December 2017 |date=20 October 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222050812/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20071028005079/en/Hulu-Debuts-Private-Beta-Distribution-Partners-AOL |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Hulu launched for public access in the United States on March 12, 2008.<ref name=\"pr_launch\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080312005454/en/Hulu.com-Opens-Public-Offers-Free-Streams-Hit\n|title=Hulu.com Opens to Public, Offers Free Streams of Hit TV Shows, Movies and Clips from More Than 50 Providers Including FOX, NBC Universal, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Studios Inc. and Sony Pictures Television |publisher=Business Wire\n|accessdate=11 December 2017 |date=12 March 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051815/https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20080312005454/en/Hulu.com-Opens-Public-Offers-Free-Streams-Hit |archive-date=22 December 2017 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The first product to launch was the HULU Syndication network, which was designed and developed by the NBC Universal team from New York, on October 29, 2007, followed by the Hulu.com destinations site.\n\nHulu began an advertising campaign during NBC's broadcast of [[Super Bowl XLIII]] with an initial ad starring [[Alec Baldwin]] titled \"Alec in Huluwood\".<ref name=\"TV Ads\">{{cite web |url= http://www.hulu.com/watch/58538/hulu-tv-ads-alec-in-huluwood |title= Hulu TV Ads: Alec in Huluwood |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work= Hulu |publisher= Hulu |accessdate= May 10, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090508080115/http://www.hulu.com/watch/58538/hulu-tv-ads-alec-in-huluwood |archive-date= 2009-05-08 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The ad intended to humorously reveal \"the shocking secret behind Hulu\", portraying the site as being an \"evil plot to destroy the world\" by suggesting that Baldwin is really an alien in disguise.<ref name=\"hulu-shock\">{{cite web |url= http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-10150197-36.html |title= Hulu to shock the world with Super Bowl ad |last= McCarthy |first= Caroline |date= January 26, 2009 |publisher= CNET News |accessdate= February 2, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090806043548/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13577_3-10150197-36.html |archive-date= August 6, 2009 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> Advertisements have since aired featuring [[Eliza Dushku]], [[Seth MacFarlane]], [[Denis Leary]], and [[Will Arnett]].\n\nIn July 2007, [[Providence Equity Partners]], the owner of [[Newport Television]], became one of the earliest \"outside\" investors by purchasing a 10 percent stake in the company for [[United States dollar|US$]]100 million [[equity (finance)|equity investment]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cable360.net/competition/web/25376.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120906054018/http://www.cable360.net/competition/web/25376.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 6, 2012 |title=NBC and Fox Jump Through Hulu Hoop |accessdate=2007-08-29 |date=August 29, 2006 |first=Shirley |last=Brady |work=Cable360.net }}</ref> before the company was known as \"Hulu\".<ref name=\"SoldStake\" /> With its investment came a seat on the board of directors, where Providence was said to act as an \"independent voice on the board\".<ref name=\"SoldStake\" /> In April 2009, [[The Walt Disney Company]] joined the Hulu consortium as a stakeholder, with plans to offer content from [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and [[Disney Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-us-disney-hulu-043009-2009apr30-story.html|title=Disney joins NBC and News Corp. with Hulu stake|date=2009-04-30|website=San Diego Union-Tribune|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.multichannel.com/news/disney-takes-stake-hulu-video-site-298847|title=Disney Takes Stake In Hulu Video Site|last=Spangler|first=Todd|website=Multichannel|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/disney-signs-onto-hulu/|title=Disney signs onto Hulu|last=McCarthy|first=Caroline|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Providence sold its 10 percent stake to \"Hulu's media owners\" and ceased participation in the board.<ref name=\"SoldStake\">{{cite news|url = https://techcrunch.com/2012/10/12/providence-equity-sells-its-stake-in-hulu/|title = It's Done: Early Hulu Investor Providence Equity Partners Has Sold Its Stake For $200M|accessdate = 2012-05-12|date = May 12, 2012|first = Ryan|last = Lawler|work = techcrunch.com|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121013055831/http://techcrunch.com/2012/10/12/providence-equity-sells-its-stake-in-hulu/|archive-date = October 13, 2012|url-status = live|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2010, Hulu chief executive Jason Kilar said the service had made a profit in two quarters and that the company could top $100 million in revenue by summer 2010, more than its income for all of 2009. [[ComScore]] says monthly video streams reached 903 million in January 2010, over three times the figure for a year earlier,<ref name=\"Stelter\">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2011517934_bthulufuture05.html?syndication=rss|title=Hulu, the online-video hub, contemplates its future|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|last2=Stone|first2=Brad|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2010-04-05|accessdate=2010-04-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622021349/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2011517934_bthulufuture05.html?syndication=rss|archive-date=2011-06-22|url-status=live}}</ref> and second only to [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"Grotticelli\">{{cite news|url=http://broadcastengineering.com/news/hulu-plans-subscripiton-service-0426/ |title=Hulu plans subscription service |last=Grotticelli |first=Michael |work=Broadcast Engineering |date=2010-04-26 |accessdate=2010-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704080501/http://broadcastengineering.com/news/hulu-plans-subscripiton-service-0426/ |archivedate=2010-07-04 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 16, 2010, a report revealed that Hulu was planning an [[initial public offering]] (IPO) which could value the company at more than $2 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20100816/tc_nm/us_hulu_ipo|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820123350/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20100816/tc_nm/us_hulu_ipo|url-status=dead|title=U.S. video viewing site Hulu plans an IPO: report|archivedate=August 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Dealbook |url=http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/16/hulu-is-said-to-be-ready-for-an-i-p-o/ |title=Hulu Is Said to Be Ready for an I.P.O |publisher=Dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com |date=2010-08-16 |accessdate=2010-12-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101022161929/http://dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/16/hulu-is-said-to-be-ready-for-an-i-p-o/ |archive-date=2010-10-22 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2011, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that an \"unsolicited offer\" caused Hulu to begin \"weighing whether to sell itself\".<ref>{{cite news |author= Vascellaro |url= https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303936704576400133483416612 |title= Website Hulu Considers Sale |work= [[The Wall Street Journal]] |date= 2011-06-21 |accessdate= 2011-06-21 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150328030500/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303936704576400133483416612 |archive-date= 2015-03-28 |url-status= live }}</ref> However, on October 13, 2011, Hulu and its owners announced that they would not sell the company, as none of the bidders offered an amount that was satisfactory to its owners.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://mashable.com/2011/10/13/no-hulu-sale/ |title= Hulu Is No Longer For Sale |last1= Parr |first1= Ben |date= October 13, 2011 |work= [[Mashable]] |publisher= Mashable, Inc. |accessdate= June 14, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130521112923/http://mashable.com/2011/10/13/no-hulu-sale/ |archive-date= May 21, 2013 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHulu generated $420 million in revenue in 2011, $80 million short of the company's target.<ref>{{cite web |last= Van Grove |first= Jennifer |date= January 31, 2012 |title= Hulu CEO Jason Kilar: Original programming is an important part of the agenda. |url= https://venturebeat.com/2012/01/31/hulu-jason-kilar/ |work= VentureBeat |access-date= August 31, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170703055106/https://venturebeat.com/2012/01/31/hulu-jason-kilar/ |archive-date= July 3, 2017 |url-status= live |df= mdy-all }}</ref> The vacant CEO post was officially filled by former Fox Networks President Mike Hopkins on October 17, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Hopkins Named CEO of Hulu|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20131017006396/en/Mike-Hopkins-Named-CEO-Hulu|accessdate=17 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020060749/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20131017006396/en/Mike-Hopkins-Named-CEO-Hulu|archive-date=20 October 2013|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2013-10-17}}</ref> Fox Networks Group COO Randy Freer was named CEO on October 24, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/hulu-randy-freer-named-new-ceo-succeed-mike-hopkins-1202193844/|title=Hulu Names Randy Freer New CEO To Succeed Mike Hopkins|last=Andreeva |first=Nellie|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 24, 2017|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Disney ownership ===\nIn December 2017, Disney announced that they would [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquire 21st Century Fox]], including its 30% stake in Hulu, in a sale completed on March 20, 2019. The deal resulted in Disney having a controlling 60% interest in Hulu.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/12/14/media/disney-fox-deal/index.html|title=Disney is buying most of 21st Century Fox for $52.4 billion|last=Riley|first=Charles and [[Hadas Gold]]|work=CNNMoney|access-date=2018-01-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180121041657/http://money.cnn.com/2017/12/14/media/disney-fox-deal/index.html|archive-date=2018-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/fox-corporation-debut-disney-murdoch-1203165925/|title=Fox Corporation Emerges as Standalone Entity, Paul Ryan Joins Board|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|last2=Steinberg|first2=Brian|date=March 18, 2019|website=Variety|language=en|accessdate=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2019, [[AT&T]] (via [[WarnerMedia]]) sold its 9.5% stake in Hulu back to the company for $1.43 billion.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/15/att-sells-hulu-stake-valuing-company-at-15-billion.html|title=AT&T sells Hulu stake, valueing company at $15 billion|last=Levy|first=Ari|date=2019-04-15|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-04-15}}</ref> WarnerMedia plans to launch [[HBO Max]], its own competing service featuring content from its entertainment brands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-att-streaming-service-20181010-story.html |title=WarnerMedia announces new streaming service to compete with Netflix and Disney |last=Faughnder |first=Ryan |first2=Wendy |last2=Lee |website=Los Angeles Times |access-date=October 13, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Huluownership.jpg|alt=Ownership history of Hulu.|left|thumb|257x257px|Ownership history of Hulu.]]\nOn May 14, 2019, Comcast relinquished its control in Hulu to Disney effective immediately. As a result, the streaming service became a division of [[Walt Disney Direct-to-Consumer & International]] with Comcast effectively becoming a [[Partnership#Silent partners|silent partner]]. Under the agreement, Comcast's 33% stake can be sold to Disney at [[fair market value]] as early as 2024. The fair market value will be determined at that time, but Disney guaranteed a minimum valuation of the entire company at $27.5 billion (valuing the Comcast stake as worth at least $5.8 billion).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/what-expect-hulu-under-disneys-control-1212776|title=\"Older, Broader, Edgier\": What to Expect From Hulu Under Disney's Control|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|date=May 22, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref> Randy Freer would report to Disney executive [[Kevin A. Mayer|Kevin Mayer]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nIn the wake of the deal, Disney CEO [[Bob Iger]] explained that direct integration of Hulu with Disney's studios would allow increased investments in original content,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/06/18/hulu-ceo-expect-more-original-content-now-that-disney-is-in-control.html|title=Hulu CEO: Expect to see more original content now that Disney is in control|last=Whitten|first=Sarah|date=June 18, 2019|work=CNBC|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref> which would in turn allow it to \"make the service even more compelling and a greater value for consumers\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/14/comcast-has-agreed-to-sell-its-stake-in-hulu-in-5-years.html|title=Disney to take full control over Hulu, Comcast has option to sell its stake in 5 years|last=Sherman|first=Lauren Feiner,Christine Wang,Alex|date=2019-05-14|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/disney-full-control-hulu-comcast-deal-1203214338/|title=Disney Assumes Full Control of Hulu in Deal With Comcast|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2019-05-14|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nNBCUniversal will continue to license its content to the service through at least 2024, but it will have the option to begin transitioning its exclusivity deals with Hulu to non-exclusive terms beginning in 2020, and to end other content deals beginning in 2022.<ref name=\"Disney\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/14/comcast-has-agreed-to-sell-its-stake-in-hulu-in-5-years.html|title=Disney to take full control over Hulu, Comcast has option to sell its stake in 5 years|last=Feiner|first=Lauren|last2=Wang|first2=Christine|last3=Sherman|first3=Alex|work=CNBC|date=May 14, 2019|accessdate=May 14, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, NBCUniversal had announced an intent to launch its own competing streaming platform known as [[Peacock (streaming service)|Peacock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/nbcuniversal-entering-the-streaming-wars-with-2020-launch-of-bonnie-hammer-run-service-mark-lazarus-jeff-schell-get-major-promotions-1202534914|title=NBCUniversal Entering The Streaming Wars With 2020 Launch Of Bonnie Hammer-Run Service; Mark Lazarus, Jeff Shell Also Get Major Promotions|last1=Hayes|first1=Dade|date=January 14, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191030214327/https://deadline.com/2019/01/nbcuniversal-entering-the-streaming-wars-with-2020-launch-of-bonnie-hammer-run-service-mark-lazarus-jeff-schell-get-major-promotions-1202534914/|archive-date=October 30, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDisney stated that its control of Hulu was the third major component of its direct-to-consumer strategy, complimenting its sports streaming service [[ESPN+]], and its then-forthcoming [[Disney+]] (which would be focused primarily on [[family-friendly]] content from Disney's flagship franchises and studios). Hulu would be oriented towards \"general\" entertainment and content targeting mature audiences.<ref name=\"deadline-norrated\">{{cite web |author=Mike Fleming Jr. |title=Disney Unveils Inaugural Streaming Service Launch Slate To Town; No R-Rated Fare |url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/disney-streaming-service-launch-slate-star-wars-marvel-1202281846/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=April 5, 2018 |date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226065353/http://deadline.com/2018/02/disney-streaming-service-launch-slate-star-wars-marvel-1202281846/ |archivedate=February 26, 2018 }}</ref> \n\nOn July 31, 2019, Disney reorganized Hulu's reporting structure, placing Hulu's Scripted Originals team under [[Walt Disney Television]]. Under the new structure, Hulu's SVP of Original Scripted Content would report directly to the chairman of Disney Television Studios and ABC Entertainment.<ref name=\"HuluWDTV\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/hulu-scripted-originals-disney-tv-erwich-1203287122/ |title=Walt Disney Television Gains Oversight of Hulu's Scripted Originals Content Team |publisher = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date= July 31, 2019 | accessdate = July 31, 2019 | first = Elaine | last = Low}}</ref> As of November 2019, [[FX (TV channel)#FX Networks|FX]] and [[Searchlight Pictures|Fox Searchlight]] were assigned to supply Hulu with content.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Littleton |first1=Cynthia |last2=Littleton |first2=Cynthia |title=FX to Produce Original Series for Hulu as Brands Become More Closely Intertwined |url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/fx-hulu-disney-mrs-america-american-horror-story-1203397601/ |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |work=Variety |date=November 7, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Disney eliminated the role of Hulu CEO, as part of fully integrating Hulu with Disney's business model. Under the new structure, top Hulu executives would report directly to DTCI and Walt Disney Television leads.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/hulu-ceo-randy-freer-exits-streamer-is-integrated-into-disneys-direct-to-consumer-international-1202848283/ | title = Hulu CEO Randy Freer Exits As Streamer Is Integrated Into Disney's Direct-to-Consumer & International Unit | publisher = [[Deadline Hollywood]] | first = Nellie | last = Andreeva | date = January 31, 2020 | accessdate = January 31, 2020}}</ref> On January 31, 2020, CEO Randy Freer resigned from his role as part of a major restructuring of Disney's streaming business;<ref>{{cite news|last=Flint|first=Joe|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hulu-ceo-randy-freer-to-exit-as-part-of-disney-restructuring-11580512202|title=Hulu CEO Randy Freer to Exit as Part of Disney Restructuring|date=2020-01-31|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref> a part of the restructuring, Disney announced on February 25, 2020 that Kelly Campbell would run Hulu as president, reporting to DTCI Chairman, Kevin Mayer.<ref name=\"HuluPresident\">{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-promotes-kelly-campbell-run-hulu-1281088 | title = Disney Promotes Kelly Campbell to Run Hulu | publisher = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | first = Natalie| last = Jarvey | date = February 25, 2020 | accessdate = February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Partners ==\nFollowing the start of its service, Hulu signed deals with several new content providers making additional material available to consumers. On April 30, 2009, [[The Walt Disney Company]] announced that it would join the venture, purchasing a 27 percent stake in Hulu.<ref name=\"abchulu\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/30/AR2009043001853.html|title=It's Official: Disney Joins News Corp., NBCU In Hulu; Deal Includes Some Cable Nets|author=Kramer, Staci D.|date=April 30, 2006|accessdate=October 30, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504054305/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/30/AR2009043001853.html|archive-date=May 4, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nStarting August 15, 2011, viewers of content from Fox and related networks are required to authenticate paid cable or satellite service wherever Fox streams episodes, including on Hulu, to be able to watch them the morning after the first airing. Non-subscribers will see those episodes delayed a week before they are viewable.<ref>[[Brian Stelter]], ''[[The New York Times]]''. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/27/business/media/fox-to-limit-next-day-streaming-on-hulu.html Fox to Limit Next-Day Streaming on Hulu to Paying Cable Customers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531154143/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/27/business/media/fox-to-limit-next-day-streaming-on-hulu.html |date=2013-05-31 }}\". July 26, 2011. Retrieved July 28, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn October 28, 2011, Hulu announced that they had inked a five-year deal with [[The CW]], giving the streaming site access to next-day content from five of the six major networks.<ref>Wasserman, Todd, [[Mashable]] [http://mashable.com/2011/10/28/hulu-gossip-girl-cw/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111030165419/http://mashable.com/2011/10/28/hulu-gossip-girl-cw/ |date=2011-10-30 }}</ref> On September 18, 2013, Hulu announced a multi-year deal with the [[BBC]] that will deliver 2,000 episodes from 144 different titles in the first 12 months.<ref>{{cite web | title = Hulu BBC Deal, A Positive Step After Some Cloudy Times | url = http://ceoworld.biz/2013/09/18/hulu-bbc-deal-a-positive-step-after-some-cloudy-times | work = CEOWORLD Magazine | date = 18 September 2013 | access-date = 20 August 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130928075905/http://ceoworld.biz/2013/09/18/hulu-bbc-deal-a-positive-step-after-some-cloudy-times | archive-date = 28 September 2013 | url-status = live | df = dmy-all }}</ref> \n\nIn 2015, Hulu began offering content from [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] for an additional $8.99/month, which is cheaper than Showtime's own streaming service. On June 16, 2016, Hulu announced a deal with the Disney-ABC Television Group for the exclusive SVOD rights to past seasons of seven Disney Channel, Disney Junior and Disney XD series, and more than 20 Disney Channel original movies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adweek.com/news/television/hulu-makes-big-kids-programming-push-new-disney-channel-deal-172048 |title=Hulu Makes Big Kids Programming Push With New Disney Channel Deal |work=[[Ad Week]] |access-date=17 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160617144309/http://www.adweek.com/news/television/hulu-makes-big-kids-programming-push-new-disney-channel-deal-172048 |archive-date=17 June 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe CW's agreement with Hulu ended September 18, 2016; in-season streaming of current CW programs moved to the network's own digital platforms, and Netflix began to carry past seasons of The CW's programs through 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/official-netflix-cw-reach-new-908442|title=It's Official: Netflix, The CW Reach New Streaming Pact|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> {{As of|2017|January}}, a limited amount of content from [[CBS]]'s library is available on-demand, mostly limited to shows that are no longer producing new episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.hulu.com/articles/22330147|title=CBS shows on Hulu|website=help.hulu.com|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105084731/https://help.hulu.com/articles/22330147|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulu.com/companies/cbs|title=CBS|website=Hulu|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105080054/http://www.hulu.com/companies/cbs|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 4, 2017, it was reported that a deal was reached to bring live broadcasts of CBS and several affiliated channels to Hulu's upcoming live streaming service<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-cbs-corp-hulu-deal-idUSKBN14O1Y1|title=CBS signs deal to be on Hulu's live-streaming platform|date=2017-01-04|publisher=Reuters|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170104233511/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-cbs-corp-hulu-deal-idUSKBN14O1Y1|archive-date=2017-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as to make more shows available on-demand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/04/hulu-adds-cbs-to-its-upcoming-live-tv-service/|title=Hulu adds CBS to its upcoming live TV service|publisher=[[Engadget]]|access-date=2017-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105061502/https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/04/hulu-adds-cbs-to-its-upcoming-live-tv-service/|archive-date=2017-01-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Hulu announced a partnership with [[Spotify]] that allows users to purchase both streaming services for a discounted price per month. This discount also includes an even more discounted rate for university students.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17222646/spotify-hulu-bundle-deal-now-available-pricing|title=Now you can get Spotify and Hulu together for just $12.99 each month|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412001334/https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/11/17222646/spotify-hulu-bundle-deal-now-available-pricing|archive-date=2018-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\n\n=== {{anchor|Hulu Plus}} Hulu subscription service ===\nAt an industry conference held on October 21, 2009, [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] Deputy Chairman [[Chase Carey]] stated that Hulu \"needs to evolve to have a meaningful subscription model as part of its business\" and that it would likely start charging for at least some content by 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/blog/ADverse_Atkinson_on_Advertising/23941-Chase_Carey_Hulu_to_Charge_in_2010.php?nid=2228&source=title&rid=6454445 |title=Chase Carey: Hulu to Charge in 2010 |date=2009-10-21 |author=Atkinson, Claire |work=Broadcasting & Cable |publisher=Reed Business Information |accessdate=2009-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025045542/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/blog/ADverse_Atkinson_on_Advertising/23941-Chase_Carey_Hulu_to_Charge_in_2010.php?nid=2228&source=title&rid=6454445 |archive-date=2009-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carey's comment jibes with other News Corp. heads, including Rupert Murdoch who has expressed a desire to charge for content with a number of online units.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-10381622-261.html |title=More signs Hulu subscription service is coming |first=Greg |last=Sandoval |date=October 22, 2009 |accessdate=November 4, 2009 |work=Media Maverick |publisher=CNET |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617000040/http://news.cnet.com/8301-31001_3-10381622-261.html |archive-date=June 17, 2011 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHulu's subscription service was launched in [[Beta test|beta (preview)]] on June 29, 2010,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/29/hulu-unveils-subscription-service-for-9-99-a-month/ |title=Hulu Unveils Subscription Service For $9.99 a Month |first=Brian |last=Stelter |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2014 |work=New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112160157/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/29/hulu-unveils-subscription-service-for-9-99-a-month/ |archive-date=12 November 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and officially launched on November 17, 2010 under the branding '''Hulu Plus'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/17/hulu-drops-prices-to-compete-with-netflix/ |title=Hulu Drops Prices to Compete With Netflix |first=Brian |last=Stelter |date=27 November 2010 |accessdate=12 November 2014 |work=New York Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112161947/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/17/hulu-drops-prices-to-compete-with-netflix/ |archive-date=12 November 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  The service remains advertising-supported, but it offers an expanded content library including full seasons, day-after access to current season content and more episodes of shows available. Hulu also launched Hulu Plus apps on other types of devices, including mobile, [[digital media player]]s, and [[video game console]]s. By the end of 2011, Hulu Plus had around 1.5 million subscribers.<ref>Nakashima, Ryan January 13, 2012. [http://www.newsday.com/business/hulu-plus-ends-year-with-1-5-million-subscribers-1.3448597 \"Hulu Plus ends year with 1.5 million subscribers\"].</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2015, it was announced that the \"Hulu Plus\" branding would be discontinued, and that the service would be henceforth marketed as simply \"Hulu\" to place it in-line with its subscription-only competitors. By then, the service had grown to 9 million subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/hulu-makes-name-change-official-ditches-the-plus-1201520583/|title=Hulu Makes Name Change Official, Ditches the Plus|last=Roettgers|first=Janko|last2=Roettgers|first2=Janko|date=2015-06-16|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=Advertising Age|url=http://adage.com/article/media/hulu-drop-hulu-brand-picks-seinfeld/298305/|title=Hulu Will Drop Hulu Plus Brand, Picks up 'Seinfeld'|accessdate=September 13, 2015|author=Peterson, Tim|date=April 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906123704/http://adage.com/article/media/hulu-drop-hulu-brand-picks-seinfeld/298305/|archive-date=September 6, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Wall Street Journal'' reported in July 2015 that Hulu was exploring an advertising-free subscription option for around $12 to $14 a month.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Shields|url=https://www.wsj.com/article_email/hulu-explores-adding-ad-free-option-to-its-service-1437103682-lMyQjAxMTI1MzE1NzIxMDc2Wj|title=Hulu Explores Adding Ad-Free Option to Its Service|date=July 16, 2015|publisher=Wall Street Journal|access-date=March 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109235948/http://www.wsj.com/article_email/hulu-explores-adding-ad-free-option-to-its-service-1437103682-lMyQjAxMTI1MzE1NzIxMDc2Wj|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> This was confirmed as going forward {{as of|2015|September|2|lc=y|df=US}}, with a \"No Commercials\" plan priced at $11.99, $4 more than the $7.99 monthly rate for a \"Limited Commercials\" subscription,<ref>{{cite web|title = Hulu \u2013 About|url = http://www.hulu.com/about|website = Hulu|accessdate = 2015-04-08|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150406223353/http://www.hulu.com/about|archive-date = 2015-04-06|url-status = live}}</ref> though a few highlighted network series (less than 10) would retain pre-roll and post-roll{{clarification|date=April 2020}} ad pods.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/hulu-adds-mostly-ad-free-subscription-service-1201583375/|title=Hulu Adds (Mostly) Ad-Free Subscription Service|last=Wallenstein|first=Andrew|date=2 September 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=2 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150903042841/http://variety.com/2015/digital/news/hulu-adds-mostly-ad-free-subscription-service-1201583375/|archive-date=3 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Starting in 2019, Hulu plans to begin displaying on-screen ads when the viewer pauses the show, although it is unclear whether this will apply to customers on the $11.99/month No Ads plan.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Anthony|last=Ha| url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/31/hulu-pause-ad/ | title=Hulu announces a new ad unit that appears when you pause|website=[[TechCrunch]]|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Hulu announced that it had reached 12 million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|title=Hulu closes in on 12 million subscribers; plans cable-like TV option|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/05/04/media/hulu-subscribers-cable-bundle/|website=CNN Money|publisher=CNN|accessdate=1 November 2016|date=4 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103234634/http://money.cnn.com/2016/05/04/media/hulu-subscribers-cable-bundle/|archive-date=3 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In January 2018, Hulu announced that it had reached 17 million subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Stelter|first1=Brian|title=Hulu closes in on 12 million subscribers; plans cable-like TV option|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/9/16868864/hulu-17-million-subscribers-announced-2018|website=theverge.com|publisher=Verge|accessdate=6 February 2018|date=9 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207123153/https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/9/16868864/hulu-17-million-subscribers-announced-2018|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2016, Hulu announced that it would discontinue its free video on-demand content, and syndicate it to [[Yahoo!]] on a new website known as [[Yahoo! View]]. This service features recent episodes of ABC, Fox, and NBC series. The Hulu website is now devoted exclusively to the subscription service.<ref name=\"wp-hulunofree\">{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Fung|title=This is the end of Hulu as we know it|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/08/08/hulu-is-getting-rid-of-what-made-it-famous/|website=Washington Post|accessdate=9 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809122415/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/08/08/hulu-is-getting-rid-of-what-made-it-famous/|archive-date=9 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|title=Hulu to End Free TV Service|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hulu-end-free-tv-service-917917|accessdate=August 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=August 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808222239/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hulu-end-free-tv-service-917917|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Brodkin|first=Jon|title=Hulu will soon end its free streaming options|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/08/hulus-free-shows-move-to-yahoo-as-it-becomes-a-paid-only-service/|accessdate=August 8, 2016|work=Ars Technica|date=August 8, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808160803/http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/08/hulus-free-shows-move-to-yahoo-as-it-becomes-a-paid-only-service/|archive-date=August 8, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Hulu introduced [[5.1 surround sound]] on select devices for its original content.<ref>[https://help.hulu.com/en-us/sound-quality Audio quality on Hulu]. Hulu.</ref> In December 2016 Hulu began streaming content in [[4K resolution|4K]], also limited to its original content.<ref>[https://www.hulu.com/press/4k-ultra-hd-now-streaming-on-hulu/ 4K Ultra HD Now Streaming on Hulu]. Hulu Press Release. 2 December 2016.</ref> 4K video was quietly rolled back in 2018, and reintroduced in July 2019. [[High-dynamic-range video|HDR]] video is not supported.<ref>[https://www.cordcutters.com/can-you-get-4k-hdr-video-hulu Can you get 4K HDR video on Hulu?] Cord Cutters. 4 October 2018.</ref><ref>[https://bgr.com/2019/07/12/hulu-4k-streaming-devices-original-shows/ Hulu finally brings back 4K streaming after killing it last year]. BGR. 12 July 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/home-theater/4k-back-on-hulu/|title=Hulu Brings Back 4K Streaming, But There Are Some Major Limitations|date=2019-10-14|website=Digital Trends|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, 2019, Hulu announced a $2 price drop for the basic ad-supported plan to $5.99. The $5.99 monthly plan has previously been offered as a promotional offer since late 2017 where users that signed up (or reactivated accounts that had previously ended their service) during the offer period would keep the price for an entire year before paying the regular rate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Welch |first1=Chris |title=Hulu drops to just $5.99 per month after Netflix's price hikes |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/1/23/18193539/hulu-price-change-subscription-ads-live-tv-2019 |website=The Verge |accessdate=23 January 2019 |date=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSince the launch of Disney+ in November 2019, the service has been available in a bundle with ESPN+ and the ad-supported tier of Hulu, priced at US$12.99 per-month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/6/20757626/disney-plus-espn-hulu-bundle-price-date-streaming-service|title=Disney announces $12.99 bundle for Disney+, Hulu, and ESPN+|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2019-08-06|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Hulu + Live TV ===\nIn May 2016, Hulu announced that it planned to begin offering an [[over-the-top content|over-the-top]] [[IPTV]] service with \"live programming from broadcast and cable brands\" some time in 2017.<ref name=\"verge-hululivetv\">{{cite web|title=Hulu confirms plan to stream live TV next year|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11590306/hulu-confirms-live-tv-2017-plans|website=The Verge|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=10 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810115549/http://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11590306/hulu-confirms-live-tv-2017-plans|archive-date=10 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2016-05-04}}</ref> In late 2016, co-owners 21st Century Fox and The Walt Disney Company agreed to supply their channels to the streaming service, joined by Time Warner, which previously reached an agreement with Hulu.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lieberman|first1=David|title=Disney And Fox Agree To Provide Sports And Broadcast Channels To Hulu|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/disney-fox-agree-provide-sports-other-channels-hulu-1201846186/|accessdate=January 24, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030818/http://deadline.com/2016/11/disney-fox-agree-provide-sports-other-channels-hulu-1201846186/|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe service, originally marketed as \"Hulu with Live TV,\" that couples the live TV offerings with Hulu's existing library of television series and films, launched in [[beta testing|beta]] on May 3, 2017. It was later renamed to \"Hulu + Live TV.\" The service \u2013 which provides support for [[Xbox One]], [[Android TV]], [[Apple TV]], [[Chromecast]], [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices \u2013 offers live streams of more than 50 broadcast and cable-originated channels, including feeds of the five major broadcast networks \u2013 ABC, CBS, NBC, Fox and The CW \u2013 as well as cable channels owned by Hulu co-parents NBCUniversal, 21st Century Fox and The Walt Disney Company, along with [[ViacomCBS]], [[Turner Broadcasting System|WarnerMedia Entertainment]], [[Scripps Networks Interactive]] and [[A+E Networks]] (encompassing networks such as [[CNN]], [[Food Network]], [[Disney Channel]], [[A&E (TV network)|A&E]], [[MSNBC]] and [[ESPN]]), with the Showtime OTT service available as an add-on for an extra fee. Hulu representatives stated that it intends to negotiate carriage agreements with independently owned broadcasting groups to gain distribution rights to local stations from additional markets.<ref>{{cite web|title=You can now watch 50-plus channels of live TV on Hulu with $39.99 upgrade|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/05/03/net-video-streamer-hulu-gets-3999-live-tv-upgrade/101218510/|author=Mike Snider|newspaper=USA Today|publisher=Gannett Company|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508210018/https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/05/03/net-video-streamer-hulu-gets-3999-live-tv-upgrade/101218510/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hulu Live TV launches in beta: What you need to know|url=http://www.techhive.com/article/3193912/streaming-services/hulu-live-tv-launches-in-beta-what-you-need-to-know.html|author=Jared Newman|website=[[TechHive]]|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170509022030/http://www.techhive.com/article/3193912/streaming-services/hulu-live-tv-launches-in-beta-what-you-need-to-know.html|archive-date=May 9, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Todd Spangler\">{{cite web|title=Hulu Live TV Service Launches With 50 Channels for $40 Monthly|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-launch-channels-1202407778/|author=Todd Spangler|periodical=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508083536/http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-launch-channels-1202407778/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Todd Spangler\" /> \n\nFeatures include the ability to create up of six user account profiles per a single subscription (with personalized program recommendations based on a user's favorite programs and varying simultaneous streams depending on the package), personalized sports recommendations and a [[cloud computing|cloud]] [[digital video recorder|DVR]] with between 50 and 200 hours of storage depending on the level of service (the lower-tier DVR does not have ad skipping functionality).<ref>{{cite news|title=Hulu just launched its $40-a-month cable-TV competitor \u2014 here are all the details|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/hulu-live-tv-package-details-pricing-channels-features-2017-5|author=Nathan McAlone|website=Business Insider|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170507140451/http://www.businessinsider.com/hulu-live-tv-package-details-pricing-channels-features-2017-5|archive-date=May 7, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hulu launches live TV service|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/03/media/hulu-live-tv-service/index.html|author=Sandra Gonzalez|website=CNN Money|publisher=Time Warner|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503203436/http://money.cnn.com/2017/05/03/media/hulu-live-tv-service/index.html|archive-date=May 3, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hulu Live TV Bundle: Full Channel Lineup|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-full-channel-lineup-1202407833/|author=Todd Spangler|periodical=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=May 3, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508033929/http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-full-channel-lineup-1202407833/|archive-date=May 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hulu Live TV Service Won't Have Viacom Networks|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-no-viacom-networks-1202006300/|author=Todd Spangler|periodical=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512084000/http://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-service-no-viacom-networks-1202006300/|archive-date=May 12, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Subscribers must have a residential broadband connection in order to use the Hulu with Live TV service. The Hulu with Live TV service can be used on mobile devices and networks, but service will be blocked unless the user has accessed the service on the device via their designated \"home\" network within the past 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2020/03/hulus-live-tv-doesnt-work-on-t-mobile-home-internet/|title=Hulu\u2019s live TV doesn\u2019t work on T-Mobile home Internet|last=Brodkin|first=Jon|date=2020-03-06|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe service was initially priced at $39.99 per-month. In December 2019, the price had been increased to $54.99 per month (after having previously been raised to $44.99).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-hulu-20190122-story.html|title=Hulu will raise price of live TV packages, but lower the cost of basic streaming|date=2019-01-23|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/15/hulu-is-increasing-the-price-of-its-hulu-live-stream-starting-dec-18.html|title=Hulu is increasing the price of its Hulu + Live TV 22% starting Dec. 18|last=Cosgrove|first=Elly|date=2019-11-15|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-17}}</ref> By May 2018, the service had reached 800,000 subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/hulu-pay-tv-bundle-hits-800k-subscribers-1202400295/|title=Hulu Pay-TV Bundle Hits 800K Subscribers|last=Hayes|first=Dade|date=2018-05-30|website=Deadline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref> In the third quarter of 2019, Hulu overtook [[Sling TV]] as the top OTT pay television service in the United States, with 2.7 million subscribers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/hulu-live-tv-beats-sling-top-streaming-pay-tv-research-1203406138/|title=Hulu Live TV Tops Sling TV as No. 1 Streaming Pay-TV Service, Analysts Estimate|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2019-11-15|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== Viewership ==\nViewership numbers for the site are tracked by measurement firms such as [[ComScore]], [[Nielsen ratings]], and [[Quantcast]]. In partnership with comScore, Hulu is the first digital company to receive multi-platform measurement at an individual level that includes co-viewing for living room devices. When factoring this in, Hulu's reach among adults aged 18\u201349 increases 50 percent.\n\nHowever, the reliability of these metrics has been drawn into question, partly due to widely divergent estimates. For example, between May and June 2010, ComScore updated its scoring methodology and its estimates for Hulu dropping from 43.5 million unique and special viewers to 24 million in a single month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/26/business/la-fi-ct-hulu-20100721|title=Hulu's sharp decline in viewership underscores inconsistency in measuring size of online audience|publisher=LA Times|author=Dawn C. Chmielewski|date=26 Jul 2010|accessdate=1 Nov 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311095132/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/26/business/la-fi-ct-hulu-20100721|archive-date=11 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a comScore digital trends report in 2010, comScore's Digital Year in Review report found that Hulu was watched twice as much as viewers who watched on the websites of the five major TV networks combined.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schonfeld|first1=Erick|title=ComScore: Hulu Is Watched Twice As Much As The 5 Major TV Networks Online Combined|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/02/07/comscore-hulu-tv-networks/|publisher=TechCrunch|date=7 Feb 2011|access-date=11 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212031532/https://techcrunch.com/2011/02/07/comscore-hulu-tv-networks/|archive-date=12 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHulu in May 2018 announced it has surpassed 20 million subscribers in the United States.<ref name=\"Media Play News\">{{cite news|last1=Gruenwedel|first1=Erik|title=Hulu Tops 20 Million Subs, Inks First Deal with DreamWorks Animation|url=https://www.mediaplaynews.com/hulu-tops-20-million-subs-inks-first-deal-with-dreamworks-animation/|accessdate=May 2, 2018|work=Media Play News|date=May 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503041617/https://www.mediaplaynews.com/hulu-tops-20-million-subs-inks-first-deal-with-dreamworks-animation/|archive-date=May 3, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tally, which puts the company about 36 million subscriptions behind Netflix, was disclosed at a media presentation at the newly named Hulu Theater at Madison Square Garden in New York. Hulu said it has grown total engagement by more than 60%, with 78% of viewing taking place in the living room on connected TVs.\n\n== Programming ==\n\n=== Content partners ===\nHulu distributes video on its own website and syndicates its hosting to other sites,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120519822483125987 |title=Can Hulu Find Its Mojo With Viewers? |accessdate=2008-03-19 |date=2008-03-11 |author=Rebecca Dana and Emily Steel |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109235949/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120519822483125987 |archive-date=2016-01-09 |url-status=live }}</ref> and allows users to embed Hulu clips on their websites.<ref name=\"pr_launch\" /> In addition to NBC, ABC and Fox programs and movies, Hulu carries shows from networks such as [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]], [[Big Ten Network]], [[Bravo (American TV channel)|Bravo]], [[E!]], [[Fox Sports 2]], [[FX (TV channel)|FX]], [[PBS]], [[NFL Network]], [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]], [[RT America]], [[Fox Sports 1]], [[SundanceTV]], [[Syfy]], [[USA Network]], [[NBCSN]], and online comedy sources such as [[Onion News Network]].<ref name=\"The Live Feed\">{{cite web|url= http://www.thrfeed.com/2009/04/abc-to-offer-shows-on-hulu.html|title= ABC to offer shows on Hulu|publisher= The Live Feed|date= April 30, 2009|access-date= December 11, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090504084734/http://www.thrfeed.com/2009/04/abc-to-offer-shows-on-hulu.html|archive-date= May 4, 2009|url-status= live|df= mdy-all}}</ref> Hulu retains between thirty and fifty percent of advertising revenue generated by the shows it distributes.<ref name=\"Stelter\" />\n\nIn November 2009, Hulu also began to establish partnerships with record labels to host music videos and concert performances on the site, including [[EMI]] in November 2009,<ref name=\"emi-hulu\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2356071,00.asp|title=Hulu, EMI Strike Deal for Music Videos, Concerts|date=November 18, 2009|publisher=PC Magazine|accessdate=24 December 2009|first=Chloe|last=Albanesius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121155534/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2356071,00.asp|archive-date=21 November 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Warner Music Group]] in December 2009.<ref name=\"hulu-wmg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2357529,00.asp|title=Hulu, Warner Music Sign Deal for Music Content|date=December 23, 2009|publisher=PC Magazine|accessdate=24 December 2009|first=Chloe|last=Albanesius|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227044623/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2357529,00.asp|archive-date=27 December 2009|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn early March 2010, [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] announced that it was pulling two of the website's most popular shows, ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' and ''[[The Daily Show]]'', off Hulu.<ref name=\"nydn\">''[[New York Daily News]]'' article: \"[http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2010/03/03/2010-03-03_comedy_central_pulls_daily_show_and_colbert_off_hulu.html Comedy Central's 'The Daily Show' and 'The Colbert Report' off Hulu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306151209/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/2010/03/03/2010-03-03_comedy_central_pulls_daily_show_and_colbert_off_hulu.html |date=2010-03-06 }}.\"</ref> The programs had been airing on Hulu since late 2008.<ref name=\"mcn\" /> A spokesman for [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] noted that \"in the current economic model, there is not that much in it for us to continue at this time. If they can get to the point where the monetization model is better, then we may go back.\"<ref name=\"mcn\">Multichannel News article: \"[http://www.multichannel.com/article/449861-Dauman_Vivendi_Could_Return_To_Hulu.php Dauman: Vivendi Could Return To Hulu].\"</ref> In February 2011, both shows were made available for streaming on Hulu again. ''The Daily Show'' was again removed from Hulu in March 2017 in order to push viewers to watch the program on Viacom and Comedy Central's apps.\n\nIn April 2017, Hulu signed a first-run license deal with [[Annapurna Pictures]]. Hulu also has output deals with [[IFC Films]] and [[Magnolia Pictures]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/hulu-annapurna-pictures-movie-output-deal-1202024899 | title=Hulu Inks Annapurna Pictures Pay-One TV Window Movie Output Deal| date=2017-04-06}}</ref>\n\nNew releases from 20th Century Studios will not immediately be available on either Disney+ or Hulu, as it has an existing output deal with [[HBO]] until 2022.<ref name=\"HBO Fox\">{{cite news|title=HBO and 20th Century Fox renew output deal|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-hbo20th-20120815,0,5442974.story|author=Joe Flint|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHulu in May 2018 announced its first-ever license deal with [[DreamWorks Animation]], becoming the exclusive streaming home for future DWA movies feature films, as well as library films. DWA had streamed exclusively through Netflix since 2013.<ref name=\"Media Play News\" /> Films will be available on the service in 2019, while original series will be available later in 2020.\n\nOn December 4, 2018, Hulu confirmed an exclusive multi-year first-look SVOD deal with [[Funimation]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/hulu-funimation-anime-japanese-series-1203079274/ | title=Hulu Lands Funimation First-Look Deal for Japanese Anime Series (EXCLUSIVE)| date=2018-12-04}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Hulu and [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] signed an output deal with [[Lionsgate]], where Hulu and FX would respectably gain the streaming and TV rights to films released under the Lionsgate label in 2020 and 2021.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/lionsgate-hulu-fx-distribution-deal-1203240225/|title=Lionsgate Pacts With Hulu, FX for Two-Year Output Deal|date=June 11, 2019|work=Variety|accessdate=July 30, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Hulu agreed to control the streaming rights to upcoming films released by [[Bleecker Street (company)|Bleecker Street]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/hulu-bleecker-street-partner-on-exclusive-svod-deal-1202661486/|title=Hulu & Bleecker Street Partner On Exclusive SVOD Deal|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|date=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2020, Hulu launched a dedicated \"hub\" for content from FX branded as ''FX on Hulu'', with the service becoming the exclusive streaming outlet for current and past series from the network. Beginning with [[Breeders (TV series)|''Breeders'']], new episodes of FX original series also become available on Hulu immediately after their television airing, and selected series will also premiere exclusively on the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/fx-on-hulu-check-out-the-release-schedule-for-all-/1100-6472637/|title=FX On Hulu: Check Out The Release Schedule For All Your Favorite New Shows|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/disney-fx-hulu-streaming-cate-blanchett-disney-earnings-1202780657/|title=Hulu To Be Official FX Streaming Home Next Year, Bob Iger Says; Cate Blanchett\u2019s \u2018Mrs. America\u2019 & 3 Other Series Move Online|last=Patten|first=Dominic|last2=Patten|first2=Dominic|date=2019-11-07|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/john-landgraf-calls-fx-on-hulu-transformative-opportunity-for-cabler-tca-1202825633/|title=John Landgraf Calls FX On Hulu \u201cTransformative Opportunity\u201d For Cabler As Digital Hub Sets March Launch Plans \u2013 TCA|last=White|first=Peter|last2=White|first2=Peter|date=2020-01-09|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Original content ===\n{{Further|List of original programs distributed by Hulu}}\nFrom January 17, 2011 to April 24, 2014, Hulu streamed its own in-house web series ''[[The Morning After (web series)|The Morning After]]'', a light-hearted pop-culture news show. It was produced by Hulu in conjunction with [[Jace Hall]]'s HDFilms and stars Brian Kimmet and Ginger Gonzaga. Producing the show was a first for the company, which in the past has been primarily a content distributor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gigaom.com/video/new-series-the-morning-after-nudges-hulu-into-production/ |title=New Series The Morning After Nudges Hulu Into Production |date=2011-01-18 |author=Liz Shannon Miller |publisher=GigaOM |accessdate=2011-05-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718145157/http://gigaom.com/video/new-series-the-morning-after-nudges-hulu-into-production/ |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2012, Hulu announced that it would be airing its first original script based program, titled ''[[Battleground (TV series)|Battleground]]'', which premiered in February 2012. The program aired on Hulu's free web service rather than on the subscription-based Hulu Plus. ''Battleground'' is described as a documentary-style political drama.<ref>Rother, Larry, January 16, 2012, [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/16/hulu-announces-first-original-script-based-program/ \"Hulu Announces First Original-Script-Based Program\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065859/https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/16/hulu-announces-first-original-script-based-program/ |date=2017-10-29 }}</ref>\n\nLater that same month, Hulu announced it would air ''The Fashion Fund'', a six-part reality series, and the winner of the show would receive $300,000 to start their career.<ref>Poggi Jeanine January 27, 2012. [http://adage.com/article/mediaworks/hulu-introduces-fashion-fund-original-reality-series/232384/ Hulu Adds Unscripted Series 'The Fashion Fund,' Accelerating Original Content Effort.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120710210257/http://adage.com/article/mediaworks/hulu-introduces-fashion-fund-original-reality-series/232384/ |date=2012-07-10 }}</ref>\n\nTo continue with its original programming movement, Hulu announced that there would be a total of seven original programs that were planned to air on its service: ''Battleground'', ''Day in the Life'', and ''Up to Speed'' were previously mentioned; and on April 19, Hulu added four more shows to its list: ''Don't Quit Your Daydream'', ''Flow'', ''The Awesomes'', and ''We Got Next''. Some of these programs began airing in 2012, while others premiered over the next few years.<ref>{{cite news|author=Perez, Sarah|date=April 19, 2012|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/04/19/hulu-announces-four-more-original-series-will-feature-snl-vets-adrian-grenier-of-hbos-entourage-others/|work=TechCrunch|title=Hulu Announces Four More Original Series|access-date=December 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029174512/https://techcrunch.com/2012/04/19/hulu-announces-four-more-original-series-will-feature-snl-vets-adrian-grenier-of-hbos-entourage-others/|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2012, Hulu announced it would be bringing [[Kevin Smith]] to its line-up of original programming. Smith hosts a movie discussion show titled ''[[Spoilers (TV series)|Spoilers]]'', which began airing in mid-2012.<ref>{{cite news|author=Wasserman, Todd|date=May 21, 2012|title=Hulu to Launch New Show With Kevin Smith Plus 9 Other Titles|url=http://mashable.com/2012/05/21/hulu-new-shows-kevin-smith/|work=Mashable|access-date=December 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029174001/http://mashable.com/2012/05/21/hulu-new-shows-kevin-smith/|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, [[Lionsgate Premiere]] and Hulu jointly acquired distribution rights to the film, ''[[Joshy (film)|Joshy]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/lionsgate-hulu-joshy-1201712664/|title=Lionsgate, Hulu Acquire Comedy 'Joshy'|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anita|last=Busch|date=March 1, 2016|accessdate=March 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302195219/http://deadline.com/2016/03/lionsgate-hulu-joshy-1201712664/|archive-date=March 2, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> which was later released on August 12, 2016.<ref name=\"RELEASE\">{{cite web|url=https://thefilmstage.com/reviews/sundance-review-joshy/|title=Joshy Sundance 2016 Film Review|website=The Film Stage|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=May 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616225857/https://thefilmstage.com/reviews/sundance-review-joshy/|archive-date=June 16, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2016, Hulu acquired ''[[The Beatles: Eight Days a Week]]'', as its first documentary acquisition, as part of a planned Hulu Documentary Films collection.<ref name=\"Kastrenakes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11589950/hulu-documentaries-ron-howard-the-beatles-eight-days-a-week|title=Hulu is getting into documentaries, starting with Ron Howard's Beatles film|last=Kastrenakes|first=Jacob|date=4 May 2016|work=[[The Verge]]|accessdate=16 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507104718/http://www.theverge.com/2016/5/4/11589950/hulu-documentaries-ron-howard-the-beatles-eight-days-a-week|archive-date=7 May 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The film premiered theatrically on September 15, before debuting on the streaming service on September 17.<ref name=\"Beatles Official\">{{cite web|title=Watch the Trailer for ''The Beatles: Eight Days a Week \u2013 The Touring Years''|accessdate=20 June 2016|url=http://www.thebeatles.com/news/watch-trailer-beatles-eight-days-week-touring-years|publisher=[[The Beatles]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624042652/http://www.thebeatles.com/news/watch-trailer-beatles-eight-days-week-touring-years|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== ''South Park'' ===\n{{overly detailed|date=February 2020}}\nOn July 12, 2014, it was announced that Hulu had signed a three-year deal purchasing exclusive online streaming rights to the ''[[South Park]]'' library. Through the deal, the [[South Park]] Studios website became powered by Hulu video and featured advertising.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/pecom/20140712005015/en|title=Hulu and South Park Announce Exclusive Multi-Year Content Licensing Deal at 2014 Television Critics Association Summer Press Tour \u2013 Business Wire|work=businesswire.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212193104/https://www.businesswire.com/news/pecom/20140712005015/en|archive-date=2017-12-12|url-status=live|date=2014-07-12}}</ref> Along with this, the domain name changed from \"southparkstudios.com\" to \"southpark.cc.com\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southparkstudios.com|title=South Park \u2013 Watch Full Episodes, Clips & More|work=southparkstudios.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712171540/http://www.southparkstudios.com/|archive-date=2014-07-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://southpark.cc.com|title=South Park \u2013 Watch Full Episodes, Clips & More|work=cc.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927005623/http://southpark.cc.com/|archive-date=2017-09-27|url-status=live}}</ref> Previously, the show had been available on the television website [[Netflix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knowyourmobile.com/apps/20082/netflix-removes-south-park-and-other-titles-its-library|title=Netflix removes South Park and other titles from its library|work=Know Your Mobile|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212032206/http://www.knowyourmobile.com/apps/20082/netflix-removes-south-park-and-other-titles-its-library|archive-date=2017-12-12|url-status=live}}</ref> The new site launch caused some technical issues, which were resolved allowing fans to watch uncensored<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxim.com/gadgets/all-uncensored-south-park-episodes-available-legally-free-online |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019085802/http://www.maxim.com/gadgets/all-uncensored-south-park-episodes-available-legally-free-online |archivedate=2014-10-19 }}</ref> episodes and clips. For viewers outside the US, episodes and clips still stream through the \"classic\" South Park player and nothing changed aside from the new site design. A handful of countries also have their own localized versions of South Park sites, with the old experience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://southpark.cc.com/blog/2014/07/28/south-park-new-site-faqs|title=South Park \u2013 New Site FAQs|work=cc.com|access-date=2017-12-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171212031653/http://southpark.cc.com/blog/2014/07/28/south-park-new-site-faqs|archive-date=2017-12-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced that beginning in September 2014, following the premiere of the 18th season, only 30 select episodes will be featured for free viewing at a time on the website, with new episodes being available for an entire month starting the day following their original airings. Almost every episode will be available for viewing on the Hulu subscription service, except for \"[[Super Best Friends]]\", \"[[200 (South Park)|200]]\", and \"[[201 (South Park)|201]]\", until June 2020, when the show will exit the service due to the acquisition of streaming rights by [[HBO Max]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/tv/news/1107582-hbo-max-streaming-rights-rick-and-morty-and-south-park|title=South Park & Rick and Morty Streaming Rights Go to HBO Max|date=2019-10-30|website=ComingSoon.net|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Neon Alley ===\n[[Neon Alley]] is a [[Viz Media]]-owned anime-oriented streaming service that launched on October 2, 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2012-10-02/viz-debuts-neon-alley|title=Viz Debuts Neon Alley|accessdate=8 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628222130/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2012-10-02/viz-debuts-neon-alley|archive-date=28 June 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> streaming to both the US and Canadian markets. At the start of April 2014, the service discontinued its original livestream format and relaunched as a video-on-demand ([[Video on demand|FVOD]]) platform accessible on either its website or [[Internet]]-connected devices through Hulu. Since Hulu wasn't available in the Canadian market, Neon Alley subsequently restricted its service to the United States. On July 21, 2016, [[Tubi TV]] announced that they had commenced streaming of certain Viz titles in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tubitv.com/blog/2016/07/21/stream-naruto-sailor-moon-viz-media-partners-tubi-tv-deliver-free-anime/|title=Stream Naruto, Sailor Moon & More: VIZ Media Partners with Tubi TV to Deliver Free Anime|publisher=Tubi TV|date=July 21, 2016|accessdate=October 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024131340/http://tubitv.com/blog/2016/07/21/stream-naruto-sailor-moon-viz-media-partners-tubi-tv-deliver-free-anime/|archive-date=October 24, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHulu is known for streaming anime titles from many distributors, including [[Funimation]], [[TMS Entertainment]], and [[Bandai Visual]], in addition to Viz Media.\n\n=== International platforms ===\n* [[Viki (website)|Viki]] (Asian programs)\n\n== Awards ==\n\nHulu's original series [[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|''The Handmaid's Tale'']], won two awards at the [[33rd TCA Awards|33rd annual Television Critics Association Awards]] for [[TCA Award for Program of the Year|Program of the Year]] and [[TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Drama|Outstanding Achievement in Drama]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/tca-awards-winners-carrie-coon-the-handmaids-tale-this-is-us-atlanta-1202516771/|title=TCA Award Winners: 'The Handmaid's Tale,' 'This Is Us,' 'Atlanta,' Carrie Coon Take Top Honors|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|date=5 Aug 2017|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004030647/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/tca-awards-winners-carrie-coon-the-handmaids-tale-this-is-us-atlanta-1202516771/|archive-date=4 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/handmaids-tale-wins-top-honor-at-2017-tca-awards-1027101/item/outstanding-achievement-drama-1027110|title='Handmaid's Tale' Wins Top Honor at 2017 TCA Awards|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=5 Aug 2017|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911075757/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/handmaids-tale-wins-top-honor-at-2017-tca-awards-1027101/item/outstanding-achievement-drama-1027110|archive-date=11 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[69th Primetime Emmy Awards|69th]] [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, Hulu earned a total of 8 awards for ''The Handmaid's Tale'' and became the first streaming service to win [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/the-handmaids-tale-wins-emmy-best-drama-series-hulu-streaming-service-1202171581/|title=Hulu's 'The Handmaid's Tale' Win Marks First Best Series Emmy For A Streaming Service|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002002658/http://deadline.com/2017/09/the-handmaids-tale-wins-emmy-best-drama-series-hulu-streaming-service-1202171581/|archive-date=2 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/18/media/hulu-emmy-win/index.html|title=And the top award goes to ... Hulu?|last=Stelter|first=Brian|date=18 Sep 2017|website=[[CNN]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005120828/http://money.cnn.com/2017/09/18/media/hulu-emmy-win/index.html|archive-date=5 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''The Handmaid's Tale'' also received Emmys for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Directing]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Drama Series|Outstanding Writing]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Cinematography for a Single-Camera Series|Outstanding Cinematography]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Production Design for a Narrative Contemporary or Fantasy Program (One Hour or More)|Outstanding Production Design]]. [[Elisabeth Moss]] won the Emmy for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress]], and [[Ann Dowd]] received the award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/17/arts/television/emmy-winners-list.html|title=Emmys 2017 Winners List|last=Chow|first=Andrew R.|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106073636/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/17/arts/television/emmy-winners-list.html|archive-date=6 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-nominees-winners-list-2017-story.html|title=The complete list of 2017 Emmy winners and nominees|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714020129/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-nominees-winners-list-2017-story.html|archive-date=14 July 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the 75th Golden Globe Awards ''The Handmaid's Tale'' took home two awards, Best TV Drama and Best Actress in a Drama TV Series<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2018/all|title=Winners & Nominees 2018|website=www.goldenglobes.com|access-date=2018-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114092934/https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/2018/all|archive-date=2018-01-14|url-status=live}}</ref> (Elisabeth Moss).\n\nAt the [[22nd Critics' Choice Awards|2016 Critics' Choice Documentary Awards]], Hulu's first-released documentary, [[The Beatles: Eight Days a Week|''The Beatles: Eight Days A Week \u2013 The Touring Years'']] won the award for Best Music Documentary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/|title=CRITICS' CHOICE DOCUMENTARY AWARDS FEATURED ON CBS SUNDAY MORNING, OCT 29|date=9 Oct 2017|website=[[Critics' Choice Movie Award|Critic's Choice]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://archive.today/20171112085340/http://www.criticschoice.com/documentary-awards/|archive-date=12 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/critics-choice-documentary-awards-o-j-made-in-america-13th-1201848408/|title=Critics' Choice Documentary Awards: 'O.J.: Made In America' & '13th' Dominate|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106124126/http://deadline.com/2016/11/critics-choice-documentary-awards-o-j-made-in-america-13th-1201848408/|archive-date=6 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all|date=2016-11-04}}</ref> The documentary also received [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Film]] at the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|2017 Grammy Awards]] and Best Documentary at the 16th Annual Movies for Grownups Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html|title=Grammys 2017: Complete list of winners and nominees|date=12 Feb 2017|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206205501/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-grammys-2017-nominations-winners-list-20161205-story.html|archive-date=6 December 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/7603856/beatles-eight-days-a-week-producer-nigel-sinclair-grammys-2017-nomination|title='The Beatles: Eight Days a Week' Producer Nigel Sinclair 'Honored' by Best Music Film Grammy Nomination|date=6 Dec 2016|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104051948/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/7603856/beatles-eight-days-a-week-producer-nigel-sinclair-grammys-2017-nomination|archive-date=4 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[Creative Arts Emmy Award|Creative Arts Emmys]], the documentary earned two Emmys including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Sound Editing for Nonfiction Programming (Single or Multi-Camera)|Outstanding Sound Editing]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Sound Mixing for a Nonfiction Program (Single or Multi-Camera)|Outstanding Sound Mixing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/emmys-2017-hulu-handmaids-tale-1202557512/|title=Hulu Carried to Emmys Glory by Eight Wins for 'Handmaid's Tale'|last=Otterson|first=Joe|date=17 Sep 2017|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003004312/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/emmys-2017-hulu-handmaids-tale-1202557512/|archive-date=3 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/09/09/creative-arts-emmy-awards-2017-winners-list/|title=2017 Creative Arts Emmy winners include Carpool Karaoke, RuPaul's Drag Race, SNL|last=Romano|first=Nick|date=9 Sep 2017|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014151028/http://ew.com/tv/2017/09/09/creative-arts-emmy-awards-2017-winners-list/|archive-date=14 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[68th Primetime Emmy Awards]], Hulu received its first Emmy Award nominations for its Original series, ''[[11.22.63]]'' and for [[Triumph the Insult Comic Dog|''Triumph's Election Special 2016'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2016/outstanding-special-visual-effects-in-a-supporting-role|title=68th Emmy Awards Nominees and Winners|website=[[Emmys]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001235315/http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/2016/outstanding-special-visual-effects-in-a-supporting-role|archive-date=1 October 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-2016-nominees-winners-list-20160714-snap-story.html|title=Complete list of 2016 Emmy nominations and winners|last=Lewis|first=Dave|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714190232/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-emmys-2016-nominees-winners-list-20160714-snap-story.html|archive-date=14 July 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2016, Hulu received its first [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nomination for its Original series, [[Casual (TV series)|''Casual'']], for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|TV series, Comedy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/golden-globes-hulus-first-nomination-for-casual-2015-12|title=Hulu just got its first Golden Globes nomination and it's a huge blow to the major networks|last=Nededog|first=Jethro|date=10 Dec 2015|website=[[Business Insider]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106064620/http://www.businessinsider.com/golden-globes-hulus-first-nomination-for-casual-2015-12|archive-date=6 January 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/golden-globes-hulu-casual-mike-hopkins-1201658366/|title=Golden Globes: 'Casual' Comedy Series Nom Marks Hulu's Awards Arrival|last=Birnbaum|first=Debra|date=10 Dec 2015|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=4 Oct 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925205945/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/golden-globes-hulu-casual-mike-hopkins-1201658366/|archive-date=25 September 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== International availability ==\nIn July 2010, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' revealed that Hulu had been working on plans for an international launch of Hulu Plus for several months, and had identified the UK and Japan as markets where its free website and subscription model could feasibly work.<ref>Garrahan, Matthew. [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f01d42b0-8ade-11df-bead-00144feab49a.html Hulu eyes launching global pay platform] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924150838/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/f01d42b0-8ade-11df-bead-00144feab49a.html |date=2015-09-24 }}, ''Financial Times'', July 8, 2010. Retrieved July 11, 2010.</ref> Hulu chief executive Jason Kilar expressed his belief that the US model could be replicated elsewhere, saying \"We won't be satisfied until this is a global service.\"<ref>Laughlin, Andrew. [http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/digitaltv/news/a240992/hulu-puts-uk-launch-back-on-agenda.html Hulu 'puts UK launch back on agenda'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110921051701/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/digitaltv/news/a240992/hulu-puts-uk-launch-back-on-agenda.html |date=2011-09-21 }}, ''Digital Spy'', July 9, 2010. Retrieved July 11, 2010.</ref> Hulu's first expansion into an international market took place with the launch of a service in Japan on September 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hulu officially launches streaming service in Japan |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/hulu-officially-launches-streaming-service-in-japan/ |website=CNET |accessdate=18 July 2018 |date=1 September 2011}}</ref> On February 27, 2014, [[Nippon TV]] announced that it would acquire Hulu's Japanese business. The service would maintain the Hulu name under license, and Hulu would continue to provide its infrastructure and support to the service as a regional licensee. Nippon TV also planned to produce its own original content for the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/global/hulu-japan-to-be-acquired-by-nippon-tv-1201122915/|title=Hulu Japan to Be Acquired by Nippon TV|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2014-02-28|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nAs rights to its content are already held by other broadcasters, U.S.-based video on demand services are not usually available in Canada. Hulu also cited a small advertising market in Canada as reasoning.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mudhar|first1=Raju|title=Why these five well-known online services snub Canada|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/01/04/why-are-these-five-well-known-online-services-snubbing-canada.html|website=Toronto Star|accessdate=1 November 2016|date=4 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103235733/https://www.thestar.com/business/2016/01/04/why-are-these-five-well-known-online-services-snubbing-canada.html|archive-date=3 November 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Rights to Hulu's original series have often been picked up by domestic broadcasters; for example, ''[[The Mindy Project]]'' was retained by its previous broadcast home, [[Citytv]], after its move to Hulu,<ref>{{cite web|title=Mindy Project staying on City despite being dropped by Fox|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/05/25/mindy-project-staying-on-city-despite-being-dropped-by-fox.html|website=Toronto Star|accessdate=27 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928204054/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2015/05/25/mindy-project-staying-on-city-despite-being-dropped-by-fox.html|archive-date=28 September 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Handmaid's Tale (TV series)|The Handmaid's Tale]]'' was acquired by [[Bell Media]] cable network [[Bravo (Canada)|Bravo]] (unrelated to the NBC-owned channel) and its streaming service [[Crave (streaming service)|Crave]],<ref name=\"torstar-hmtbravo\">{{cite news|title=The Handmaid's Tale finally gets Canadian distributor|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/2017/03/27/the-handmaids-tale-finally-gets-canadian-distributor.html|work=Toronto Star|first=Debra|last=Yeo|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref> and ''[[The Path (TV series)|The Path]]'' by [[Showcase (Canadian TV channel)|Showcase]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/2511881/aaron-paul-tv-show-the-path-coming-to-showcase-this-spring/|title=Aaron Paul TV show 'The Path' coming to Showcase this spring|date=2016-02-11|work=Global News|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nThe lack of international operations had been considered a potential shortcoming of Hulu in comparison to competitors, such as [[Prime Video]] and [[Netflix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/television/hulu-could-go-international-to-compete-with-netflix-1314601|title=Hulu could go international to compete with Netflix|last=James|first=Dave|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref> During an earnings call on November 8, 2018, Disney CEO Bob Iger stated that after its purchase of 21st Century Fox, it planned to make stronger investments into Hulu, including wider international expansion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/11/9/18079218/disney-hulu-original-series-international-bob-iger-fox|title=Disney plans heavy investment in Hulu, wants more original series|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=2018-11-09|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Iger announced that the international expansion of Hulu will start likely by 2021.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perez |first1=Sarah |title=Disney aims to launch Hulu internationally in 2021 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2020/02/05/disney-aims-to-launch-hulu-internationally-in-2021/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |accessdate=5 February 2020 |date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Netflix]]\n* [[CBS All Access]]\n* [[Disney+]]\n* [[HBO Max]]\n* [[Hotstar]]\n* [[Locast]]\n* [[Peacock (streaming service)]]\n* [[Seeso]], a defunct service launched by NBCUniversal in 2016 focusing on comedy\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Hulu}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Disney}}\n{{Comcast}}\n{{VOD services}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Hulu| ]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2007]]\n[[Category:NBCUniversal]]\n[[Category:The Walt Disney Company subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:Subscription video on demand services]]\n[[Category:2007 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Internet television streaming services]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 software]]\n", "name_user": "Bbbzzziii", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hulu"}
